report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 49-year-old male with a history of seizures since his late 20's.  Head injury at age 13 with coma and concussion.  The patient has 2-3 nocturnal seizures a week.

MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Depakote.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the alpha rhythm is 8.5 Hz, 30-40 uV. There is a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. There is a scant amount of theta activity in wakefulness.
Drowsiness is characterized by bitemporal wicket and slow rolling eye movement.  . Hyperventilation  produces  occasional bursts of  right temporal beta.   Photic stimulation  elicits
symmetric driving response.

HR: 72BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right temporal focal slowing in hyperventilation


CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen. A structural or functional abnormality on the right can be considered. To further identify epileptiform activity, a repeat record with sleep is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Right temporal focal slowing in hyperventilation

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old male with post-traumatic epilepsy with increasing improvement in seizure control.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  There is no mention of a previous craniotomy defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with some temporal wicket.  In stage I sleep, vertex waves and POSTS are seen.
Subtle abnormalities are seen in hyperventilation with an increase in amplitude, particularly from the left temporal region and occasion focal slowing seen in the temporal regions, left greater than right.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Subtle focal features from the left temporal region in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports an underlying structural or functional process on the left.  No epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Subtle focal features from the left temporal region in hyperventilation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old male with epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol, Dilantin, and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous, symmetric, and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy, which is evidenced by increased beta activity as well as theta activity.  A few vertex waves are also seen. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG in the lab capturing deeper stages of sleep or sleep deprivation prior to the EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
HISTORY: 52 year old male  with epilepsy  since late 20's following  head  trauma  at age 13. Recent cluster of four seizures in the emergency room.
MEDICATION: Clonazepam, Depakote, Phenytoin, ACTIVATION: Hyper ventilation, Photic Stimulation.
INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: In wakefulness,  there  is  a  10  Hz,  40  uV  posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral  beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized  by slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm with prominent temporal wicket.  This is a bit higher amplitude on the left and there is a very subtle underlying  slow wave underlying some of the wicket from the left.  This same pattern can be seen in hyperventilation as well as in early drowsiness. On one or two occasions, there is a slight asymmetry with a bit more beta in the left frontal  region when compared to the right.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.   Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:   72 BPM
IMPRESSION: Subtly abnormal EEG due to:
1.         An underlying area of focal slowing from the left temporal region underlying  the wicket.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the fourth EEG for this patient.  None of the EEG's have ever identified epileptiform activity on the left.   The last two EEG's were normal.   A previous EEG showed some subtle  right temporal  features in drowsiness.   Additional  EEG recording or capturing one of his spells may be helpful in terms of localization.   The wicket activity described above ma y mask subtle epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Subtly abnormal EEG due to 1.         An underlying area of focal slowing from the left temporal region underlying  the wicket.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old male with tonic-clonic epilepsy since age 20.  History of head trauma at age 13.  Occasionally non-severe tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Depakote, and Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is some subtle slowing with primarily theta frequency activity picked up in the posterior regions, slightly more so on the left than the right.   Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a bit more irregularity in the right hemisphere compared to the left.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmicity of the background, and the subtle focal features previously described are not quite as prominent.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving bilaterally, somewhat more intense on the right.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
1.	Subtle irregular slowing in the posteriotemporal regions, right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  There is a slightly more vigorous driving response in the right compared to the left at faster frequencies, raising the possibility of a breach rhythm, although none is reported with examination of the scalp.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Subtle irregular slowing in the posteriotemporal regions, right greater than left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with seizures since childhood, seizure-free for years and then recurrent seizures for the last two years.  Convulsions yesterday.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  There are spontaneous arousals from drowsiness and then she drifts off to a drowsy pattern with slow rolling eye movements and a beta background.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces some head rocking artifact.  The head rocking artifact is most prominent in the posterior temporal region.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These results are the same as previous EEGs.  In this individual with longstanding, refractory epilepsy consideration for long-term video EEG monitoring is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
HISTORY:

59 y.o. female with a history of childhood

epilepsy, colon cancer, obesity, and DVT presenting with


repetitive seizures and prolonged somnolence in the ED referred

for routine EEG for management of seizure exacerbation and

assessment of mental status change.




MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Dilantin




SEDATION: None listed



TECHNIQUE:


A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and


included a single channel of EKG.






EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well

organized symmetric mixture of alpha and beta frequencies, with a


symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR).



There are occasional disorganized bursts of sharply contoured

diffuse theta and delta frequencies.




The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and


amplitude is present.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse


background slowing are seen.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and

K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




Mild generalized slowing is present.

There is abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic


slowing.

There is abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal

polymorphic slowing.




EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

1. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by


sleep

2. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3

max), activated by sleep

3. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None




ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation


are not performed.




EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.




HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 84 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.




IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:

1. Mild generalized slowing


2. Abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic slowing

3. Abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal


polymorphic slowing

4. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by

sleep

5. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3


max), activated by sleep

6. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2








CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These findings indicate the presence of multifocal epileptiform


discharges (left temporal and left fronto-temporal > right

temporal), superimposed on bitemporal dysfunction and mild

diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

There were no electrographic seizures captured during this study.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 
1. Mild generalized slowing


2. Abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic slowing

3. Abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal


polymorphic slowing

4. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by

sleep

5. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3


max), activated by sleep

6. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:  18-year-old female with new onset generalized  tonic-clonic seizure in January 2005.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and folic acid.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation  were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized  with  a  10 Hz  posterior  dominant  rhythm and  a  small  amount  of  low  voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Early on in the record, there are several spike wave complexes seen maximum   at   01   but  also  P3.     These  discharges  are  accentuated   by  hyperventilation. Occasionally, the discharges are preceded by rhythmic theta in the left parieto-occipital region. Photic stimulation also accentuates the discharges.   In the course of the recording, the patient achieves stage I and stage II sleep evidenced by POSTS, vertex waves, and a few spindles.· Photic stimulation elicits a symmetric driving response.
HR:  78BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Focal spike waves at the left parieto-occipital region, which is preceded by rhythmic slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a focal or localization-related mechanism for this patient 's epilepsy.  The preceding theta and focal slowing  at the left parieto-occipital region indicates a structural abnormality. Correlation with neuroimaging data is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Focal spike waves at the left parieto-occipital region, which is preceded by rhythmic slowing.

report:
History:	28 YR OLD FEMALE WITH STATUS ELECTROGRAPHIC SEIZURES.
Medications:	ATIVAN 2MG IV PUSH, LAMICTAL, KEPPRA
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes
Description:
Waking background is characterized by at best a 7HZ alpha rhythm.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz
activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows
to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  As drowsiness progresses, symmetric vertex waves appear.
Continuous rhythmic delta activity is present in the left midtemporal region during wakefulness,
increasing during drowsiness.  Frequent focal spikes are present with phase reversal and amplitude
maximum at C3/P3. At times in 1Hz bursts for seconds.  Multiple O2 electrographic seizures
occurring for ~3 minutes. The appear to remain posteriorly with minimal spread. There is no
clinical correlate. They begin with spiky theta discharged minimally spreads centrally.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.  HR
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, frequent, right posterior
Spikes, frequent, left central
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, continuous
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep

report:
HISTORY: 87 yr old female found on the floor by her daughter.  Phone was busy since the night before. In the ER, she had a generalized tonic clonic seizure.

MEDICATION: Dilantin and Heparin.

ACTIVATION: Photic Stimulation and Hyperventilation.

INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: The background EEG is  unusual.   There  is an alpha rhythm  of  8.5  - 9.5  Hz.    The  alpha  rhythm  is  intermittently  disruptive  on  the  right  and intermittent right occipital temporal delta is seen.   In addition, there is a vertex wave seen at CZ/FZ/C4.  There is clearly delineated in stage II sleep but also can be picked up in wakefulness. Features of stage II sleep include a symmetric vertex wave, normal appearing vertex waves and abundant spindles.  Various montages were employed in an attempt to localize the epileptiform activity.

HR.: 96BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Right occipital delta
2. 	Spike and slow wave activity which is very close to midline but seems to phase reverse to
the right of the midline

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the right.  Consideration for a localization related mechanism for epilepsy is appropriate.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Right occipital delta
2. Spike and slow wave activity which is very close to midline but seems to phase reverse to
the right of the midline

report:

MEDICATIONS: Depakote and aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation  was performed.   This is an
awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION  OF  THE   RECORD: In wakefulness, the  background  EEG  is  slow  and disorganized.  The alpha rhythm is 6 to 7 Hz.  There is occasional delta on the background, right greater than left.  The patient transitions into stage II sleep with vertex waves and persistent eye movements.  Auditory stimulation in sleep produced an attenuation response.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.

1.   Background slowing and disorganization.
2.   Occasional focal slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to a study done seven months ago, this EEG demonstrates significant background slowing and disorganization.   In contrast to her EEG one year ago, no epileptiform activity was seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Background slowing and disorganization. 2.   Occasional focal slowing on the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with focal sclerosis glomerulonephritis and childhood epilepsy.  Patient seizure-free for five years.  The patient is now experiencing staring spells at work.  Previous history of tonic-clonic seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Norvasc.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  The major abnormalities occur around the time of photic stimulation.  The tech starts to awaken the patient for photic.  A brief burst lasting just under one second is seen with high amplitude, sharply contoured activity without a really well-defined spike and slow wave complex, but with notched frontal activity.  Reviewing the burst with different montages, it seems to phase reverse slightly to the left.

1 seizure occurred in the EEG lab at 13:51.  This follows photic stimulation, but does not occur during photic stimulation.  The patient is resting quietly with her eyes closed.  As the seizure begins at 13:51:57, no clinical signs or symptoms are noted.  The technologist notes the change in behavior.  The patientÕs eyes open at 13:52:10.  The technologist asks the patient questions at 13:52:16.  The patient opens her eyes and swallows.  When asked where she is she replies that she is in the neurologistÕs office.  She remains somewhat confused in the minutes that follow.  The tech calls the patient at 13:52:39.   At 13:52:46, she sits, staring blankly, and then she starts to rub her eyes in her head.  The tech asks if she is okay.  At this point, when the tech is asking the patient questions, the seizure has ended and the patient is confused.

EEG characteristics of this seizure include the appearance of rhythmic theta frequency activity, which is more remarkable in the posterior regions.  This seizure seems to start with some low voltage fast activity and then some rhythmic theta, more remarkable in the posterior regions and perhaps maximum in the right posterior region.  Reviewing this seizure with a circle montage, seems to confirm a phase reversal in the right occipitotemporal region but also involving the right central region, nearly isoelectric Cz to C4.  The activity shows frequency evolution and seems to occur in two phases with secondary build-up at 13:52:19 with fast activity and more of a generalized appearance.  The activity ends at 13:52:51 as the patient starts to rub her head with postictal slowing.

HR:  96 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex partial seizure, which was difficult to localize and which may have had some generalized features at the start, but with some evidence of focality in the same seizure.
2. An unusual paroxysmal burst frontal in nature.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of an underlying seizure disorder.  There may be more than one contributing factor for this patientÕs seizures.  This EEG did not provide adequate localization for the seizures that this individual experienced.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Complex partial seizure, which was difficult to localize and which may have had some generalized features at the start, but with some evidence of focality in the same seizure. 2. An unusual paroxysmal burst frontal in nature.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with a childhood seizure disorder with recurrent seizures in recent months (last seizure one to two weeks ago with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion).
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Previous EEGs are not available for comparison.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Of note, there is a single four second burst in photic stimulation where the patient seems to have had eye flutter, but looking at the eyes there is no discernable eye movement, and the activity is in the frontal regions with a somewhat different field of spread in the eye monitor in comparison to the patient’s other eye movements.  This burst is highly suspicious for frontally predominant notched delta as might be seen in generalized spike and slow wave activity.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is abnormal due to:
1.	A single, suspicious, approximately 2 to 3 second burst of notched frontal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  The activity described above can be seen in a primary or secondary generalized process.  Rather than repeating additional studies, correlation with previous studies may be the most effective way to place these findings in their appropriate clinical context.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is abnormal due to 1.A single, suspicious, approximately 2 to 3 second burst of notched frontal delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with childhood epilepsy with recurrent seizures – last occurring in May 2006 with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. This patient’s previous EEGs were available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is a scant amount of background theta, compatible with age.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing a small amount of slowing. There is a single burst of notched slowing in the occipital regions, right greater than left, seen at the end of hyperventilation.  As the patient becomes drowsy, additional, sharply contoured irregular slowing is seen.  The burst identified is generalized, but there may be an underlying right temporal sharp wave associated with that burst.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very subtly abnormal EEG due to:
Two somewhat unusual bursts seen in the background with some localization to the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s two previous EEGs, there is much less in the way of epileptiform activity, and the overall background is more consistently normal.  The epileptiform activity in this record was not well defined - really only suspicious underlying sharply contoured activity with the paroxysmal bursts.  These findings suggest an improvement compared to the first study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very subtly abnormal EEG due to Two somewhat unusual bursts seen in the background with some localization to the right hemisphere.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Morphine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is wearing a hard collar.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient is drowsy throughout much of the EEG with rhythmic background slowing. Brief stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old  woman with seizures  with VNS implantation  in
2003 now with change in seizure type. MEDICATIONS: Topamax and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital  video EEG is performed in the lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement  with one channel  of EKG. Hyperventilation  and  photic  stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.



DESCRIPTION OF  THE   RECORD: In  wakefulness,  the  background  EEG  is  symmetric,


continuous, and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant  alpha rhythm,  which  is  attenuated  with  eyes  opened.    There  is  a  small  amount  of  low  voltage, frontocentral  beta  activity.   As the tracing continues,  alternative  sharp  waves  in  the posterior region, as well as 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity were seen in drowsiness.  The 3 Hz activities repeatedly occurred  in drowsiness, lasting from 1 to 3.5 seconds without change in behavior. This activity seemed to emanate from the left central and temporal regions.   No clinical behavior was observed  on  the  video  can1era. Drowsiness  is  characterized  by  a  mixed frequency  of  brain activity,  but deeper stages of sleep  were not achieved.   Hyperventilation  mildly  increased  the slow theta activity on the background.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.

ID:  60BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  alternative sharp activity in the posterior region.
2.   3 Hz spike and slow wave activity seen in drowsiness, repeatedly originating  from the left central and temporal areas- C3 and T3 areas.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This abnormal EEG reflects an underlying pathologic process of the brain and provides a partial mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  The occurrence of 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity is a likely epileptogenic in origin and  bears clinical  significance. However,  the electric  artifact from  the VNS device should be excluded.    A repeat EEG  with careful attention to the VNS device is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.  alternative sharp activity in the posterior region. 2.   3 Hz spike and slow wave activity seen in drowsiness, repeatedly originating  from the left central and temporal areas- C3 and T3 areas.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old woman with a long history of refractory epilepsy and seizures in June and July of 2006, both of which seem to have been provoked.  No seizures since July.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Phenytoin, VNS.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in theta.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
There is a single abnormality identified in this record in the transition just as the patient is drifting off to sleep and it does seem to elicit an arousal.  This is a frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex with a poly spike and slow wave component reaching amplitudes up to 200 uV.  It is symmetric and frontally predominant.  The whole entire entity includes a burst of approximately one second without clear correlate, but with an alerting.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	An isolated, frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous studies, this EEG demonstrated a relative paucity of epileptiform activity.  This may be due to the little sleep that was recorded in this record.  Of note, this patient has a history of prominent spike and slow wave activity in sleep.  The observation of an arousal in association with epileptiform activity may be part of this patient’s underlying sleep disturbance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.An isolated, frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old female with epilepsy since 1994, but seizure-free since 1999.  Past EEG showed generalized spike and slow wave activity.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by prominent rhythmic diffuse theta activity particularly in the occipital regions.  Hyperventilation is performed out of drowsiness and seems to accentuate this activity as well.  There are rare bursts of higher amplitude more sharply contoured frontal theta at the close of hyperventilation and there is a single, discrete left anterior temporal sharp wave in the transition from hyperventilation to sleep.  As the patient reaches stage I sleep, there are slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of the alpha rhythm, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively asleep with features of stage II sleep identified during photic stimulation.  While there is a low voltage, symmetric brief driving response following photic stimulation as the patient drifts off to sleep, there are two bursts of symmetric, low voltage TFA.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG to due to:
Brief bursts of generalized paroxysmal fast activity identified following photic stimulation in a state of relative drowsiness.
A single left anterior temporal sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is the third EEG for this patient.  The GPFA is similar to abnormalities identified on the October 5, 2000 EEG.  The 1994 EEG was normal, and the 2002 EEG identified some left 5 Hz activity from the occipital scalp region.  The major relevant difference between the two EEGs is the presence of a discrete, left frontal sharp wave.  This has been reported in the literature as part of the maturational process of a primary generalized epilepsy, but it could also be seen in the setting of a partial or focal epilepsy as well.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG to due to Brief bursts of generalized paroxysmal fast activity identified following photic stimulation in a state of relative drowsiness. A single left anterior temporal sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman with primary generalized epilepsy, history of myoclonic and absence seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is 8Hz posterior dominant rhythm.
In hyperventilation and in drowsiness,  however, there is more rhythmic 5Hz background theta with almost a rhythmic 5Hz posterior dominant rhythm.
There are intermittent bursts of frontally predominant generalized spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity. These occur in hyperventilation and are of 3-5 seconds duration. They are seen post hyperventilation in bursts lasting approximately 3 seconds in duration. The last burst is seen at 120 seconds post hyperventilation as the patient transitions into sleep.  Additional bursts are seen in the transition to stage I sleep.  They do not clearly produce an arousal response, although the first burst is seen in the first transition to sleep.  Other features of stage II  sleep include spindles and posts.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.   On 1 occasion the spike and wave activity also seems to be associated with the photic stimulation.
Heart rate: 70 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of 3-5Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity.
2.	Spike and wave activity seen in hyperventilation and 1 time photic stimulation.
3.	Rhythmic theta activity, greater than one might expect in wakefulness and early drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The primary epileptiform abnormality in this record is generalized spike and wave activity as was previously identified.  There are a number of other normal variants or mild abnormalities, including the prominent 5 Hz activity identified. There is also some psychomotor variant, which in this case is likely a normal variant.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Bursts of 3-5Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity. 2.Spike and wave activity seen in hyperventilation and 1 time photic stimulation. 3.Rhythmic theta activity, greater than one might expect in wakefulness and early drowsiness.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In both hyperventilation and in drowsiness, there is an increase in shifting, right or left temporal theta, as well as some sharply contoured theta frequency activity which reaches higher amplitudes up to 70 V from the right mid-to-anterior temporal region.   Stage II sleep is characterized by symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving, as well as LAMBDA waves.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	The appearance of shifting, right greater than left temporal theta in drowsiness and hyperventilation with higher amplitude, more sharply contoured theta activity from the right identified on one occasion from the temporal regions and on one occasion from the parietal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above are non-specific.  They support a process involving the temporal regions and the right hemisphere more strongly than the left.  While there are no definite epileptiform discharges, the sharply contoured higher amplitude theta from the right hemisphere is suggestive of such a process.  Correlation with imaging and previous EEGs may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.The appearance of shifting, right greater than left temporal theta in drowsiness and hyperventilation with higher amplitude, more sharply contoured theta activity from the right identified on one occasion from the temporal regions and on one occasion from the parietal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old, right-handed female in a motor vehicle accident in December 1996, meningitis 2000, fall down the stairs with recurrent falling and loss of consciousness.  Diagnosis of non-epileptic seizures made in the emergency room at Frankford. Multiple episodes of confusion and daily seizures versus pseudo-seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None at present.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient experiences a single episode of left leg shaking.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posterior slow waves of youth.  In the transition to drowsiness, on rare occasions, there is subtle, rhythmic theta activity identified from the left anterior temporal and frontal region.  On one occasion, this activity is also identified in hyperventilation.  Features of stage I sleep include high amplitude vertex waves.
Hyperventilation elicits a rare burst of slowing described above as well as bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude 3 Hz activity which is well formed, but without definite spike or slow wave activity underlying it.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
The patient had a single episode of right leg shaking.  This occurred after hyperventilation.  The EEG at this time identified a normal awake pattern.  The patient was able to answer questions throughout.  The activity lasted about 90 seconds and there was a bit of head bobbing associated with it.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The behavior recorded during this EEG did not have an EEG correlate.  The subtle focal slowing described above is of unclear clinical significance.  Correlation with history and imaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old, right-handed female with hypothyroidism and a question of seizures versus non-epileptic seizures. Her history is multiple episodes with bilateral shaking without loss of consciousness.  These have occurred during previous EEGs without an EEG correlate.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This was a fasting record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm reaching amplitudes up to 70  V with posterior slow waves of youth. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and elicits initially subtle, left temporal sharply contoured theta, which is somewhat irregular.  There appears to be a sharp wave varied in this frontotemporal theta.  The sharp wave can be identified on three different occasions.  Review of this activity with reformatting suggests a maximum at F7 but on other occasions in the left frontal region.  As hyperventilation continues, there are bursts of synchronous, high amplitude rhythmic frontally predominant delta.  Features of stage II sleep include high amplitude vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Left anterior temporal focal slowing with a suspicious underlying sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This second record again identifies left anterior temporal focal slowing.  The suspicious sharp wave merits additional evaluation to determine whether or not this patient is having behaviors which are seizures in addition to the behaviors which appear to have been confirmed not to be epileptiform.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Left anterior temporal focal slowing with a suspicious underlying sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 15, seizure-free for “awhile,” but with a seizure one year ago with loss of consciousness and generalized tonic-clonic activity, but no postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 12 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in faster frequency activity and then attenuation of the alpha with background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for LAMBDA activity, but also some driving at faster flash frequencies.  Hyperventilation produces a generous burst of high amplitude, frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz activity.  The patient reports feeling tingling in the mouth and hands during HV.  The data is re-reviewed with appropriate sensitivities and even with fewer channels per page to make sure that there is no underlying spike and wave activity, and none can be determined
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for an adult of this age in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The relatively fast alpha rhythm is not pathological.  There is a very vigorous, high amplitude response to hyperventilation, but there is no definite spike and wave activity.  In this individual with seizures a year ago, a repeat study with hyperventilation may be of value.  Alternatively, comparison with childhood EEGs may provide the same information.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for an adult of this age in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  please check, not listed
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The tech reports difficulty with impedance despite attempting to clean the scalp. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz, 30 to 40 V.  Early in drowsiness there is prominent slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and there are bursts of shifting, left or right temporal delta.  Temporal wicket is also identified. Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and snore artifact are identified in sleep.
Hyperventilation is attempted but the patient seems to be too drowsy to perform hyperventilation.
Photic stimulation does not activate the tracing.  The patient seems to drift off to sleep in photic simulation.
HR: 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
Excessive temporal slowing early in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The temporal features described above are non-specific but are most commonly described in supravascular disease in the elderly.  This is, however, outside the acceptable range for a subject of this age.  In this individual who is
hypersomnolent with a lot of snore artifact, consideration for an underlying sleep disorder might be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to Excessive temporal slowing early in drowsiness.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The patient rapidly drifts into deeper stages of sleep with relatively symmetric, theta frequency activity as well as vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles. INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.

DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized with primarily a theta frequency background and
a posterior dominant rhythm which is approximately7 Hz on the left, slower on the right. There is shifting arrhythmic delta
activity. There are also some bursts of sharply contoured slowing and sharp waves in the left mid temporal region.
Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

slowing are compatible with a bihemispheric disturbance. Renal failure, and/or cerebrovascular disease can also
contribute to this picture. Previous EEGs were not available for review.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Shifting slowing a nd diffuse sharply contoured slowing on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old male with a childhood seizure with a complex partial seizure versus syncope this past winter.
MEDICATIONS: Previously on Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 50 to 70 V posterior dominant rhythm, which is higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.  There is also a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
The major abnormality is some subtle, isolated focal slowing from the left temporal region with a mixture of primarily theta but a smaller amount of delta activity.  Other features in stage I and into stage II sleep are prominent POSTS, which are higher amplitude on the left, and at times there is an appearance of almost a very subtle posterior temporal focus of isolated 3 Hz activity.  In addition, there is a discrete sharp wave identified again in the left mid to anterior region, which is identified in drowsiness and into stage II sleep.  This is also elicited in apparent wakefulness around the time of photic in relaxed wakefulness.  It occurs over a background of relatively sharply contoured activity with the potential for a normal variant such as wicket, but there seems to be only this discharge from the left temporal region.  There is no other phase reversal on the contralateral side and there is a bit of focal slowing underlying this rhythmic, sharply contoured activity.  All discharges are relatively small and discrete, but again identified on one occasion in relaxed wakefulness and on rare occasions into stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation produces vigorous background delta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving. 	HR:  60 BPM
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle, left temporal focal slowing seen primarily in the anterior temporal region but on some occasions in the posterior temporal region with a small discrete sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This activity is outside of the range of possibilities for a normal variant and consideration for a partial mechanism for epilepsy is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle, left temporal focal slowing seen primarily in the anterior temporal region but on some occasions in the posterior temporal region with a small discrete sharp wave.

Low amplitude, rare, discrete sharp waves were noted in the right mid temporal region with on rare occasions an after going slow wave.
Tactile stimulation of the patient produced moaning and stiffening.
Heart rate 67 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a low voltage, slow pattern.
A suspicious, rare, low voltage, right temporal sharp waves in the context of a low voltage background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most supportive of the significant, diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting gray and white matter such as a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or pharmacologic effect.
The subtle temporal sharp waves raise the possibility of a localization-related mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with a low voltage, slow pattern. A suspicious, rare, low voltage, right temporal sharp waves in the context of a low voltage background.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a five-year-old female with febrile convulsions with a complex partial seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin and Valium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in Children’s Hospital using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake EEG in a child who becomes only briefly drowsy. Overall cooperation is fair.  The child’s mother was at the bedside, attempting to hold the child’s eyes closed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is medium to high amplitude.  The overall organization is slightly outside the range of normal for a child of this age, despite movement artifact.  Prominent frequencies in the background include theta frequency activity.  On one or two occasions, there seems to be LAMBDA activity from the occipital regions bilaterally.  There is a subtle asymmetry with some arrhythmic delta activity in the right posterior temporal region and a triangular shaped or triphasic shaped discharge from the right posterior temporal/occipital region.  On rare occasions, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of faster frequency approximately 6 to 7 Hz identified.  While this is symmetric on some occasions, on other occasions it seems to be better represented on the left compared to the right. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a decrease in movement. As the child makes the transition to drowsiness, initially the posterior dominant rhythm seems symmetric and then there seems to be a subtle delta from the right posterior quadrant.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Mild background slowing without some of the anticipated features of organization expected at this age.
Subtle focal slowing with an almost triphasic-like component in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Generalized background slowing is non-specific and may be related to either a postictal state, medications, or an underlying disorder of cerebral function.  Correlation with imaging may be helpful to further evaluate the changes in the right posterior temporal region.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Mild background slowing without some of the anticipated features of organization expected at this age. Subtle focal slowing with an almost triphasic-like component in the right posterior quadrant.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is a 7 Hz, 30 to 60 V dominant rhythm.  Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral right focal slowing is characterized by frontal theta and delta. As the patient becomes drowsy, there are more prominent bursts of frontal slowing and a breech on the right.  Although the EEG is abnormal, it is nearly symmetric and well organized at times. Hyperventilation produces right frontal delta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.  There is no EEG change at the time of twitching.

Intermittent bilateral as well as unilateral focal slowing characterized by frontal theta or delta.
Right frontal breech with increased beta and increased amplitude of the delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing suggests an underlying structural problem most likely affecting both frontal hemispheres. No sharp waves could be identified. A follow-up EEG during deeper stages of sleep may be useful in identifying focal epileptiform activity given the breech rhythm.

Background slowing and disorganization.
Occasional focal slowing on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old male with alcohol abuse, stroke, epilepsy, and temporal abnormalities admitted with alcohol-withdrawal seizure
MEDICATIONS: Klonopin, Topamax, Keppra, Serax,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. The patient had previously been experiencing severe benzodiazepine withdrawal on July 3. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is awake throughout much of the record.  The background EEG is rich in beta frequency activity and there is also excess background theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is some underlying rhythmic temporal slowing most prominently seen from the left with some spread into the frontocentral regions.  There is prominent lateral rectus eye artifact noted in the awake and drowsy record.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving at faster flash frequencies.  There is perhaps a single underlying right temporal sharp wave.
HR:  __ BPM.

Generalized background slowing.
A handful of subtle temporal abnormalities left and right, but no definite spikes or sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The features described above are similar to previous EEGs, some of which have demonstrated significant left temporal features, others which have not consistently identified left temporal abnormalities.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. A handful of subtle temporal abnormalities left and right, but no definite spikes or sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old, left-handed woman with epilepsy since childhood with increasing headaches, nausea, vomiting, and accelerating seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Heparin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the initial portions of the record, there is a marked intrahemispheric asymmetry.  From the left hemisphere, there is a 9.5 Hz, 35 V posterior dominant rhythm.  This is somewhat disrupted on the right, and the right hemisphere demonstrates disruption of faster frequency activity with arrhythmic delta activity particularly from the centrotemporal regions and T2 sharp and slow wave or spike and slow wave complexes. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and seems to accentuate this pattern. As the post-hyperventilation pattern resolves, the focal slowing becomes somewhat less prominent and the intrahemispheric asymmetry slightly less marked.  Later on, as the patient drifts into stage I and stage II sleep, there is again disruption of faster frequency activity particularly from the right frontal regions. Symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving bilaterally at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the right hemisphere characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity as well as focal delta and theta activity maximum in the temporal regions.
T2 spike and slow wave complexes, which are overall high amplitude.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This record was compared to this patient’s five previous EEGs.  Some have demonstrated epileptiform activity on the right or left temporal regions, as well as others with bitemporal activity.  The activity in this record is much more marked on the right.  Correlation with imaging may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing from the right hemisphere characterized by disruption of faster frequency activity as well as focal delta and theta activity maximum in the temporal regions. T2 spike and slow wave complexes, which are overall high amplitude.

a 41 y.o. male with a history of seizures (last in), referred for routine EEG

divalproex (DEPAKOTE) 500 mg EC tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily. Indications:
EPILEPSY

No current facility-administered medications for this visit.

TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory
record and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.

amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.

None

any EEG changes.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.

A heart rate of 78 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal awake only routine EEG, remarkable only for excess of beta frequencies.  There are

This is a normal awake only  routine EEG.

IMPRESSION

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 38-year-old female with epilepsy. No other details are known and no seizure history is known.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were attempted.  The patient spoke no English and had no caregiver to help translate. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record are well-organized with a 9.25 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the initial portions of the record, the patient is a bit drowsy and hyperventilation is attempted.  There are bursts seen in this portion of the record in the temporal regions.  There are irregular bursts, which appear in the left or right temporal regions, sometimes a bit more on one side than the other or starting on the left and going to right or vice versa.  With the use of the T1-T2 electrodes, the activity appears to be maximum at T1 and there is an underlying sharp wave at T1-T3.  This becomes more prominent in the later HV recording. In these bursts, there are also T2 sharp waves and a sharply contoured background.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there are additional sharp waves again seen at T1.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in the irregular temporal theta and the occasional sharp waves.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous.
Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  If further characterization of this patient’s epilepsy is needed, an additional recording capturing sleep or one of her seizures would be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Irregular temporal slowing with an unusual field of spread often involving both temporal regions but asynchronous. Left greater than right temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The somewhat unusual response in hyperventilation and seen with a paroxysmal, somewhat irregular burst in HV and on one occasion in drowsiness, is not epileptogenic in nature and is of unclear clinical significance.  The asymmetric wicket described above is a normal finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

Medications:	NONE
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
There is intermittent focal slowing noted over the left hemisphere, fronto-temporal region.  No
epileptiform discharges are present.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces a modest, symmetric photic
driving response.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy due to intermittent left frontotemporal focal
slowing. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically
indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.  Focal slowing
may indicate a structural brain lesion.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy due to intermittent left frontotemporal focal
slowing. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically
indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.  Focal slowing
may indicate a structural brain lesion

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old male with a history of epilepsy since birth, seizure-free until three years ago when he began to have symptoms.  The patient reports a warm feeling in his head then loss of sight, shaking and confusion, but no loss of consciousness.  He remains upright, but may have to grab onto something.  History of chronic pain syndromes, acid reflux, hepatitis C, depression, and other medical problems including C-spine disease.
MEDICATIONS: Prevacid, Zyprexa, Benztropine, and amitriptyline.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is mainly a drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the record.  There is a low voltage, 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage beta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in theta.  There is intermittent, irregular theta activity in the left temporal regions, left greater than right, with a subtle, sharply contoured slowing seen in the same region.  On rare occasions, there is some bitemporal slowing with some sharply contoured activity on the right. Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation produces a minimal bilateral driving response.  The patient was drowsy through photic.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort.  The temporal features are identified in hyperventilation, which is almost equivalent to a drowsy state for this individual.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
1.	Irregular, sharply contoured temporal theta, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No spike and slow wave or definitive sharp and slow wave discharges were seen in this record.  To further characterize this patient’s epilepsy, an additional recording may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Irregular, sharply contoured temporal theta, left greater than right.

HR: 90 bpm

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with epilepsy, seizure-free for nearly two years.  Previous EEGs demonstrated generalized epileptiform activity and generalized spike and slow wave activity in 1997.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The major abnormality in this record are bursts of frontally predominant, well formed, high amplitude 3.5 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  A typical burst duration is three seconds, but bursts can be seen that are longer, up to 5 seconds including some that have some theta.  In addition, there are rare, subtle frontal  spike and wave complexes, a handful of which are maximum in the right frontal region or the left and which appears as a couplet with first one in the left and the second in the right or vice versa.  The epileptiform activity is clearly accentuated in hyperventilation and in early drowsiness.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits a photoparoxysmal response with brief bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 4 to 6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.  None of the bursts last the duration of the stimulus and in one occasion the burst is seen following HV.  There is a single burst of 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity immediately following hyperventilation.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized, 3-6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  These results are similar to previous records.  The presence of occasional frontal isolated spikes can be seen in an inherited generalized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized, 3-6 Hz spike and slow wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 25-year-old, left-handed woman with a prolonged period of seizure-free status with previous generalized spike and slow wave epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record. No clinical seizures were recorded.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. The major abnormality in this record is a total of seven generalized spike and slow wave complexes, most of which are 5 Hz, but occasionally slightly slower or faster. Typical bursts are four seconds in duration, but there is a triplet of three bursts lasting a total of eight seconds. There is only a single, isolated frontal spike and slow wave complex, although there is a current burst. This generalized epileptiform activity occurs in wakefulness, seems to be elicited slightly in hyperventilation, perhaps elicited by photic stimulation, although it is clearly present in the background. Drowsiness may also be a precipitating factor. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR: 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Five to six hertz generalized spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is essentially identical to the previous 2003 study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Five to six hertz generalized spike and slow wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old woman with epilepsy starting in 1997, seizure-free since 2000.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is a11 awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm. Central MU is identified, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. On rare occasions, there is a small amount of rhythmic, mid-temporal theta of drowsiness. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a frontally predominant, high amplitude, 5 and 13 Hz photoparoxysmal response of short duration, lasting less than three seconds without clinical signs.
HR: 70BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike a11d wave activity of 3 to 6 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The photoparoxysmal response described above can be seen in inherited epilepsies. It was elicited at the 5 Hz stimuli at the onset of the flash stimulus. No clinical seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Frontally predominant spike a11d wave activity of 3 to 6 Hz.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 27-year-old left-handed woman with childhood epilepsy. The patient stopped topiramate earlier in 2007 and had a seizure in October 2007.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz symmetric reactive posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Weakness observed. The patient is drowsy throughout most of the record with background theta. Epileptiform is elicited in hyperventilation, drowsiness, and photic stimulation. The vast majority of this activity is rhythmic, frontally predominant, symmetric, a 2-7 Hz spike and wave activity. It is clearly accentuated by photic stimulation. On rare occasions an occipitally predominant 7 Hz spike and wave complexes are also observed. Duration of the spike and wave bursts are typically 2 seconds, but some are as long as 4 seconds. Photic stimulation also elicits driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized high amplitude spike and wave activity and poly spikes
2. Wave activity reaching 7 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing differs from previous in that in addition to frontally predominant spike and wave activity there was also on 1 occasion occipitally predominant spike and wave activity. Aside from this these studies are similar to this patient's many previous
studies dating to 2003. The activation with hyperventilation and photic stimulation suggests an inherited mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized high amplitude spike and wave activity and poly spikes
2. Wave activity reaching 7 Hz.

report:
HISTORY:

36 y.o. female with a history of JME referred for routine EEG for characterization of
seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

topiramate (TOPAMAX) 50 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth every morning.

topiramate (TOPAMAX) 100 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily for 360 days. Start 1 at
bedtime for 2 weeks, then 1 BID


folic acid (FOLVITE) 1 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.


gabapentin (NEURONTIN) 100 mg capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth 3 times daily.


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:






A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 8.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Synchronous and symmetric vertex waves are seen in sleep; stage II transients are not captured.



No generalized slowing is present.

No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

Frequent (>1/min to <1/10s) bursts of generalized, frontally predominant 5-Hz spike- and polyspike-
and-wave activity are seen in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Discrete bursts last up to 3 seconds but
occasionally occur <1 second apart, for a total duration of 5.5 seconds. In drowsiness spikes may
fragment, with equal predominance seen between the hemispheres.




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produced
a single 1-second burst of diffuse sharply contoured theta activity.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces scant
symmetric photic driving, particularly at 9 Hz, which is a normal finding. There is no increase in burst
duration/prevalence during photic stimulation as compared with the rest of the study. There is no
photoparoxysmal response.




EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:



A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:


1. Frequent bursts of generalized, frontally predominant 5-Hz spike- and polyspike-and-wave activity


CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These findings are similar to prior EEGs and are consistent with this patient's diagnosis of juvenile
myoclonic epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to 

1. Frequent bursts of generalized, frontally predominant 5-Hz spike- and polyspike-and-wave activity

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old woman with epilepsy since age six with tonic seizures.  The patient was seizure-free until age 40 and then seizures recurred. However, she has been seizure-free for the past two years.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11.3 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with amplitudes of 50 to 80 V.  There is a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is frequent eye blink artifact.  As the patient gradually becomes somewhat drowsy, there is an increase in background beta, but deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving; however, at 3 Hz to 7 Hz, the activity is slightly irregular on the left in comparison to the right.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In that the overall driving response is symmetric, the changes in the left anterior temporal region in photic stimulation is of unclear clinical significance.  Comparison with this patient’s previous EEGs may be of use regarding the slightly unusual field and response to photic stimulation at those two frequencies.  Alternatively, an additional recording with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful in terms of further evaluating the left anterior temporal region.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy, complex partial seizures sometimes with an aura of a funny nasal feeling.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In wakefulness, on rare occasions, there is a small amount of discrete beta activity from the right temporal region.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and again produces a small amount of discrete, rhythmic theta activity.  Some of this is identified in the posterior regions on the right and measures at 6 Hz.    As hyperventilation continues, there are one or two bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta activity from the temporal regions.  Following hyperventilation, there is some EKG artifact in the right temporal region.  Despite this, there is subtle, discrete right temporal slowing and a handful of tiny, discrete right temporal sharp waves, which can be differentiated from the patient’s EKG and are identified in quiet wakefulness.
Photic stimulation elicits brief driving.  At the close of the record, just following hyperventilation, intermittent bursts of background slowing with vertex waves and K complexes are identified followed by arousals, supportive of stage II sleep.
HR:  __ BPM. Check tech sheet
IMPRESSION: Subtle, but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Right temporal focal slowing and small discrete sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The epileptiform features in this record are less prominent than those seen a year ago. With the subtle focal slowing and the discrete sharp waves, a partial mechanism for epilepsy rather than a normal variant would be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Subtle, but abnormal EEG due to 1.Right temporal focal slowing and small discrete sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with epilepsy, admitted for recurrent seizures associated with aspiration pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Zithromax, Zantac.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.  In hyperventilation and early drowsiness, there is subtle focal slowing from the right mid-temporal region with rare, discreet T2/T4 sharp waves as well as a single sharp wave from the left. There are isolated, rhythmic bursts of 2 to 3 Hz activity, again maximum in the right temporal region.  There is also EKG artifact picked up in the same electrodes.  This can be differentiated from the focal slowing or epileptiform activity. Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  The patient is observed to be in stage II sleep during photic stimulation.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Rare, subtle right temporal focal slowing.
Rare temporal sharp waves, right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  The features are on the right are similar to previous studies, and the single left temporal sharp has not previously been identified.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Rare, subtle right temporal focal slowing. Rare temporal sharp waves, right greater than left.
