report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old male with metastatic lung cancer.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The awake background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The most striking abnormality in this record is a high amplitude spike and slow wave, poly spike and slow wave complex identified from the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread including C4, P4, and T4.  The focal spiking may be intermittent, periodic, or occur in transient clusters.  When the spiking stops, the posterior dominant rhythm on the right is well defined and there are portions of the record where it is defined bilaterally.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the epileptiform activity becomes increasingly periodic and the EEG develops a small degree of discontinuity in sleep around the epileptiform activity.
Photic stimulation elicits primarily a photoelectric effect, but there is a suggestion of a driving response underneath that.
HR:  118 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions.
Associated focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural abnormality as well as a partial localization method for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions. Associated focal slowing.

report:

report:

MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. This EEG was compared to previous EEGs from 2001 and 2003.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10 Hz, 50 to 75 V posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posterior slow waves of youth.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha with vertex waves and stage I sleep.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Occasional POSTS are identified in sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Of note, the last two EEGs for this child have not identified epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 16.11-year-old male seizure-free since 2001, history of 3 Hz, generalized spike and slow wave activity with two previous EEGs normal, now off AED.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Posterior slow waves of youth are seen and there are one or two brief epochs where the child has just a single burst of a vertex wave, a bit of drowsiness, and then immediately returns to wakefulness.
The major abnormalities in this record are elicited in hyperventilation and include a frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave discharge lasting less then three seconds in duration, typically on the order of 1 to 1.5 seconds in duration.  This is seen in hyperventilation and in the minutes that follow hyperventilation.  After this, the patient becomes drowsy.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, there is some slowing of the background.  Some of the features seen in the initial portions of the record with a microscopic lead are seen again, sometimes with a parietal maximum.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  In the interburst interval again, the activity in the parietal region PZ is identified.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized frontally predominant spike and slow wave and poly spike and slow wave complexes of 4 to 5 Hz in duration, all brief, seen primarily in hyperventilation.
Focal transience seen in the parietal region, PZ and occasionally P3.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is similar to this child’s first EEG and contrast from the last two did not demonstrate epileptiform activity.  The parietal activity seen may be an unusual manifestation of the generalized discharge, or a separate, focal feature. The PZ/P3 findings described above may not necessarily change the classification of this child’s epilepsy syndrome.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized frontally predominant spike and slow wave and poly spike and slow wave complexes of 4 to 5 Hz in duration, all brief, seen primarily in hyperventilation. Focal transience seen in the parietal region, PZ and occasionally P3.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 17-year-old male with a history of generalized epilepsy, previous history of spike and slow wave activity, last seizure sometime this past summer.  No warning and no postictal drowsiness.  Seizures have been described like “waking up from a dream.”
MEDICATIONS: Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posterior slow waves of youth. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and does not activate the record.
The major abnormality in this tracing is a subtle finding and includes very discrete bursts of paroxysmal, sharp and slow complexes of approximately 4 to 5 Hz occurring as couplets.  There are also some brief paroxysmal bursts of slowing without a definitive sharp and slow wave complex.  These appear to be generalized and unfortunately seem to be contaminated by some eye artifact, which follows them.   No clinical correlates are noted.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Subtle but clearly present paroxysmal 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to the reports of previous EEGs, this EEG shows less in the way of epileptiform activity.  The subtleties of this activity may be part of the maturational changes for this teenager.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Subtle but clearly present paroxysmal 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.

report:

report:

2008 or 2005.

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

In addition, the left hemisphere demonstrates disruption of faster frequency activity and a bit more theta. Drowsiness is characterized  by background slowing and accentuation of the interhemispheric asymmetry. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, right more remarkably than the left.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to,
1. 	Focal slowing from the left, characterized by disruption of faster frequency on that side.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were observed. Additional recording is recommended.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to,
1. Focal slowing from the left, characterized by disruption of faster frequency on that side.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  78 year-old male with a diagnosis of left temporal epilepsy, last seizure June 2008.  Past medical history of a stroke, CEA, seizure disorder, hypertension, and coronary artery disease.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, ASA, Enalapril, Cozaar, Norvasc, Carvedilol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and asleep record with photic stimulation done.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Current EEG is abnormal. There is generalized background slowing with alpha rhythm of 7.8 Hertz bilaterally.  In addition, there is an interhemispheric asymmetry with higher amplitude on the left, a digital focal slowing on the left, with sharply contoured slowing on the left. Vertex waves are seen during sleep. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. The heart rate is 48 beats per minute and irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized frontal background slowing.
Superimposed focal slowing, most prominent in the temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. The focal slowing is congruent with the left temporal stroke history.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild generalized frontal background slowing. Superimposed focal slowing, most prominent in the temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy, but has been seizure-free for years.  This is a follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized.  There is a 10 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Wicket activity can be seen in the right temporal area.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the background amplitude as well as a small amount of slowing.  In drowsiness discrete T4 sharp activity, occasionally with slow activity, was seen.  Sleep is characterized by slow rolling eye movements, followed by theta.  In stage II sleep: spindles, and K complexes.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving bilaterally, with an unusual  photoparoxysmal response which included  slowing  with frequency evolution but no spike and wave activity and no clinical symptoms.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Discrete right temporal sharp activity with associated underlying focal slowing.
Unusual photoparoxysmal response
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG done on December 18, 2002, this tracing yields a similar discrete right temporal sharp activity supporting a partial mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.  The photoparoxysmal response was reported in this patients’ childhood records.  Wicket activity is a normal variant.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Discrete right temporal sharp activity with associated underlying focal slowing. Unusual photoparoxysmal response

report:

report:

report:

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to shifting temporal slowing, left greater than right noted in drowsiness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old male with epilepsy and HIV infection with multiple frequent seizures and strong suspicions for non-epileptic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Phenobarbital, and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient has a long behavioral event and requires Ativan to calm down.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient starts hyperventilation early on in the record without the development of epileptiform activity.  At 11:48:34, he begins to have shaking movements, shaking the head from side to side and arms going up and down.  There are then some rotatory components or circular movements of the head.  The activity waxes and wanes.  The physician comes in to test the patient at 11:55:30.  The patient’s behavior waxes and wanes.  He is examined by a physician and nurse, and is clearly interactive during the spell.  Ativan is given at 16:14 and by 16:17, he is a bit more responsive and interactive.  When asked where he is, he responds that he is at [hospital] Hospital.  The EEG demonstrates a relatively normal pattern by the end with some generous beta.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prolonged behavioral event, lasting almost 20 minutes, was not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG.  Consideration for other diagnostic categories is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
History:	65 year old woman with seizures.

Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is noted.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm
attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication
effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication
effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

HR:  __ BPM.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old male with a hyperglycemic-related seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Benadryl, Folate, Clonidine, Ativan, and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized, low voltage with an 8.5 Hz, 15 to 20 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in the background beta activity, as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  As the tracing continues, the patient is increasingly restless and the EEG has increasing amounts of muscle.
Photic stimulation elicits brief, bilateral driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There were no specific hallmarks of a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old male with epilepsy and drug abuse who presents with right arm shaking and weakness and right eye twitching.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Clonidine, and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and briefly asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 25 to 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry seen mainly in hyperventilation, which is characterized by drop-out of faster frequency of the left centrotemporal area and occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves.  Stage I sleep is briefly achieved and characterized by vertex waves and slow rolling eye movements.  MU rhythm is seen better in the right hemisphere than on the left.  Photic stimulation elicits a minimal driving response.
HR:  87 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
A subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry with left centrotemporal slowing in early hyperventilation.
Occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves, which increase in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  Correlation with neuroimaging studies would be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to A subtle intrahemispheric asymmetry with left centrotemporal slowing in early hyperventilation. Occasional left frontotemporal sharp waves, which increase in hyperventilation.

report:

report:
HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old male with adult-onset epilepsy and vagus

system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well .
organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low
voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In the transition to drowsiness, there is a single burst

artifact. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of generalized background slowing.
Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR: 72BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

cannot be considered pathological. Additional recording capturing stage II sleep may be
valuable. Of note, only one previous normal BEG from 2004 was identified in the file for
this individual today. Additional longer-term sleep recording may be critical to
characterize epileptiform activity if seizures persist.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old man with seizures.  Patient fell down the stairs with a left parietal subdural.

MEDICATIONS: Tetanus shot, Dilantin, Tylenol, and Thiamine.

INTRODUCTION: Digital  video EEG  is performed in  the  lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: The background EEG is organized. The posterior rhythm is about 10Hz alpha, and the anterior rhythm is low voltage beta. Diffusely, there is excessive beta activity seen in this record.  Drowsiness and sleep were not noted during this record. There is no abnormal epileptiform activity seen in this record.   There is no abnormal interhemispheric  attenuation or slowing seen in this record.

HR:  80BPM.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG, however, there is excessive sedative  drug effect due  to beta activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this patient who is on sedative agents, the excess beta probably represents medication effect. However, abnormal epileptiform activity was not seen this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG, however, there is excessive sedative  drug effect due  to beta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 43-year-old male with recurrent seizures, last seizure three weeks ago with loss of consciousness with generalized tonic-clonic activity for one to two minutes.  History of skull fracture associated with subdural hematoma following an MVA in 2002 and alcohol abuse.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, but mildly disorganized.  There is a 12 Hz, 10 to 15 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is attenuated with eyes opened. There is a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, producing an increase in the slow activity of theta in the frontal region.  Post-hyperventilation, the activity returns to baseline within two minutes. Sleep is not achieved in this tracing.  Photic stimulation elicits driving, but no abnormal responses.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Mildly disorganized background.
Excessive beta activity seen throughout the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings are non-specific.  The increased beta activity may be due to medication or long-term alcohol use.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background. Excessive beta activity seen throughout the record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This  is  a  44-year-old   male  with  alcohol  withdrawal,  head trauma, and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Probably Trazodone, Lexapro, or others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video BEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system  of  electrode  placement  with  one  channel  of  EKG.  The  patient  is  somewhat confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: The background BEG is abnormal and includes a pattern of diffuse  beta.   The left hemisphere  demonstrates  higher amplitude  arrhythmic delta  activity  with  a breach  rhythm  and  at  times  sharply contoured  delta  in the  left frontocentral frontotemporal region.   Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, but deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR:  96BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal BEG due to:
1.  Excess background  beta.
2.   Continuous  mixed  arrhythmic  delta and theta from the left hemisphere,  particularly from the frontocentral region.
3.   Sharply contoured delta in the same region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This BEG supports a structural abnormality  on the left, as well as likely  a prior breach rhythm given the head trauma history.  Excess beta may be due to medications  or other causes.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal BEG due to 1.  Excess background  beta. 2.   Continuous  mixed  arrhythmic  delta and theta from the left hemisphere,  particularly from the frontocentral region. 3.   Sharply contoured delta in the same region.

report:
HISTORY: 18-year-old female with new onset seizures in November 2003 x two.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and  well organized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.   There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation activates the record with focal slowing at T6 and O2 areas and occasionally with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges in T6 as well as occasional bilateral posterior temporal slow activity. Focal findings can also be observed in drowsiness. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing at T6 and O2 accentuated in hyperventilation with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges at T6, as well as slowing in the bilateral posterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this tracing are suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient and supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing at T6 and O2 accentuated in hyperventilation with subtle 3 Hz slow wave discharges at T6, as well as slowing in the bilateral posterior temporal region.

Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, severe
No reactivity
Interpretation:

of reactivity. These findings are indicative of severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically nonspecific.

etiologically nonspecific

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old male with paroxysmal dyskinesias versus epilepsy (PKD) diagnosed at age eight.  Symptoms occur with no warning, now with increasing symptoms in the setting of stress.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record. Of note, the patient was experiencing a feeling as if he was about to have one of his attacks on the day of this study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 50 uV with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The overall waking background is well organized. On one occasion in drowsiness and during hyperventilation, there are occasional, brief bursts lasting one to five seconds, typically on the order of three seconds, of slightly irregular theta.  Particularly during hyperventilation, the theta seems to be a bit more prominent on the right with disruption of the posterior dominant rhythm on the right. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
The patient experiences an ongoing feeling throughout the EEG as if he is about to have one of his spells and at 14:39 he reports pressure in his right leg. He reports to the tech at 14:47 that the right leg feels numb at that time.  No EEG changes are seen in association with these symptoms, and the brief bursts of slightly irregular slowing are not seen at the specific times that the patient reports his symptoms.
HR:  68 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Brief bursts of slightly irregular theta, which during hyperventilation seem to disrupt the alpha rhythm on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were seen in this record.  The brief bursts of slightly irregular theta are a non-specific abnormality and may be correlated with neuroimaging.  The symptoms that this patient experienced were not associated with a change in the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Brief bursts of slightly irregular theta, which during hyperventilation seem to disrupt the alpha rhythm on the right.

report:

Modest disorganization.
Occasional FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old  woman with refractory  epilepsy  characterized by nocturnal tonic-clonic  seizures for the past 13 years.
MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital  video EEG is performed  in the lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement  with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This i s an one­ hour EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness  is characterized by slow rolling  eye movements.  Vertex waves,  K complexes,  and spindles  are  seen  in sleep.   In the transition to drowsiness,  there are  brief  bursts  of frontally predominant  very high amplitude spike and slow wave activity.  Tl1e sensitivity  of the EEG must be adjusted to 20 uV/mm.  There are discrete bursts that appear and can be differentiated from the patient's  other normal  morphologies of sleep.   As the patient more cl early transitions  to stage I sleep,  the  vertex waves  that  were  noted  are broader  in  morphology.    There  seems  to be  an asymmetry technically between the two regions.
In this one-hour recording, these brief bursts  of frontally predominant spike and wave activity are notable.
Photic stimulation  elicits a driving response.  No photoparoxysmal  response  was noted.
HR:  96BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Frontally  predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike and wave activity seen  in the  transition  b and from sleep, but not typically in deeper stages of sleep and not in wakefulness.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old male who fell and hit his head, losing consciousness.  History of cocaine use and prior traumatic brain injury.  CAT scan showed a left parietal subacute effusion.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is mildly disorganized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 20 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which attenuates with eyes opened.   There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  As the recording continues, bilateral focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right, is seen.  The patient easily fell asleep, which is evidenced by vertex waves and spindles, as well as a lot of snoring.  The focal slowing was more dramatic during sleep and the asymmetry did not change during sleep.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mildly disorganized background.
Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this EEG are indicative of an underlying pathological process suggestive of a structural lesion. The patient’s loud snoring may be suggestive of obstructive sleep apnea and follow-up with a pulmonologist to rule out a sleep disorder is suggested.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mildly disorganized background. Focal arrhythmic delta activity, more predominant on the left than the right.

report:
HISTORY: 59-year-old woman with complex partial seizures, last seizure 3 months ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 10 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Soon after the beginning of this recording, wicket activity is seen in the left anterior temporal area.  In drowsiness, occasional sharp activity is also observed in the temporal area with intermittent focal slowing. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Occasional left anterior quadrant sharp activity with intermittent focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal findings in this supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy in this patient. Wicket activity is a normal variant, however, it was only seen in the left anterior temporal area, which is an unusual finding. Correlation with neuroimaging studies is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Occasional left anterior quadrant sharp activity with intermittent focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old woman with epilepsy, schizophrenia, COPD admitted with multiple complex partial seizures, drug interactions. Previously seizure free.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin,  Dilantin, Hydralazine, Ciprofloxacin, Percocet
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel of EKG. The date of this patient's seizures is not provided.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG includes an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm on the right, disrupted on the left. The left hemisphere includes arrhythmic delta activity with a high amplitude periodic sharp wave, maximum at T2 with a generous field of spreading involving the total of T3, T5 and F7. As the recording continues and the patient is stimulated this arrhythmic delta activity in the sharp waves waxes and wanes. The sharp waves may occur in bursts and trains but none last more than 10 seconds. The patient drifts into stage  1  sleep with vertex waves. The focal sharp wave contoured delta, focal slowing and sharp waves persist. There is a generous field of spread both for the sharp waves and to the focal slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, more so on the right.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Prominent focal slowing from the left temporal region.
2.	Prominent left temporal sharp waves, sometimes periodic, sometimes occurring in trains.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   This EEG supports a highly irritative focus and a localization related mechanism to epilepsy. Please pull previous studies for comparison to this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Prominent focal slowing from the left temporal region. 2.Prominent left temporal sharp waves, sometimes periodic, sometimes occurring in trains.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old right handed male with recent left MCA infarct, aneurysm repair, ACA clip, chronic encephalomalacia in the right frontal region now with drowsiness and new left-sided weakness transferred back from the nursing home.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Lovenox, Depakote, ASA
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient has a prominent craniotomy in the right frontal region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG is markedly abnormal and slow.  In fact, the right hemisphere is not as slow as the left.  There is a 7 Hz alpha rhythm on the right.  The left hemisphere demonstrates lower voltage and slower theta.  The right hemisphere demonstrates a prominent breach rhythm at C4 with prominent accentuation of beta frequency activity.  As the patient transitions to sleep, however, there are some sharp waves and spikes noted at C4-P4.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response more prominently from the right than the left.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry.
A slow pattern on the left.
A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a process involving the left hemisphere more significantly than the right.  This may reflect the  bilateral nature of this patient's multiple CNS insults.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry. A slow pattern on the left. A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.

report:
HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old, left-handed male with epilepsy since age 9 with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  No previous records were available for comparison.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is occasional temporal wicket, but there is a suspicious, underlying right temporal sharp wave identified in early drowsiness.
As the patient emerges to and from sleep, there is some rhythmic frontal mixed theta and delta, which is on the whole symmetric, although on one or two occasions there is a suggestion of maximum on the right.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  On two occasions, there are bursts of rhythmic frontally predominant, paroxysmal activity.  On one occasion, this occurs in the setting of hyperventilation and there seems to be some underlying eye blink, but there is suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz frontally predominant spike and slow wave and poly spike and slow wave activity followed by a more clearly defined eye blink.  The second burst occurs with the transition to sleep.  Again, the burst is less than two seconds long with approximately 5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave/poly spike and wave activity.  No eye blink can be seen at this time, although the activity is picked up on the eye monitor at the midline.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  66 BPM. April 15, 2004

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz poly spike and slow wave activity seen in hyperventilation and on one occasion in drowsiness.
Subtle right anterior temporal sharp waves with questionable focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Consideration for more than one mechanism to account for this patient’s seizures would be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Suspicious, 3 to 5 Hz poly spike and slow wave activity seen in hyperventilation and on one occasion in drowsiness. Subtle right anterior temporal sharp waves with questionable focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old woman with a history of hypertension, end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis admitted for subdural hemorrhage, which was surgically.  Acute seizures, not described

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, antihypertensives, and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the Neuro ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is continuous and symmetric with generalized slowing.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Soon after the EEG commences, the patient began to shake her left arm and then both arms and hands on her abdomen.  The shaking was in a different direction at different rhythms.  The patient could open and close her eyes and follow commands during this episode.  Alternatively, when her left-hand shaking stopped, she began to open and close her legs with shaking, left side worse then the right.  With the prolonged episode, muscle movement artifact can be seen, but no significant EEG changes or correlates were found.  On the video camera, several doctors were called to see the patient.  The patient can open and close her eyes, follow commands, and lift her arms and legs up.  Interestingly, the patientÕs episodes spontaneously subsided if no one paid attention to her and she responded to a placebo of saline injection.  Throughout the EEG, there were no epileptiform discharges, but occasionally sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area is seen.

HR:  116 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffusely slow background.
2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The diffusely slow background, as well as occasional sharply contoured delta activity in the left central area may be suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient, which is commonly seen in patients with hypertension and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.  This finding can also be seen in patients with subdural hematoma.  During the tracing, the patient had prolonged episodes of arm or leg shaking without EEG change, as well as being responsive to commands.  This is suggestive of non-epileptic seizures.  These findings were communicated with the primary neurosurgery team.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern or clinically indicated, when the patient is more stable and cooperative, a repeat EEG in the lab with full activation including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, as well as capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Diffusely slow background. 2. Occasional sharply contoured delta in the left central area.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 30-year-old male with likely frontal lobe epilepsy with frequent nocturnal seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. In drowsiness, there is a very subtle difference.  There is a bit more beta in the left frontal region than the right.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Beta asymmetry seen in drowsiness with a bit more beta from the left compared to the right and a slightly lower voltage record on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Given the description of this patient’s seizures with involuntary turning of the head and twitching before loss of consciousness, this area of the brain may be difficult in terms of identifying epileptiform activity, but additional studies in sleep could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to Beta asymmetry seen in drowsiness with a bit more beta from the left compared to the right and a slightly lower voltage record on the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old male with a history of epilepsy and a syncopal episode with jerking movements of the body and gasping sounds.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Benadryl, and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the/at the lab/bedside? using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of the waking record is poorly organized, although at the very end of the record, the background EEG is actually reasonably well organized with a low voltage pattern and a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  In the early portions of the record, when the patient appears to be awake, the background EEG is moderately disorganized with some shifting slowing.  There is also some temporal wicket activity seen.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and elicits rhythmic bursts of frontally predominant, high amplitude delta, which are quite prominent.  In addition, underlying this, there are some right temporal sharp waves.  In the post-HV recording, there is an underlying right temporal sharp and slow wave activity.
Photic stimulation elicits a photoelectric artifact only.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Despite the technical limitations described above, this EEG is abnormal due to:
Right temporal sharp waves.
Shifting arrhythmic delta activity seen particularly in the initial portions of the record.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy.  The dynamic changes with improvement in the organization towards the end of the record may be part of this patient’s recovery from some sort of acute disturbance, which may be postictal, metabolic, or post-syncope. With a prominent frontal delta in HV, this is a non-specific finding and comparison with previous studies may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Despite the technical limitations described above, this EEG is abnormal due to Right temporal sharp waves. Shifting arrhythmic delta activity seen particularly in the initial portions of the record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old male with seizures characterized by eyes rolling back, loss of consciousness, and emotional reactions. Recent, adult onset epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal and Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 to 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. In wakefulness, there are occasional, high amplitude left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes.  These reach amplitudes well over 100 uV and are preceded and followed by focal slowing.  There is intermittent left mid-to-anterior temporal focal slowing seen in brief bursts lasting less than one second with a mixture of delta and theta frequency activity, as well as a disruption of alpha frequency activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is also some rhythmic left temporal theta identified. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, as well as attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  The drowsy record is primarily recorded in referential montage, and the left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes can be identified in this montage.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  The epileptiform discharges are also seen in photic stimulation, but are not clearly accentuated by this procedure.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal spike and slow wave activity identified in wakefulness.
Intermittent focal slowing seen from the left temporal region, accentuated in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  In comparison to previous studies, the epileptiform activity in this record is on the left as opposed to being on the right in the initial study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal spike and slow wave activity identified in wakefulness. Intermittent focal slowing seen from the left temporal region, accentuated in drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed male with epilepsy post-stroke, tonic clonic seizures for the last four years, last seizure was one month ago. History of hypertension, epilepsy post-stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Keppra, Metoprolol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is occasional shifting temporal theta, more prominent on the left than the right. Discrete anterior temporal sharp waves are observed with rare (2) right centrotemporal sharp waves and a very subtle accentuation of beta activity in the right centrotemporal region, seen in sleep. Hyperventilation accentuates the focal features from the left temporal region. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. Sharp waves seen primarily on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been described in previous EEGs and support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. Of note, the epileptiform activity on the right has been noted in this individual with many studies, not all have identified epileptiform activity as is often the case in complex partial epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing. 2. Sharp waves seen primarily on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old right-handed man with history of seizures during asleep described as generalized tonic-clonic activity.  His last seizure was 6 months ago.  Past medical history is significant for hypertension and memory difficulties and hypertriglyceridemia.  This is a followup EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, oxazepam, Lamictal, citalopram, lithium.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm is 8.5-9 Hz in frequency, 30-35 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 7-7.5 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is presence of stage 1 sleep characterized by disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Brief stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not result in a driving response.  Hyperventilation was also performed and results in diffuse slowing of the background activity.  Heart rate was 70-80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures are identified in this record.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old male with complex partial epilepsy, now with increasing seizures since he ran out of Lamictal.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Tegretol, Lamictal, and Glucotrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal. The right hemisphere is relatively well organized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz, 30 uV.  The left hemisphere demonstrates intermittent arrhythmic delta activity seen occasionally in wakefulness, accentuated by hyperventilation, maximum in the temporal region.  There are a handful of left anterior temporal sharp waves identified in hyperventilation in the bursts of rhythmic slowing.  Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, the focal slowing from the left is accentuated.  On one occasion there is a train of sharp waves identified from the left temporal region, as well as a single right temporal sharp wave.  These can be differentiated from the patient’s EKG artifact.   On some occasions, there is a somewhat periodic left temporal sharp wave picked up, but mixed in this discharge there will be a subtle right anterior temporal sharp wave.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  The epileptiform activity appears to decrease in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal focal slowing.
Left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes, which are sometimes periodic.
Occasional right temporal sharp waves, which seem to occur out of the background, independently at times periodic sharp waves on the left, but occur during the same epochs when the focus on the left is active.  No seizures were recorded.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy as well as structural abnormality on the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal focal slowing. Left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes, which are sometimes periodic. Occasional right temporal sharp waves, which seem to occur out of the background, independently at times periodic sharp waves on the left, but occur during the same epochs when the focus on the left is active.  No seizures were recorded.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with seizures since age 9.  Increasing seizures in pregnancy characterized by jerking of the hands followed by loss of consciousness, tonic-clonic activity, incontinence, tongue biting, and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, folate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 80 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a modest amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing a small amount of slowing as well as increasing the amplitude of the background.  At the end of hyperventilation, there is a single burst of arrhythmic delta seen first on the left and then on the right.  Following this, the patient becomes drowsy with an increase in background beta as well as occasional vertex waves.  Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and POSTS with intermittent arousals from sleep.  As she awakens from sleep for photic stimulation, a hypersynchronous pattern is identified.
Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response seen with a spiky driving at 5 Hz, but no definite spike and slow wave complex.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered normal in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The single asynchronous burst seen in hyperventilation is of unclear clinical significance.  Given the pattern identified with a 5 Hz driving response, comparison with childhood EEGs may be helpful in characterizing this patient’s epilepsy.  Alternatively, additional recording with repeat photic stimulation at various frequencies and/or accentuated by hyperventilation could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered normal in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy or asleep throughout much of the record.  In drowsiness, there is rhythmic background theta followed by vertex waves in sleep.  He has multiple brief arousals.  Maximal wakefulness is not sustained, but in the brief occasion that wakefulness is achieved, his alpha rhythm is 8 Hz.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Mild slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 26-year-old female with seizures in February and July of 2004.  Most recent seizure associated with Xanax withdrawal. Positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The major abnormality in this record is occipitally predominant rhythmic approximately 5 Hz activity.  This can be seen in wakefulness and is clearly accentuated in hyperventilation.  On some occasions it is seen into stage II sleep.  This activity can be reviewed in both circle montage and a referential montage.  In hyperventilation, this activity appears to be sometimes maximum on the right spreading to the left, but in other settings, the activity appears to be symmetric, nearly identical or clearly identical at O1 and O2.  During hyperventilation, the occipitally predominant theta frequency activity has some paroxysmal build up, but does not evolve.  Other features of hyperventilation include both eye blink and hypersynchronous rhythmic high amplitude delta.
Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.  Some of the occipitally predominant bursts can be seen even in photic.
HR:  82 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Occipitally predominant, 5 to 6 Hz theta activity, increasing in hyperventilation and persisting into stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: To further localize this activity, a follow-up study with special electrodes may be valuable.  Correlation with neuroimaging may be helpful.  These findings were not seen on this patient’s previous EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Occipitally predominant, 5 to 6 Hz theta activity, increasing in hyperventilation and persisting into stage II sleep.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.

The patient goes in and out of stage I and stage II sleep with high amplitude vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal. The background EEG is sharply contoured.  There are some sharply contoured normal variants, but there is a slight amount of irregular theta in stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Correlation with previous imaging and previous studies would be helpful in terms of evaluating this patient’s risks for future seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal. The background EEG is sharply contoured.  There are some sharply contoured normal variants, but there is a slight amount of irregular theta in stage II sleep.

Occasional left temporal sharp waves.
Hyperventilation producing left temporal slowing more than the right.

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle left temporal focal slowing elicited in hyperventilation and persisting afterwards, at times sharply contoured.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old woman with epilepsy since childhood, one of a pair of twins.  Mild cognitive impairment and obsessive-compulsive disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lamictal, Risperdal, Lithium, and Paxil.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In wakefulness, there is frequent eye blink, but in the transition from wakefulness to drowsiness, there is also notched, sharply contoured, frontally predominant 5 to 7 Hz activity in the frontal regions, as well as a signal left mid-to-anterior temporal sharp wave.  There were a total of four left anterior temporal sharp waves.  Features of sleep include an increase in beta activity as well as occasional vertex waves and spindles.  There are multiple brief arousals from sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and appears to accentuate some of the rhythmic frontal 5 to 7 Hz activity.  In sleep, there is a second, left temporal sharp wave.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Some sharply contoured, notched 5 to 7 Hz activity seen in the frontal regions, sometimes with isolated discharges and sometimes seen with brief bursts seen in wakefulness and in sleep.
Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy.  The rhythmic theta frequency activity described above may be part of this patient’s constellation of neurologic abnormalities.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Some sharply contoured, notched 5 to 7 Hz activity seen in the frontal regions, sometimes with isolated discharges and sometimes seen with brief bursts seen in wakefulness and in sleep. Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. HR:  88 BPM.

1.	Left anterior temporal sharp and slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings contrast to a previous, normal EEG.  Consideration for a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Left anterior temporal sharp and slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old woman with asthma, anxiety, and epilepsy for ten years consisting of complex partial seizures.  Patient admitted with multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Phenobarbital, Ativan, Combivent, Prevacid, Flonase, and Trazodone.

Hyperventilation increases the slow activity in the background.  Sleep is evidenced by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  44 year old left handed female with refractory seizures, GERD, hyperlipidemia, DVT, PE, asthma, diabetes, and hypertension who complains of chest pain.  She did not take Zonisamide this morning.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, Lisinopril, Percocet, Narcan, Zocor, Lovenox, ASA.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in stage I and stage II sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F7/T1.
Focal slow waves seen almost continuously at F7/T1 throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
Continuous slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy, with seizures likely arising from the left anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which has a high correlation with a structural lesion in that region.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal sharp waves. Continuous slowing.

report:
History:	47 year old woman who was found down.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, asleep
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of polymorphic up to 9 Hz unstable alpha activity with poor
AP gradient.  The background contains excess polymorphic theta and delta activity.  Patient rapidly
transitions between wakefulness and drowsiness.  Symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-
complexes are noted.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is nearly continuous T5
electrode artifact.
Summary of Findings:
Artifact, electrode, nearly continuous,  T5 electrode artifact
No epileptiform discharges
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep portable EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
background disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse
cerebral dysfunction.  But in this patient, these findings could also be contributed to excessive
drowsiness ( given rapid transitions between wakefulness and drowsiness).  The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep portable EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and
background disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male who was being evaluated for an intra-arterial TPA when he had a seizure.  He was noted to be aphasic and was in the middle of the stroke protocol when the event occurred.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, aspirin, Heparin, thiamin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record in a patient who varies between drowsiness and restlessness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are brief portions of the record where the patient is maximally alert and a low voltage 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is identified.  During much of the waking record, there is bilateral excess theta.  In addition, temporal wicket is seen.  There is intermittent, arrhythmic temporal slowing identified, left greater than right.  Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves.  As the recording continues in this postictal patient, the overall background organization improves and the focality is more left temporal than right.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially, bihemispheric slowing.
Shifting temporal slowing, which by the close of the record is most prominent on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This tracing supports a dynamic process, which seems to be improving over time and may reflect a postictal state.   Correlation with neuroimaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Initially, bihemispheric slowing. Shifting temporal slowing, which by the close of the record is most prominent on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient has a history of seizures since 5 months of age.  He remained seizure-free for 9 years, but the seizures resumed 1 year ago in sleep.  The most recent seizure was in March 2013 during which he was shaking and was unarousable.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed using the 10-20 electrode placement system with one channel of EKG.  The EKG was recorded in awake, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.

A normal frontal central beta rhythm is noted.
Stage I and stage II sleep was achieved during the recording.  Stage II was characterized by vertex waves and spindles.

SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  The single burst of right midtemporal slowing is of nonspecific clinical significance.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Normal EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.  Clinical correlation recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  The single burst of right midtemporal slowing is of nonspecific clinical significance.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 31-year-old male with childhood epilepsy, seizure free until recent years.  Patient states that he is currently seizure-free for the past year.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra, retrovirals.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  A subtle asymmetry is noted between the 2 hemispheres with a bit of 7 Hz theta noted in the right hemisphere relative to the left and very subtle disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the record becomes increasingly synchronous and symmetric.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic background theta and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Brief spindles were noted with POSTS in stage 2 sleep.  Photic stimulation was performed as the patient is drifting in to stage 2 sleep, and did not significantly activate the record.  Hyperventilation produced a vigorous hyperventilation response with an increase in rhythmic theta as well as an increase in beta.  There is some subtle, asymmetric bursts noted in hyperventilation with higher amplitude rhythmic theta noted on the left.  There is one, suspicious underlying sharp waves noted at the close of hyperventilation in the right centrotemporal region.
Heart rate 56 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm.
An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only a single sharp wave was seen there for this must not be considered definitively epileptogenic.  This is the 7th EEG for this individual.  Previous EEGs have identified right mid temporal sharp waves, which were not identified at this time.  This patient's 2004-2008 EEGs were not available for comparison.  No prominent epileptiform or focal features were noted, and no new findings were noted in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to A very subtle asymmetry, identified using a frequency analysis with an increase in 7 Hz activity noted intermittently in the right hemisphere with disruption of the alpha rhythm. An asynchronous hyperventilation response with higher amplitude rhythmic theta.

efavirenz-emtrictabine-tenofovir (ATRIPLA) 600-200-300 mg per tablet, TAKE 1 TABLET BY
MOUTH NIGHTLY.

None

report:
HISTORY:

47 y.o. male with a history of MS, Epilepsy, NIDDM, Hypothyroidism, Congenital
hydrocephalus, from longterm care facility. referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

mirtazapine (REMERON) 15 mg tablet, Take 15 mg by mouth nightly.

multivitamin (THERAGRAN) per tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.


rivaroxaban (XARELTO) 20 mg Tablet, Take 20 mg by mouth daily.

bisacodyl (DULCOLAX) 10 mg suppository, Place 10 mg rectally daily.

sodium phosphates (SODIUM PHOSPHATE) 19-7 gram/118 mL Enema, Place 1 enema rectally
daily as needed.


magnesium hydroxide (MILK OF MAGNESIA) 400 mg/5 mL Suspension, Take  by mouth daily.


levothyroxine (SYNTHROID) 25 mcg tablet, Take 25 mcg by mouth daily.

clindamycin (CLEOCIN) 150 mg capsule, Take 150 mg by mouth 3 times daily.

docusate sodium (COLACE) 100 mg capsule, Take 100 mg by mouth 2 times daily.




levetiracetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 500 mg by mouth 2 times daily.

megestrol (MEGACE) 20 mg tablet, Take 20 mg by mouth daily.


loperamide (IMODIUM A-D) 2 mg capsule, Take 2 mg by mouth 4 times daily as needed for Diarrhea.

tramadol (ULTRAM) 50 mg tablet, Take 50 mg by mouth every 6 hours as needed for Pain.


acetaminophen (TYLENOL) 325 mg tablet, Take 650 mg by mouth every 6 hours as needed for
Pain.

SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric and reactive, with a fairly organized mixture of alpha, beta, and
theta frequencies, with fragments of a symmetric and reactive posterior dominant rhythm that
approaches 8 Hertz. The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present
but suboptimal.




Drowsiness and sleep are not captured.



Mild generalized slowing is present.

There is occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing.



There are frequent spikey waveforms over F7, F8 that appear most consistent with lateral rectus spikes.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.




EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 120 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to:

1. Mild generalized slowing and suboptimal organization


2. Occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing

3. Tachycardia


CLINICAL CORRELATION:



These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of the presence of left frontal dysfunction
superimposed on a mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.


Tachycardia is noted on a single EKG lead.



A call was placed to this patient's long term care facility to notify them of the tachycardia.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to 
1. Mild generalized slowing and suboptimal organization


2. Occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing

3. Tachycardia

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male with falls.  Evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Norvasc, Lipitor, Dilantin, Zocor, Lorazepam, and aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is organized with a 10 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
The major abnormality in this record is intermittent rhythmic temporal delta (FIRDA) seen in quiet wakefulness, accentuated by hyperventilation, and prominent in the transition to sleep.  It is sometimes associated with left anterior temporal spike and slow wave or sharp and slow wave complexes.  On one occasion, fast activity is associated with this.  Photic stimulation elicits both an arousal response and some driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional spike and slow or sharp and slow wave activity in the left anterior temporal region.
Left temporal FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The epileptiform features in this record are more prominent compared to previous studies.  This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  This is this patient’s third EEG in 2006, and it is his sixth EEG since 2002.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Occasional spike and slow or sharp and slow wave activity in the left anterior temporal region. Left temporal FIRDA.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and doesn’t seem to activate the record.  The patient seems to be a bit drowsy.  Following hyperventilation, however, there is some rhythmic theta picked up in the temporal regions, particularly in the T1-T2 electrodes more so on the left than the right.  In addition, despite some EKG artifact, there are some underlying sharp waves seen primarily at T1, but occasionally at T2 as well. HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent rhythmic temporal delta, left greater than right, primarily seen in drowsiness.
Independent, T1 or T2 spike and slow wave complexes seen primarily in drowsiness, greater on the left than the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Correlation with imaging may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent rhythmic temporal delta, left greater than right, primarily seen in drowsiness. Independent, T1 or T2 spike and slow wave complexes seen primarily in drowsiness, greater on the left than the right.
