report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 11-year-old male with epilepsy, seizure-free for almost two years on Dilantin.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is a sleep deprived EEG with a goal of recording 20 minutes of sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 to 9 Hz, 50 to 70 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In wakefulness, there are occasional LAMBDA waves.  Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm followed by vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS in stage II sleep.  In the initial sleep recording, there are occasional left or right centrotemporal sharp waves.  As the sleep recording continues, the epileptiform activity is seen less frequently and the field may include central parietal rather than centrotemporal regions.  They are seen more frequently in the initial sleep recording than infrequently in the later sleep recording.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing hypersynchronous, rhythmic high amplitude slowing.
Photic stimulation is performed while the child is asleep; in fact, it is performed as the child starts to enter stage III sleep and produces a bit of driving at faster frequency activity although the child does not remain awake.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
1.	Centrotemporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Comparison with previous EEGs would be helpful, but this pattern may be seen in rolandic epilepsy and similar epilepsy syndromes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to 1.Centrotemporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 12-year-old boy seizure-free for more than two years.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and well organized for age.  There is an 8 to 10 Hz, 50 to 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which attenuates with eye opening. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increased the burst of theta slow wave activity in the background.  There is a single T3 sharp wave without focal slowing.  Occasionally, occipital slow activity and POSTS were seen in drowsiness. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits mild subharmonic driving.
HR:  86 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake and drowsy EEG in a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG, this tracing shows improvement without focal slowing. Only one sharp wave was observed in the left temporal area, which can be seen in a normal subject of this age.  The posterior slow waves of youth and POSTS are normal variants. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake and drowsy EEG in a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with epilepsy.  Patient had one event during the EEG characterized by tenseness with eyes opened, not focused, mild tremulousness of body and legs, and unable to respond to questions during the event.  The patient was somewhat confused for 1.5 minutes afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Norvasc, Lasix, and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Photic stimulation is performed early on in the record.  A brief driving response is seen, but as the patient relaxes a little bit further, subtle left temporal slowing is seen.  Hyperventilation is performed subsequently and the subtle focal features can be identified.  A seizure occurred following hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation.  Post-hyperventilation, the focal slowing gradually increases 20 seconds after the onset of hyperventilation.  The seizure onset is at 14:08:37 with no clinical signs, but high amplitude spike and slow wave activity with rhythmic delta and then high amplitude delta and sharply contoured delta with a clear phase reversal at T1.  The patient starts to arouse at 14:08:57, opening his eyes and then stiffening.  He is slightly tremulous and demonstrates chewing movements.  The activity makes the transition to repetitive alpha frequency activity and then 5 Hz frequency activity by 14:09:17.  The activity begins to slow and ends at 14:09:38 for an approximate one-minute seizure duration.  The background EEG demonstrates postictal slowing in the minutes that follow, which gradually resolves.  The patient is unable to speak during the seizure and in the postictal period he nods his head from side to side.  He has a relatively lengthy postictal period including almost all the way to the end of the record.  Over time, he becomes increasingly able to speak, although initially he answers all questions with “uhm-uhm” noise.  Over time, he can answer questions, but has difficulty performing simple tasks.
HR:  94 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG.
Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Diagnostic of a partial mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal seizure, relatively well characterized by scalp EEG. Left temporal focal slowing with rare sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old, right-handed male with epilepsy since age 12.  Last seizure one week ago with postictal drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a high amplitude 50 to 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm of 10.5 Hz. Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Other features of drowsiness include a handful of POSTS and an increase in background theta.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric bilateral driving. Following photic stimulation, just at the close of the EEG, there is a single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
HR:  ___ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A single burst of epileptiform activity does not make this record abnormal, however, the activity described above is compatible with a primary generalized epilepsy.  It may be more cost effective to compare this EEG with previous, childhood studies rather than repeating a study.  Alternatively, if additional mechanisms are needed to characterize epileptiform activity, a fasting, sleep deprived study with generous hyperventilation could be effective.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 12-year-old male with a history of staring spells with impairment of consciousness lasting two to five seconds, occurring one to two times per month.  These episodes have been occurring since age four.  History of hypertension and  renal disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized for a child of this age.  There is a 9.5 Hz, 70 to 80 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a fair amount of theta.   There is intermittent rhythmic left posterior temporal spike and sharp waves with occasional generalized bursts of spike wave activity lasting two to three seconds.  Hyperventilation and post-hyperventilation seems to accentuate the discharges, which are followed by brief slowing for several seconds thereafter.  The left posterior temporal discharges are localized at T5, and occasional sharp waves are also noted on the right parietal area at P4 without causing generalized spread. The generalized discharges are frontally predominant and seem to arise out of a left temporal focus maximum at T5.  Photic stimulation elicits discrete driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spike wave discharges, which are preceded by a left posterior temporal discharge focus.
Somewhat slow and disorganized background for a child of this age.
Occasional sharp waves in the right hemisphere at P4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy in this patient with a left posterior temporal focus suggestive of complex partial seizures with occasional secondary generalization.  Correlation with neuroimaging studies is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Bursts of generalized spike wave discharges, which are preceded by a left posterior temporal discharge focus. Somewhat slow and disorganized background for a child of this age. Occasional sharp waves in the right hemisphere at P4.

report:
History:	21 YEAR OLD MALE WITH A HISTORY OF SEIZURES. LAST SEIZURE AS 12/20/2013.
Medications:	Tegretol
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic


Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Occasional brief (0.5-2 seconds) bursts of sharply contoured delta activity are noted during hyperventilation and drowsiness. During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.

No focal slowing is present. No clear epileptiform discharges are present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces bursts of diffuse, symmetric high-voltage, frontally-maximal delta activity. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.

Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges

Interpretation:
This is a likely NORMAL 25-minute EEG, awake and drowsy. Brief bursts of diffuse delta activity observed during hyperventilation and drowsiness are of uncertain clinical significance and may represent sleep architecture. A repeat prolonged EEG with sleep may be of benefit.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a likely NORMAL 25-minute EEG, awake and drowsy. Brief bursts of diffuse delta activity observed during hyperventilation and drowsiness are of uncertain clinical significance and may represent sleep architecture. A repeat prolonged EEG with sleep may be of benefit

None

None

IMPRESSION

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above findings are non-specific and may suggest a mild cervical dysfunction mainly involving the gray matter.  It can be seen in patients who are excessively sleepy, in a postictal phase, or due to medications.  Clinical correlation is recommended, however, no focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG when the patient is more alert and with routine activation procedures may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in this excessively sleepy patient due to Background slowing. Slow alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3-year-old male with afebrile seizures characterized by eyes rolling back in the head for five minutes, occurring once or twice per month.  Former 28-week gestation infant born weighing 3 lbs., 10 oz.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record. This is the third EEG for this individual.  The two previous EEGs indicated that he had febrile convulsions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  In sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are identified.
The major abnormality in this record, is discrete bursts of frontally predominant 3 Hz spike and wave activity seen in the transition to and from stage II sleep.  These are high amplitude discharges, typically occurring in discrete pairs, frontally predominant, symmetric, ranging from 3 to 3.5 Hz.  They can overlap with a spindle, which is a normal morphology of stage II sleep.  On one occasion, a pair of spike and wave complexes may be associated with an arousal.  At the close of the record, the child is stimulated from sleep, and occipitally predominant rhythmic slowing is followed by an awake pattern with LAMBDA when the child is more fully awake.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This activity was not seen in the two previous EEGs.  Correlation with this patient’s history may be helpful in that there were two previous EEGs demonstrating febrile convulsions with a child who may have developed afebrile convulsions and an EEG pattern that is most consistent with an inherited epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.

lamoTRIgine (LAMICTAL) 200 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 3 times daily.

simvastatin (ZOCOR) 20 mg tablet, Take 20 mg by mouth nightly.

calcium-vitamin D (OSCAL) 250 (625)-125 mg-unit per tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.

None

HEART RATE:




A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.

IMPRESSION

reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with a history of starring spells with lip smacking. Condition has been apparent since the fifth grade with an inconclusive prior work-up. Patient with recent episode of unresponsiveness without recollection of the event.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is fairly well organized with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There are rare, tiny left centrotemporal sharp waves at C3 and T3 followed by some subtle slowing and occasional left temporal irregular delta, Hyperventilation produces generalized slowing. Post-HV, the sharply contoured slowing on the left hemisphere is slightly increased. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.

Correlation with neuroimaging studies would be valuable.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with staring spells a1d lip smacking since fifth grade with generalized spike and slow wave activity in childhood, now with headaches and subtle left temporal findings on the most recent EEG. Previous hospitalization and EEG 03/05.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm of 30 to 50 uV. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. There is some eye movement artifact picked up in the temporal regions as well as some EKG artifact. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in theta in the background. Following HV, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background beta and some rhythmic central theta. In drowsiness, there is also some rare, rhythmic 4 to 5 Hz activity from the left temporal region. This is seen on a single location with brief bursts lasting less than a second. Photic stimulation elicits both vigorous driving and some photoelectric artifact. On two occasions, in photic stimulation with a 17 Hz stimulation and following the 15 Hz stimulation, there seems to be some rhythmic focal slowing with a mixture of theta and delta identified from the left hemisphere.
HR: 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Bursts of somewhat irregular slowing identified following photic stimulation from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although there are a handful of other features including a brief burst of theta from the left, which may be a normal variant, the more remarkable slowing seen in photic stimulation raises the possibility of either a structural or functional abnormality on the left. In this individual with a childhood history of generalized spike and slow wave activity, this finding has not been seen in either of her two adult EEGs. Individuals with childhood epilepsy may haw focal features in adulthood, but those described here are unusual for that.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Bursts of somewhat irregular slowing identified following photic stimulation from the left hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 21-year-old with epilepsy since age 12 and multiple different types of events, some of which resembled syncopal spells. Seizure free aside from 4 seizures in sleep in March 2007.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, folate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, background EEG included the 9.5 posterior dominant rhythm a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. There is a small amount of background theta. In relaxed wakefulness, there are a handful of subtle sharp waves from the left or right temporal region. Most of them are small and discreet, but some have a more of a broader morphology, although they are never high in amplitude. They lack the simplicity of benign epileptiform transience of sleep. The patient has stimulated for hyperventilation and these morphologies disappear. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in background theta. There is a suggestion that it may also accentuate an arrhythmic delta from the left with independent right and left temporal sharp and slow wave, or spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity identified in hyperventilation was denoted on the record. Towards the close of the record, high amplitude right inter temple spike and slow wave complexes with generous field of spread were observed. As the patient becomes drowsy, the right temporal sharp waves are again well defined and the left temporal features are not as commonly identified. Other features of sleep include vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation elicits harmonic with supra harmonic striving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness.
2. Occasional more poorly defined left temporal sharp waves.
Clinical correlation: For this young adult with a strong family history of epilepsy, this study today is most supportive of a localization related mechanism with a right inter temple sharp wave with a generous field of spread. There is a remarkably bigger striving response, but not a clearly pathological one.
Additional review of the epilepsy in the family would be important to know if this individual's epilepsy is similar or just similar to other members in the kindred. In contrast to previous studies, the vast majority of epileptiform features today were on the right rather than the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 33 -year-old woman with epilepsy onset at the age of 20. Last seizure about two weeks ago with an aura, nausea, headache, and loss of consciousness with generalized tonic-clonic activity lasting about two to three minutes with postictal phase.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and well organized for age. There is a 10 Hz, 40 (phi)V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is waxing and waning in appearance. It is well attenuated with eyes opened, and there is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not provoke an abnormal response. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved in this tracing. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR: 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or sleep deprivation prior to the EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 34-year-old woman with epilepsy for 15 years, last seizure December 2005.  Patient ran out of medicine two to three weeks ago, presented with a tonic-clonic seizure and tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital, Dilantin, Reglan, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background, as well as some rhythmic slowing.  Following hyperventilation, there are rare occasions where there is subtle, asymmetric 3 to 4 Hz activity identified from the right hemisphere, particularly in the centroparietal and temporal regions.  Features of stage II sleep include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.
LAMBDA waves are identified in wakefulness.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Subtle focal slowing from the right hemisphere with rhythmic low voltage delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These features may be correlated with imaging.  No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.Subtle focal slowing from the right hemisphere with rhythmic low voltage delta.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 yr old male with diabetes, hypertension with 3 episodes of aphasia, facial
twisting, drooling, disorientation. Left subdural hematoma.
MEDICATION: Tegretol.
ACTIVATION: Photic Stimulation and Hyperventilation.
INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is somewhat drowsy and
in drowsiness, there is intermittent delta from the left temporal region with delta ranging from 50-100 uV, at times sharply contoured. When the patient awakens however, the delta essentially
disappears however, features of drowsiness with slow eye movements are remarkable for the
subtly emergence of the same focal delta. Lateral wicket activity is identified from both temporal
regions. Stage I sleep is identified from both temporal regions. Stage I sleep is characterized by
vertex waves and spindles. As the sleep record continues, there is some subtle asymmetry in
terms of the amplitude of the sleep record and as the patient emerges from sleep again, the left
temporal delta is identified. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR: 66BPM
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent left temporal delta
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the
left. Although there was temporal wicket activity, there was no definite epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent left temporal delta

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 64-year-old male with diabetes, hypertension, and
episodes of aphasia and drooling. Abnormal EEG and abnormal MRI. Patient reports no
episodes since last month.
MEDICATIONS: Diabetes medicine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Previous EEGs were
performed, but are not available for comparison. This is an awake and drowsy record
with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior
dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. As the
patient becomes drowsy, prominent temporal wicket is seen from the right or left
temporal region. Underlying the wicket on the left is occasional left mid-temporal focal
delta. Other features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta. In stage I
sleep, vertex waves are seen, and in stage II sleep vertex waves and K complexes are
identified. Photic stimulation elicits driving at faster flash frequencies.
HR: 70 BPM, with occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Left greater than right temporal slowing out of the anticipated range for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a non-specific finding, seen most commonly
with underlying cerebrovascular disease.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Left greater than right temporal slowing out of the anticipated range for age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 66-year-old male evaluated 9 September 2007 for generalized
seizures during sleep. Patient is awake for this event. History of diabetes, hypertension,
and 2 previous EEGs, one for episodes of aphasia and drooling in October 2005 and a
previous in September 2005 for a left subdural hematoma with recurrent episodes of
facial drooling, twisting, disorientation, and aphasia.
MEDICATIONS: Protonix, Asa, Insulin, Metformin, glipizide, Tegretol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 8 Hz alpha rhythm
identified bilaterally. There is arrhythmic delta activity identified in the left temporal
region, more significant than the right. There is wicket activity, but there is also clear
sharply contoured delta in that region. Hyperventilation was performed early in the
record, clearly accentuating sharply contoured delta in that region. Later in
hyperventilation bursts of rhythmic high amplitude generalized delta are observed.
As the patient becomes drowsy again sharply contoured delta is identified with a T3
maximum. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 65 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Sharply contoured delta in the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were observed in 2 previous EEGs but are
clearly more prominent today. While there are no definitive sharp waves, the sharply
contoured delta is quite prominent. No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Sharply contoured delta in the left temporal region.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the record.  There are some brief portions of the record when the patient is maximally awake where there is a very subtle abnormality with an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm on the left, which is subtly disrupted on the right.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the asymmetry is not quite so prominent and there is rhythmic background slowing and occasional vertex waves.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  70 BPM.

Subtle asymmetries seen particularly in the initial portions of the record with subtle disruption of the alpha on the right compared to the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old male undergoing a left carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS: Desflurane, Propofol, Etomidate, Lidocaine, Synephrine, Fentanyl, Versed, and Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the OR using standard CEA montage with one channel of EKG. The recording begins at 8:20 AM and concludes at 12:17 PM.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is in the OR.  He may have been sedated, but induction has not occurred.  There is a 7 to 8 Hz background at 8:24:39 and an anesthetic pattern with the appearance of rhythmic frontal delta and some triangular-shaped waves in the posterior region.  Following the induction of anesthesia, the EEG is slightly discontinuous, but there is no significant focality.  The discontinuity waxes and wanes and is at times subtle.  Heparin is given at 10:15, and the initial clamp is placed at 11:01.  The EEG becomes somewhat discontinuous at 11:02.  These findings are communicated to the surgeon who requests a shunt.  In the discontinuous pattern, there is also a bit of shifting asymmetry.  In addition, there is some slowing identified out of the left prior to placement of the shunt.  The shunt is opened at 11:05.  In addition, as the shunt is placed, there seems to have been a change in the level of anesthesia and in this low voltage pattern, there is more faster frequency activity.  The EEG returns to baseline by 11:06.  The clamp is removed and reclamped at 11:55, 12:01.  Patency is confirmed by doppler at 12:02.  Throughout the procedure, with the clamping  and unclamping, there is some waxing and waning with at times a bit more slowing on the left or the right and also some subtle discontinuity.
By the close of the recording at 12:17, there is some shifting asymmetries, with some head-rocking movements but a question of a bit more slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for:
An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries.
Transient focal slowing from the left and discontinuity with placement of the clamp; alleviated by shunt.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: EEG monitoring during this carotid endarterectomy was remarkable for An abnormal baseline with shifting asymmetries

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy.  Family says she has not been taking her medicines, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by head turning to the left and posturing.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient was postictal, wearing a face mask and poorly cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is abnormal and at times, partially obscured by muscle and movement artifact.  The overall background is slow.  Superimposed upon this, there is an asymmetry with more arrhythmic delta activity and disruption of faster frequency activity on the right relative to the left.  There are bursts of irregular theta delta with underlying sharp waves noted from the right hemisphere.  The irregular epileptiform activity demonstrates variable maximum, but is typically maximum in the right posterior quadrant or T4, P4T6.  In addition, there is handful of bursts of more right frontotemporal rhythmic slowing and a handful of lower voltage discrete F8 sharp waves.
Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle and movement.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region.
Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient's previous baseline EEG on long-term monitoring are not available at this time for comparison.  This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  EEG monitoring will continue.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Background slowing and disorganization. Superimposed focal slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly right temporal region. Irregular epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere particularly posterior quadrant, but at some points more anteriorly, anterior frontotemporal pathology.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 40-year-old woman with epilepsy following a craniotomy for aneurysm.  Hypertension and depression.  Last seizure one month ago.
MEDICATIONS: Wellbutrin, Zoloft, Abilify, morphine, methadone, Dilantin, and HCTZ.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. The patient’s previous EEGs were not available at this time.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is intermittent rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere.  Although there is a breach rhythm, and there is some muscle artifact, there appears to be an underlying spike and slow wave complex identified from the left mid-temporal region, accentuated by hyperventilation.  Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes drowsy and in drowsiness there are vertex waves and POSTS.  The amplitude is somewhat higher from the left than the right, accentuating the POSTS on the left.  As the patient reaches sleep, in this sharply contoured background, there is both accentuation of beta on the left but there are a handful of sharp waves that also come out of this background.  Snore artifact is also identified in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, which is markedly accentuated on the left.
HR:  54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation.
Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prominent breach rhythm accentuates the beta activity in stage II sleep and produces an increase in the amplitude of the background in photic stimulation, but is simply a manifestation of the previous craniotomy.  The focal slowing and sharp waves supports a temporal lobe disturbance and a localization-related mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal theta accentuated by drowsiness and hyperventilation. Left temporal sharp waves in hyperventilation and in stage II sleep.  The morphology is compatible with a breach rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old left handed woman with history of seizures, now admitted after multiple recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term monitoring, 6 hours EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  Wakefulness and sleep were recorded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  After 10:00 at night until 6:00 in the morning from November 6 to November 7, 2011 there was marked muscle and multielectrode artifact to almost impossible reading the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record at the beginning opens to a diffusely slow low amplitude recording with no clear posterior dominant rhythm.  By 2 hours into the recording faster frequencies can be seen and improvement of the EEG to baseline was seen.  At best the posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta seen.  Some sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Occasional bursts of polyspike and generalized spike and waves seen at 4.5 to 5 Hz with anterior predominance  symmetrically over both hemispheres.  None of the bursts last more than 1 second.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz and 20-60 mV amplitude.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized spikes and waves.
Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG findings are consistent with those of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In this patient it is likely due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized spikes and waves. Polyspikes and excessive theta in wakefulness.

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20

EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is

No epileptiform activity is present.

None

Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.

A heart rate of 48 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and early drowsy routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events

CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and early drowsy  routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

Bradycardia is noted on a single EKG lead.

IMPRESSION

reported or detected.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old, right-handed woman with absence and tonic-clonic epilepsy, seizure-free for two years.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol and Celontin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record. No previous records are available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for age with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background and accentuating the alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 60-year-old woman with absence epilepsy and tonic­ clonic  seizures.  No  tonic-clonic   seizures  for  the  last   three   years,  but  currently experiencing petit absence attacks.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and exquisitely accentuates brief bursts of 4 to 5.5 Hz spike and wave activity. The activity is not sustained, however, in HV the patient reports feeling "a little twitchy" even with a handful of discharges. The longest duration of discharges is four seconds and is at the end of HV, as the patient is becoming drowsy and testing is not performed. There is also a pair of sharp and slow wave complexes identified in the left with similar morphology, but with  a bit of localization.    Drowsiness also seems to accentuate the generalized epileptiform  activity.   Photic stimulation does not produce spike and wave activity.
HR:  72BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Previous EEGs were not available at tills time for comparison.  A sample of the epileptiform activity was printed out and should have been provided with this report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old male with epilepsy since age five with
mental retardation. Last seizure two weeks ago with loss of consciousness and postictal
confusion for 15 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was
performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior
dominant rhythm. Central MU activity is seen independently from each side, but testing
is not performed to confirm this. In apparent wakefulness, there is intermittent rhythmic
theta activity identified in the midline at the frontocentral region, but a little bit more to
the right than the left. · Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic background
slowing. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 66BPM.
IMPRESSION: This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Infrequent theta from the frontocentral regions, right greater than left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
These findings may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Infrequent theta from the frontocentral regions, right greater than left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29 year-old, right handed male with a seizure in November during sleep. Follow-up EEG requested, but no previous EEG is available.
MEDICATIONS: Protonix, thiamin, Depakote, and Tranxene.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a symmetric, reactive alpha rhythm. Central MU activity is seen, but testing is not performed to confirm this. Drowsiness and sleep are characterized by fluctuations between a drowsy and sleep pattern with persistence of eye movements into stage II sleep and very brief fragments of stage II sleep with spindles followed by arousal. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not significantly activate the record. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 60BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
The fragmented sleep described above is reported in many different conditions and could include something as simple as a noisy background or a somewhat sleep deprived individual.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This 30-year-old right-handed male with learning
disability and a recurrent epilepsy in adulthood. Recurrent seizures
in adulthood with a childhood history of epilepsy, currently seizure
free for the last 3 months.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol 200 mg twice daily.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using
standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness background EEG is well
organized. There is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of 30 microvolts
with small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Lambda
waves are observed in wakefulness. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous
bilateral driving. Features of drowsiness slow rolling eye movements
and an attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation does not
significantly activate the rhythm. In photic stimulation there is
vigorous driving. The patient appears to be awake during photic
stimulation with eye movement, but there also seems to be a vertex
sharp wave, sometimes seen prior to or following the photic
stimulation. Additional testing is not performed upon the photic
stimulation to make sure that the patient is not becoming drowsy. He
has eye movements to suggest that he is awake, and once the photic has
concluded this vertex sharp wave is not observed at another time.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. The presence of a vertex sharp wave during photic stimulation in
wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This is a very unusual finding. It may be
correlated with imaging. This contrast to a previous study which was
normal.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. The presence of a vertex sharp wave during photic stimulation in
wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 47-year-old male with a history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures – last seizure about one year ago.  History of drug and alcohol abuse.  Patient was hospitalized for one week in a coma.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra and Carbatrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is remarkable for continuous eye blink artifact with absence of the alpha rhythm as a result of same.  There is a suggestion of a posterior dominant rhythm, but again measurement of the alpha frequency could not be obtained due to the eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG with continuous eye blinking artifact.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The absent alpha rhythm is to be expected secondary to the continuous eye blink artifact, which can be seen in an anxious or nervous individual.  To further evaluate this patient’s epilepsy, a repeat EEG with sleep recording could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG with continuous eye blinking artifact.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old left handed male with a past history of epilepsy,
thought to be seizure-free since 2005 but now with episodes of incontinence.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Carbatrol.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was completed.


DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is very low voltage and includes primarily a lower voltage 5 Hz to 6 Hz beta frequency pattern with
scant amounts of delta in drowsiness and scant amounts of alpha frequency activity.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response which can be identified using the
software.


HR: 60bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Low voltage theta pattern.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous study from 2006,
with a low voltage pattern with prominent eye blink. The ability to identify the theta in the background may be due to the use of newer technologies. No epileptiform features
were seen in the last 2EEGs. Consideration for a diffuse disturbance of cerebral
function is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Low voltage theta pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old left handed male with epilepsy, mental retardation admitted today with status epilepticus. Last evaluation for epilepsy 10/28/2010, for episodic incontinence. Seizures characterized by incontinence, gazing to the left, twitching and contraction of the arms, history of anoxic brain injury and hepatitis-C.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Tegretol, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a low voltage, relatively featureless pattern. There is theta frequency activity and smaller amounts of beta activity. This very low voltage record is a little more featureless in the right hemisphere compared to the left. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity. There is some spontaneous eye movement artifact. The patient is examined during the EEG which does little to activate the record. This very low voltage record also includes a bit of shifting arrhythmic delta activity and despite some artifact and some shifting slowing in the right frontocentral region.
HR: 66 to 72 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
I. Low voltage pattern with a mixture of beta, theta and some delta
2. Shifting asymmetries with an amplitude asymmetry with somewhat higher amplitude activity on the right compared to the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, this is similar to a previous study from the prior year with a low voltage pattern and theta. The asymmetries described above are of unclear clinical significance in this critical care bedside recording and additional evaluation may be helpful to more completely evaluate epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to I. Low voltage pattern with a mixture of beta, theta and some delta
2. Shifting asymmetries with an amplitude asymmetry with somewhat higher amplitude activity on the right compared to the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old left handed man with history of peri-stroke, anoxic injury, seizures, hepatitis C, who presents with increased change in mental status and EEG to rule out subclinical seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox, Lorazepam
REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out subclinical seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and EKG electrodes.  The patient was mainly lethargic during this study and some sleep was recorded.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There is a small amount of T4 electrode artifact continuously throughout the recording period.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a low voltage diffusely slow background with no clear posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  Some waves forms are consistent with stage I sleep were seen, but no classic sleep architecture is clearly present.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz seen continuously.  At one point during the EEG there is stimulation and there is an increased amount of muscle artifact and frequencies improved to a theta frequency.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed male with prior EEGs, presents with status in the past and hypoxic injury as well as history of CVA, hep C, cirrhosis, and TBI who now is having myoclonic jerks.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ceftriaxone, Vancomycin, Zosyn, Heparin

REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures; patient having myoclonic jerks.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was unresponsive during the EEG.  No activating procedures were performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:   None

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 30 microvolts.  There is no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There appears to be no clear reactivity.  During the recorded video, there appears to be some sudden jerks with the typical appearance of myoclonus; however, the EEG did not reveal any clear correlate.  No normal sleep architecture was seen.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 30 microvolts.

SEIZURES:   None

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized slow waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the myoclonus observed during the video had no EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized slow waves.

report:

REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures.

No activating procedures were performed. During the recording the technician tries to involve the patient with verbal stimuli, as well as noxious stimuli, and ocular pressures, however, there is no change in the EEG pattern.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 1-2 Hz with an amplitude of around 10 mV seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked generalized slow waves.
Low amplitude.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Marked generalized slow waves. Low amplitude.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed man with history of seizures, presents with possible status epilepticus with past medical history of stroke, hepatitis C cirrhosis, traumatic brain injury, now with EEG for myoclonus versus seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Albuterol, Ipratropium, Dopamine, Ceftriaxone, Pantoprazole, Versed, Fentanyl.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures, now with myoclonic jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with addition of an anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.   The patient was recorded in wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  The patient did not appear to go into normal sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with low-amplitude 20-30 mV seen continuously.
Throughout the recording, there is low-amplitude sharply contoured periodic discharges seen maximally at CZ occurring about 1 Hz with no clear clinical correlate, most consistent with CZ sharp waves and periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges.
SEIZURES:  None.
Of note, during the recording, the technician did stimulate the patient, and the patient appeared to be eye fluttering and moving rhythmically, but there is no EEG correlate to this eye movement seen or fluttering of the eyes.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Central PLEDs.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability in the central region which may be due to an underlying lesion or focus of irritation.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to utility.  No seizures were clearly seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves. Central PLEDs.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 78-year-old male with episodes of syncope and presyncope with a vasovagal episode in the bathroom associated with a small right cortical hemorrhage, followed a day later by a left posteriotemporal intraparenchymal hemorrhage.
MEDICATIONS: Flomax, Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  The overall background includes excess background theta.  There is intermittent arrhythmic delta activity seen from the temporal regions more prominent from the left posterior temporal region, but seen occasionally on the right.  There are rare left temporal sharp waves seen in wakefulness.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:

wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  Additionally, faster frequencies at higher amplitudes are

captured.  During sleep they increase in frequency and become frequent.

Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, right temporal, mid, mild-to-moderate
Breach artifact, bilateral, frontocentral
Sharp waves, frequent, right, midtemporal/ central, seen during sleep
Interpretation:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG  is performed  in the lab using  standard  10-20 system of electrode  placement  with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation  and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE   RECORD: In wakefulness, the background  EEG  is low voltage with a discernable 9.5 Hz, 20 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is prominent early delta and there is some shifting asymmetries noted in the background.
Occasional frontal delta is identified, as is some arrhythmic delta from the right more so than the left.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 96 BPM, occasional PVCs.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1.  Occasional frontal slowing.
2.   Occasional shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record. The low voltage pattern is not uncommon in an adult of this age.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1.  Occasional frontal slowing. 2.   Occasional shifting slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with two first-ever seizures occurring during sleep with postictal confusion, but no incontinence.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for an adult of this age with a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.
Towards the close of the record, as the patient is in stage II sleep and photic stimulation begins, there is some artifact but there are also some pairs of suspicious underlying left centrotemporal sharp waves of low amplitude and discrete, but appear to be interrupting the background.  The patient otherwise remains in stage II sleep during photic. Low voltage left temporal sharp waves are seen only in this section of the record, and almost seem to have an electropositivity between T3 and F7, but do appear to have otherwise a clear field in the left centrotemporal and posteriotemporal regions.
HR:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording with special electrodes or special techniques may be helpful to more clearly evaluate the underlying dipole that produces this activity and to be more certain that it is not artifactual in nature.  Correlation with imaging may also be valuable for this adult with new onset seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Unusual but abnormal EEG due to 1.Suspicious left temporal sharp waves.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with epilepsy since age 17 with recurrent seizures one year ago, but none recalled by the patient for the last year.  He has been living in a nursing home.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At that time, a low voltage 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm is identified bilaterally.  Despite movement artifact, there is a glimpse of a left mid-to-anterior temporal region in HV.  This is followed by a drowsy pattern at which point there is some subtle focal slowing discernable in the left anteriotemporal region.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, he begins to snore, again producing a fair amount of artifact.  Other features of sleep include some vertex activity.   In sleep, well-defined left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are identified.  The patient remains asleep during photic stimulation, with features of stage II sleep and spindles, but no clear driving.  In this sleep state, during HV, the left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complexes are better defined and then the patient briefly awakens towards the end of HV.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity.
Left anteriotemporal focal slowing.
Low voltage, somewhat slow background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the technical challenges described above, this EEG is similar to a previous record with focal temporal epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave activity. Left anteriotemporal focal slowing. Low voltage, somewhat slow background.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old right handed male with epilepsy, sepsis, pneumonia, depression, anorexia, chronic nursing home resident. Past history of childhood epilepsy and C-spine injury.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Acetaminophen, Avodart, Baclofen, Citracal, Depakote, Lasix, Niaspan

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is completed. The patient is recorded in a somewhat stiff position. Wakefulness and sleep are identified.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes limited wakefulness but in wakefulness there is a low voltage, 10 Hertz alpha rhythm. Much of the record includes drowsiness with at times rhythmic slowing from the left frontocentral region in wakefulness. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic bilateral slowing and then some vertex waves. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR: 60bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic left frontotemporal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Epileptiform activity is less prominent in this EEG than seen in previous but previous EEGs have identified a left temporal focus with the characteristic rhythmic temporal slowing described above. Other studies identified sharp waves.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Rhythmic left frontotemporal slowing.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital, Depakote, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with electrode impedances below 5 kilo-ohms with the exception of 1 electrode at 5.1.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage.  There was a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta followed by a rhythmic central theta.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate:  54 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Electroencephalogram within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Previous EEGs demonstrated L focal slowing and anterior temporal sharp waves.  In this seizure free older adult, there is no background slowing or epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Electroencephalogram within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness for an adult of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 26-year-old woman with cerebral palsy with epilepsy since infancy.  Last seizure in 2003 characterized by stomach pain followed by mouth twisting to the right without loss of consciousness, but with some drowsiness afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol and Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is remarkable for an intrahemispheric asymmetry with a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm on the right, sometimes disrupted on the left.  In addition, in the right hemisphere, there is low voltage frontocentral mixed theta and delta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude from the left, as well as one or two bursts of generalized paroxysmal slowing.
Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR:  92 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This EEG supports a structural abnormality on the right involving both gray and white matter.  Comparison with previous studies may be valuable in terms of the search for epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
History:	34 year old female with history of seizures since childhood.  She reportedly had at
least 2 seizures in the last week.
Medications:	Hydrochlorothiazide, Tegretol, zoloft, Ambien
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that
attenuates with eye opening.  PDR is better formed and modulated over the left.  There is an
anterior-to-posterior frequency-amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes
anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely,
followed by symmetric vertex waves.
There is continuous interhemispheric voltage asymmetry with lower voltages over the right.
Additionally, there is paucity of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere, especially over the
anterior and median quadrants.  Semi-rhythmic sharply contoured delta activity at 1-1.25 Hz is
observed over the right frontotemporal region during and following hyperventilation.  Occasional
right frontotemporal sharp waves are noted.  Maximal scalp negativity occurs over F8, T2, Fp2 and
F4 electrodes.  These discharges become more apparent during photic stimulation.  No clear
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) produces semi-rhythmic sharply
contoured right frontotemporal delta activity and accentuates right frontotemporal sharp waves.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, right hemispheric, mild-to-moderate, especially over
Attenuation, continuous, mild, right hemispheric
Sharp waves, occasional, right frontotemporal, accentuated by photic stimulation
Other, right frontotemporal, focal semi-rhythmic delta is seen with photic stimulation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 24-minute EEG due to mild-to-moderate right
hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the anterior and middle quadrants and occasional
right frontotemporal epileptiform discharges. Focal slowing and voltage attenuation over the right
is suggestive of focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.  A potential epileptogenic
focus emanates from the right frontotemporal region.  Given accentuation of epileptiform
discharges and focal slowing with photic stimulation, this EEG is suggestive of photosensitive
seizures.  Please correlate clinically electrographic seizures are captured.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 24-minute EEG due to mild-to-moderate right

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a __-year-old woman with tonic-clonic seizures with postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is very sleepy throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta.  The patient has some eye movement artifact in stage I sleep, some of which is picked up in the temporal regions, but there is no definite epileptiform activity seen.  As the patient reaches deeper stages of sleep with vertex waves, no epileptiform activity is identified.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting into stage I and II sleep, and does not activate the record.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Eye movements into sleep are of unclear clinical significance.  If further information is needed to characterize this patient’s seizures, additional EEG recording may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:

MEDICATION:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient had experienced a seizure 40 minutes prior to the EEG and was quite confused.  This is a technically satisfactory record aside from slightly increased impedance in the T1 and T2 electrodes.  Digital video EEG is performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is initially postictal and confused.  She has a little difficulty cooperating with the test and some head rocking movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The initial sections of the record demonstrate a low voltage, slow record with some head rocking artifact.  A posterior dominant rhythm of 6.5 Hz was noted.  Hyperventilation was attempted.  This served to alert the patient.  Following this, the patient drift off to sleep with low voltage vertex waves.  Occasional snore artifact was noted.
Heart rate:  72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are identified.  The background slowing is an anticipated finding for an acutely postictal patient.  No epileptiform features were seen in this EEG or in this patient's 2 previous EEGs earlier this year.
__________________________
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman followed at [Hospital] with the diagnosis of epilepsy and three tonic-clonic seizures per month, all occurring out of sleep.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is some single electrode artifact picked up in the right frontotemporal electrodes, but there is an abnormality identified in this EEG identifiable after the electrodes are attended to. This includes rhythmic focal slowing from the right temporal regions, which is at times sustained and sharply contoured at the end of HV and early drowsiness.  In addition, using bipolar and average reference electrodes, there are two pairs of subtle frontotemporal sharp waves.  One has generous representation at Fp2, F4, and T4, as well as F8 and T4.  The other is clearly F8 and T4.  Other features of drowsiness include vertex waves and an increase in background beta.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for eliciting an alerting response and some driving bilaterally.  The patient is drifting in and out of stage II sleep in photic stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Right temporal focal slowing clearly accentuated by hyperventilation.
Subtle underlying pairs of right frontotemporal/frontocentral sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy and may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Right temporal focal slowing clearly accentuated by hyperventilation. Subtle underlying pairs of right frontotemporal/frontocentral sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male with status epilepticus earlier this morning status post 10 mg of Ativan, Dilantin, and Keppra. History of cervical myelopathy. Intubated and paralyzed prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Etomidate, Fentanyl, Versed, ROCURONIUM
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is starting to emerge from paralysis and demonstrates stiffening and movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is a bit quieter. Activity demonstrates a slow pattern with some rhythmic mixed theta and delta on the left with a lower voltage, slower, a bit more suppressed pattern on the right, particularly in the temporal regions.
Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle as well as alpha and theta frequency activity. During the EEG, the patient starts to wake up, move around, and cough. After this, there is a more alert pattern with more theta frequency and alpha frequency activity from the left, but the right remains quite slow. By the end of the record in this very sharply contoured record, there was a suggestion of underlying sharp activity versus part of the fast activity at F3. In addition, more sharply contoured slowing is seen at T4-T6.
HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere.
2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function as would be expected following the use of sedative, hypnotic medications. The focal slowing and rare sharp waves on the right are compatible with past right temporal hemorrhage. Additional evaluation of this patient's cerebral function may be needed. Ongoing EEG monitoring was undertaken to make sure no additional seizures occurred.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere. 2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male admitted with 4 seizures, alcohol abuse, past history of intracerebral hemorrhage, hepatitis C, stroke, and hypertension.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Tylenol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm identified on the left. Faster frequency activity is attenuated on the right. The patient is conversant with the tech. This patient has an event during the EEG. The event occurs at 10:08 a.m. It is characterized by staring, jerking of the head from side to side. The EEG is remarkable for some sharp waves and some motion artifacts. The sharp waves are seen in the right frontocentral region. There is significant muscle activity. The patient is conversant during the spell. No postictal slowing is noted. Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response on the left.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing from the right.
2. An event during the EEG without impairment of awareness. Although there is some artifact, there are some discharges in the same region as the patient's sharp waves. While the event might not be considered a simple partial or a complex partial seizure, the motor activity observed may be linked to the epileptiform activity elicited from the right frontocentral region which could have produced the features described above.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing from the right

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old, right-handed woman with COPD and epilepsy starting two years ago. Last seizure three weeks ago characterized by numbness and shaking lasting for five to ten minutes.  No previous EEGs were available.
MEDICATIONS: Patient does not recall.
