DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is markedly sharply contoured with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with prominent temporal wicket seen from either region.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a prominent increase in theta frequency activity.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is attempted, but the patient has drifted back into stage II sleep.   Occasional snore arousals are noted in the background.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is a very sharply contoured background and a great deal of temporal wicket, but no definite epileptiform activity.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old female with epilepsy and dizziness.  No other information is available.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, and Buspirone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient has an event during the EEG. Hyperventilation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Although the patient is markedly drowsy throughout much of the record, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and theta.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At the end of hyperventilation, the patient has a single episode of both shoulders jerking at 11:37:07.  Slowly, at 11:53, she starts to have rocking of the head from side to side and then has rocking from side to side with alternating movements of the hands, with hands coming up and going down and then head rocking from side to side.  During this event, although there is some movement artifact, the EEG otherwise demonstrates an awake pattern.  The technologist interacts with the patient during the event giving her a code word.  The patient has multiple different behaviors during this episode including brief hyperextension of the back and then slow rocking from side to side.
Towards the end of the behavior, the tech uses a nasal tickle.  The patient looks apprehensive and at one point turns away just briefly, but doesn’t move substantially.  She does blink to threat during the event, and towards the end of the event, seems upset or angry and is staring away from the direction of the technologist.  As the technologist moves around the room, however, the patient can be seen to track the tech with her eyes.  After the event is over, the patient tells the tech that the only thing she can remember is that her name is [patient’s name].
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although the patient was initially quite drowsy, there is no epileptiform activity.  This patient had a complex and prolonged behavioral event without EEG change.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:

record.  In comparison to a previous record, both studies show normal cerebral activity, but no behavioral events were recorded today.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old woman with a learning disability and increasing seizures with two to three seizures per day, most recent seizure 6/20/06. Increasing frequency of seizures, which may be behavioral in nature.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage with a 12 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is a well-organized, low voltage pattern with a clearly defined posterior dominant rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in low voltage, frontocentral theta and a small amount of delta.   Towards the close of hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is just a small amount of shifting arrhythmic slowing in the posterior temporal regions, slightly more so on the right compared to the left.  Features of sleep include vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Rare bursts of shifting slowing in the posteriotemporal regions in the transition from hyperventilation to sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The overall background is identical to a previous study done one year ago.  Of note, neither EEGs have demonstrated epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to Rare bursts of shifting slowing in the posteriotemporal regions in the transition from hyperventilation to sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  36 year old right handed woman with mental retardation, complex partial epilepsy, and gingival hyperplasia, seizure-free for the last 3 years.  This is the patient's third EEG.

MEDICATIONS:  Famotidine, Keppra.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is primarily a sleep EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low-voltage EEG but symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is abundant stage II sleep with K-complexes, spindles, posts, and vertex waves.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.

HR:    72 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third normal EEG for this individual who has been seizure-free for the last 4 years.  Of note, she was previously evaluated for staring spells.  If these behaviors recur and are thought to be seizures, an ambulatory EEG recording could be considered at that time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old male with epilepsy since age 4 following MVA.  Last seizure three to four years ago with postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  In wakefulness and in hyperventilation, there is subtle underlying slowing with initially some arrhythmic delta activity seen from the right hemisphere, sometimes with disruption of the alpha rhythm. As HV continues, some shifting slowing is seen.  Features of drowsiness include a decrease in eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle underlying arrhythmic slowing, a bit more prominent from the right particularly in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If characterization of underlying spike and slow wave activity is important, a repeat tracing capturing sleep may be helpful.  This EEG supports a process, perhaps involving the right hemisphere more than the left, but there is some shifting features to suggest that both hemispheres may have been impacted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to Subtle underlying arrhythmic slowing, a bit more prominent from the right particularly in hyperventilation.

report:

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL No focal nor epileptiform features were observed. This
slow frequency artifacts described above a unclear significance for this individual who is
recorded on an extremely hot and humid day.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year old with post traumatic epilepsy at the age of 4,
currently seizure free for the last 11 years.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, background EEG is well organized.
There is a 10-Hertz, symmetric posterior dominant rhythm. Central MU rhythm is
observed but testing is not performed to confirm this. There is no mention of a
craniotomy but there seems to be both a little bit of head rocking artifact in left temporal
region and hyperventilation with no definitive focal slowing. Features of drowsiness
included an increase in background beta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL In the absence of a description of a craniotomy, the
amplitude, asymmetry and the head rocking artifact merit further evaluation but may
well be due to previous cranial defect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 69-year-old male with a right carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation is not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10.5 Hz, 30 to 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing, as well as occasional slow rolling eye movements. Beta spindles are seen in stage II sleep with multiple spontaneous arousals from sleep.  POSTS are often noted.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient demonstrates some normal variance in the transition to sleep, which are of no pathological significance.  In this individual about to undergo a carotid endarterectomy, no epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 69-year-old male with a carotid endarterectomy in July 2006.  Patient had one episode of loss of consciousness followed by an MVA.  Evaluate for encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and possibly drowsy record. Previous EEG is not available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow with a 7 to 8 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There is intermittent arrhythmic delta seen in the background with some shifting asymmetries.  Drowsiness is difficult to define, but the patient is clearly interactive with his examiners.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild background slowing.
Shifting arrhythmic delta in apparent wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  The arrhythmic delta activity is a non-specific finding and may be correlated with imaging and toxic or metabolic factors.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild background slowing. Shifting arrhythmic delta in apparent wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This is a 70-year-old right-handed male with history of left carotid stenosis and right carotid endarterectomy in July 2006. He is status post open heart surgery and MI.
MEDICATIONS: 	Include Plavix, metformin and others.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using a 10-
20 electrode system placement and 1 lead of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, background EEG is adequately organized. There is 10.5 	hertz posterior alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive. Intermittent focal slowing is identified in the left temporal region with both arrhythmic and rhythmic mixed beta and delta. A handful of sharp waves are observed as he becomes drowsy. Vertex waves are seen in transition to stage 2 sleep.
HR: 	80 BPM - Irregular. IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. 	Sharp waves in the left temporal area.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Consideration for a focal process is important. Sharp waves suggest that this could be an underlying seizure disorder.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing. 2. Sharp waves in the left temporal area.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old male with a one-year history of epilepsy; last seizure three weeks ago with foaming at the mouth. History of staring spells, generalized shaking lasting two to three minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.   This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well enough organized for age with a posterior dominant rhythm averaging 6 Hz, sometimes somewhat faster, reaching amplitudes up to 100 uV.  Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  Vertex waves are identified with brief sleep epochs and then spontaneous arousals. Hyperventilation produces rhythmic slowing.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Although there are multiple episodes of hypersynchronous rhythmic 5 Hz activity, the static can be re-reviewed and is without epileptiform activity and is simply characteristic of a prominent hypnagogic hypersynchrony.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording including capturing more extended sleep may be important to characterize this child’s epilepsy if previous EEGs have not done so.  Photic stimulation may also be employed.  In comparison to previous EEGs, this study was of better quality technically, but neither studies identified epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 5-year-old male with epilepsy admitted on the 16th after he fell down the stairs and had a convulsion and a laceration on his cheek lasting five minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  This is this child’s third EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 6.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  There are portions of the record when the child is awake when the background is appropriately organized for age.
The major abnormalities in this record include complex epileptiform activity, which can be best viewed at fast paper speed of six seconds per page and/or average reference.  These include spike and slow wave complexes, which are high in amplitude and sometimes seem almost electropositive in the mid-temporal region, but in most of the montages are maximum at C3.  They are variable with some having a much more generous field of spread to the frontocentral region or left hemisphere and others more restricted.  They are picked up by volume conduction in the contralateral hemisphere.  In addition, there are some generalized frontally predominant spike and slow wave discharges, some of which are 3.5 to 4 Hz, but which are slightly irregular.  As the child drifts off to sleep, marked background slowing is observed and prominent, high amplitude slow spike and wave complexes are identified.  These are picked up in the frontocentral region, but more so on the left.
As the child drifts off to sleep, he is lying on his side, away from the camera and towards his mother.  Initially, he seems to have jerking forward of the head.  Subsequently, he seems almost to be having a salaam-like seizure as he drifts off to sleep, jerking towards his mother with his arms coming up a little bit.  This seems to elicit an arousal from sleep.  The epileptiform activity is high in amplitude, but some sections of the sleep record seem to demonstrate a sleep pattern that is remarkable for prominent attenuation of the typical morphologies in sleep with this high amplitude spike and slow wave pathology, most prominent in the frontal regions and again with an unusual field but with more of a predominance to the left hemisphere.  The child does fall off to sleep at 12:51.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere.
Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings must be correlated with imaging and clinical exam at this juncture.  They differ from the two previous EEGs, which were not successful in identifying epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere. Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old, right-handed male admitted on July 3rd with multiple seizures at home with tongue biting and postictal confusion.  Seizures on the 4th in the hospital were tonic-clonic.  History of posttraumatic epilepsy since age 17.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital, Dilantin, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a mainly asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes sleep.  Stage II sleep is well organized with vertex waves and spindles.  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but there is occasionally some posterior delta seen bilaterally in wakefulness.  Hyperventilation elicits generalized background slowing, but again also some posterior rhythmic theta and delta.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively asleep and does not activate the record.
HR:  78 BPM, occasional APCs.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Posteriorly predominant HV response.
Although there is limited wakefulness, some posteriorly predominant rhythmic slowing is intermixed with what otherwise would be a relatively normal background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  To further characterize this patient’s epilepsy, a repeat study in the lab when the patient is a bit more consistently alert may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Posteriorly predominant HV response. Although there is limited wakefulness, some posteriorly predominant rhythmic slowing is intermixed with what otherwise would be a relatively normal background.

report:

MEDICATIONS:   Dilantin, Keppra, Simvastatin, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake through stage II sleep record in a very sleepy patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  The patient drops in and out of stage II sleep with high amplitude vertex waves and spindles and K complexes.  Some of the vertex activity is spiky.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and does not really activate the record although the patient drifts off to sleep.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, but the patient is falling into stage II sleep during photic stimulation.
HR: 	66 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed in today's EEG. To further characterize his epileptiform activity, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep or utilizing other techniques may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG

report:

MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is somnolent when allowed to rest and has significant snore artifact.  He is agitated when stimulated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm identified, which is of slightly higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.  In maximal wakefulness, there is excess beta, but there is also some bilateral irregular theta. Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort, and is associated with a drowsy pattern.  Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response, but the patient continues to rock throughout photic stimulation.
HR:  66 BPM.

Mild excess generalized rhythmic theta.
Shifting, somewhat irregular mixed theta and delta, slightly more remarkable on the left than the right.
Excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Overall, the features described above are more or less bilateral.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, additional testing when the patient is cooperative may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to Mild excess generalized rhythmic theta. Shifting, somewhat irregular mixed theta and delta, slightly more remarkable on the left than the right. Excess beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-month-old male who presents with status epilepticus for 25 minutes with eye deviating to the left with left-sided shaking followed by tonic-clonic seizure activity.  Patient is a 24-week preemie.  From birth to 8 months with multiple abdominal surgeries and other medical complications.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and steroids.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is intubated in the ICU.  His eyes are opened, and he has jittering movements in all extremities, upper more so than lower.  He startled to auditory stimulation.  As time goes on, the patient’s jittering type of movement calms down and there is some sucking artifact.  The background EEG is a high amplitude, chaotic pattern with delta activity of 1 to 2 Hz.
Vecuronium is given at 9:18, and afterwards the muscle artifact significantly decreases.  There is slower delta with a frequency of 0.6 to 1 Hz.  There is a brief portion of fast activity in the frontal regions.  This occurs after the Vecuronium is given and is not associated with a change in the patient’s behavior.  It picked up what appeared to be either eye leads or frontal electrodes.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background with slow delta.
Absence of the appropriate developmental milestones for a child of this age.
Frontal fast activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  This pattern can be seen following acute, severe seizures or in the context of severe disturbance of gray and white matter.  The frontal fast activity may be epileptiform in nature. Additional EEG recording may be valuable to support additional subclinical seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Markedly abnormal background with slow delta. Absence of the appropriate developmental milestones for a child of this age. Frontal fast activity.

report:
History:	38 year old man with a history of a prior anoxic brain injury and TBI.

Patient was uncooperative during the EEG lead placement.
Medications:	ATIVAN, DEPAKOTE, BACLOFEN, OTHERS
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low amplitude 12Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce any effect.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 22-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information

report:

'

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old woman with recent onset epilepsy and seizures, which often can be eliminated by the patient with reassurance.  The patient had six seizures after she ran out of her Effexor.  Patient had a spell immediately upon cessation of the EEG characterized by staring and blinking.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Effexor, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake.  There is a 9 to 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a fair amount of eye artifact.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and does elicit some left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes in association with hyperventilation. Following hyperventilation, the patient becomes somewhat drowsy and there is a small amount of slowing in the left mid-temporal region in this somewhat drowsy pattern.  There is also a high amplitude left anteriotemporal spike and slow wave complex.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a left anteriotemporal spike component, but this has a bifrontal field.  This activity can be reviewed with other montages where again it seems to be primarily left temporal with some spread into the eye movement channel.  It is prominent with almost a focal spike and wave component as the patient becomes drowsy and reaches stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is in stage II sleep and does not significantly activate the record.  The record ends at 13:45 and the seizure is not captured on the video or the EEG.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to:
Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features differ significantly from previous EEGs and suggests that additional recording and additional evaluation is warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for this individual due to Focal, high amplitude spike and slow wave activity identified from the left anteriotemporal region with almost a focal spike and wave component.

report:

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were noted in this record, but the patient also had no clinical seizures. Correlation with previous studies would be important, but epileptiform activity may be elusive in some individuals.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 67-year-old male with a brain tumor, dizziness, and shortness of breath.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, aspirin, insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  He has a flax meningioma and a likely right temporal meningioma.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The alpha rhythm is slightly higher amplitude on the left than the right.  There is generous background beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with a dramatic increase in beta and rare bursts of arrhythmic delta from the left.    Photic stimulation elicits scant driving, but becomes more vigorous at faster flash frequencies.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A subject of this age is permitted some rare left temporal slowing as identified above.  The amplitude asymmetry is not outside of the range of normal.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
:
History:	75 year old man with a history of seizures.  Patient was seizure-free until recently,
but in the last month he had 2 reported generalized convulsions.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low voltage 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is present.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity
is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates,
and bursts of ~5 Hz monomorphic sharply contoured diffuse stereotyped theta activity appears.  This
activity becomes more prominent as drowsiness deepens.  No clear stage II sleep architecture is
Frequent polymorphic theta and delta activity is noted over the right anterior temporal region,
increasing in frequency during drowsiness.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, frequent, right temporal, anterior, mild-to-moderate
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minute EEG due to frequent mild-to-moderate focal
slowing in the right anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral
dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 25-minute EEG due to frequent mild-to-moderate focal
slowing in the right anterior temporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral
dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
HISTORY:

77 y.o. male with a history of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:


ASCENSIA CONTOUR Strip,

glipizide (GLUCOTROL) 5 mg tablet,

LEVEMIR 100 unit/mL injection,


HUMALOG KWIKPEN 100 unit/mL Insulin Pen,

SURE COMFORT PEN NEEDLE 31 gauge x 5/16" Needle,

atorvastatin (LIPITOR) 40 mg tablet, Take 40 mg by mouth daily.


FOLIC ACID/MULTIVIT-MIN/LUTEIN (CENTRUM SILVER PO), Take  by mouth.

aspirin 81 mg chewable tablet, Take 81 mg by mouth daily.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.







SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




Diffuse excess beta activity is present.



During brief drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured


No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

No epileptiform activity is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.


Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:




There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of ~66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  Rare premature QRS complexes are seen.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This is a normal awake and briefly  drowsy  routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.



Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or
barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and briefly drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic
events reported or detected.

report:
﻿CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with epilepsy following head trauma at age six when he was run over by a car.  Patient seizure-free since age 13, now with twitching of the limbs lasting for 20 seconds.  Symptoms start and stop and then move up and down the limbs.  They are not associated with loss of consciousness.

MEDICATIONS:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is limited maximal wakefulness with a well-defined alpha rhythm.  The alpha frequency is 12 Hz, 30 to 50 uV and is slightly higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  Much of the record includes drowsiness or sleep with slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In the transition to sleep, there is a drowsy pattern with rhythmic theta, which is identified bilaterally and is symmetric.  There is a slight amplitude asymmetry on some occasions as slowing develops in the record, with again slightly higher amplitude slowing from the left compared to the right.  Vertex waves in stage I sleep are symmetric.  POSTS are identified bilaterally.

Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in background beta.  Notably, at baseline, the patient’s heart rate is 72 BPM and irregular.  In hyperventilation, the heart rate becomes more irregular, increasing to 96 BPM and is associated with the feeling of light-headedness and a twitchy feeling.  The twitchy feeling is identified at 13:51.  No epileptiform features are identified at that time, although there is an increase in background beta.

Photic stimulation elicits a driving response bilaterally.  The driving response is quite vigorous, but in the slower frequency flash stimuli, it is higher amplitude and more prominent from the left compared to the right.

HR:  72 BPM, irregular.

IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with a history of childhood head trauma, these findings should be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Given the presence of an alpha asymmetry and the amplitude asymmetry, as well as the photic asymmetry, this is a mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. The amplitude asymmetry comparing the left to the right and the slightly asymmetric photic stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with possible posttraumatic epilepsy.  Patient has episodes when he falls asleep with of a feeling of hearing his blood rushing to the head with severe dizziness and tachycardia.  Last episode was this morning.  Patient states that he if catches it, he can stop it.  History of head trauma at age 6 with seizures, with last seizure at age 13.  This patient did experience another episode, as was seen in a previous EEG, with the feeling of tachycardia.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. No clinical symptoms were reported during this EEG. The patient is known to have a right skull defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. In wakefulness, there is a small intrahemispheric asymmetry with accentuation of fast activity in the right frontocentral region compared to the left.  This is compatible with a breach rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  During hyperventilation, the background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an increase in the amplitude and a small increase in theta.  Notably, in hyperventilation, the heart rate increases from 70 to 90 BPM.  The patient reports experiencing the typical symptoms of one of his events.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response.  The patient’s breach rhythm is somewhat more prominent during photic.
HR:  70 to 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the breach rhythm, which is a manifestation of a previous skull defect, the amplitude asymmetries and the beta asymmetries are anticipated findings.  As was seen in a previous EEG, the patient again felt tachycardic during hyperventilation and again demonstrated an increase in heart rate.
Additional, neurocardiac monitoring may be helpful to further characterize his spells.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old male with hypothyroidism, benign prostatic hypertrophy, and carpal tunnel syndrome bilaterally who presents with an episode of syncope and inability to communicate several minutes afterwards, but is able to comprehend.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Cardura, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There is an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Throughout the record, there is unusual eye movement artifact, with very high amplitude eye artifact and somewhat asymmetric eye movements. These movements are lower amplitude on the right side, notably at the F8 lead.  The activity from the left temporal area also seems to be of greater amplitude.  There is also a suspicion of delta activity at F7 to T3.  Features of drowsiness include wicket activity, slow rolling eye movements, and an increase in beta.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.   Photic stimulation elicits minimal driving.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In view of the asymmetric eye movement artifact described above, this EEG should be repeated capturing stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to The presence of delta in the left frontotemporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old woman evaluated for speech arrest associated with syncope, prolonged, sleep-deprived video EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Cardura, aspirin, Synthroid.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  Previous EEGs are not available for comparison. This is a one-hour EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake with a symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing synchronous bursts of slowing seen primarily in the temporal regions.   Features of drowsiness include background slowing followed by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes in stage II sleep.  Wicket activity is seen in the transition to and from deeper stages of sleep.   Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  50 to 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Temporal wicket is a normal finding.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If this patient experiences additional events, additional recording capturing an event may be of use.  Please compare to prior EEGs
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 12-year-old male with new onset seizures on 07/24/06 with loss of consciousness and incontinence of urine.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG and two channels of muscle monitoring. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 10 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is attenuated with eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, which transiently increases the slow activity of theta in the frontocentral region and returns back to baseline within one minute in post-hyperventilation. Photic stimulation elicits driving.  Following photic stimulation, POSTS are seen indicating light sleep, but no abnormal discharges were identified.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The POSTS observed in this tracing is a normal variant.  The normal developmental milestones have been met. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 7-year-old female with uncontrolled tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient is crying.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow for a child of this age with rhythmic 3 to 5 Hz activity and a posterior dominant rhythm, which is more typically on the order of 3 Hz, as well as a bit more background slowing than one would expect.  There are rare, high amplitude left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes. Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous slowing.  At times, there are more subtle underlying sharp waves from the left centrotemporal region.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Background slowing.
Rare left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing is a non-specific finding and can be seen in a postictal state, although the child does appear awake and quite interactive.  The left frontocentral spike and slow wave activity is rare, but is high amplitude and well defined.  Correlation with imaging and clinical history may be valuable.  In addition, there is a suggestion of some underlying sharp activity from the left temporal region and ongoing evaluation of that potential underlying focus may also be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Background slowing. Rare left frontocentral spike and slow wave complexes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 76-year-old, right-handed male with cardiac disease and Amiodarone toxicity with acute tonic-clonic seizure, admitted 11/28/06.  EEG requested 12/03/06.  Date of seizure is unknown.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a dominant rhythm averaging 7.8 to 8.5 Hz with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is small amount of excess theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there are occasional bursts of rhythmic frontal slowing.  At times, the drowsy pattern is sharply contoured and disorganized.  Photic stimulation elicits minimal bilateral driving.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Intermittent disorganization and generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific.  In a subject of this age, this may be due to an underlying toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or postictal state.   No epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Intermittent disorganization and generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 70-year-old, right-handed woman with right facial twitching, right numbness, right shoulder pain, CAD, MI, and breast cancer.
MEDICATIONS: Zetia, aspirin, Toprol, Nexium, Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz alpha rhythm of 30 uV.  There is a great deal of muscle noted in the background, and the muscle persists as the patient becomes drowsy.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving. Of note, the patient starts to reach stage I sleep towards the end of photic stimulation.
HR:  55 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits, albeit a low voltage record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits, albeit a low voltage record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 73-year-old woman with facial twitch on the right. Past medical history revealed CAD, Ml, breast cancer, stents for heart x2 in 2008.
MEDICATIONS: Plavix, ASA, lisinopril, simvastatin and Zetia.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hypoventilation was not performed. Photic stimulation was combated. The is an awake through light sleepless record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is a symmetric continuous but superimposed on excessive amounts of movement artifact. As the tracing continues on when, muscle artifact is subside 10 Hz, 20 microvolts of posterior dominant alpha rhythm can be seen which is attenuated with the eyes open. There is excessive diffuse fast beta activity throughout the tracing. Sleeping is evidenced by increased slow activity on the background, spindles and K complexes. Photic stimulation did not create driving. No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.
Heart rate is 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep study. No focal findings. No abnormal and no epileptic discharges were seen in this tracing. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old woman with a history of abscesses, hepatitis C, hypertension, now being evaluated for aphasia, tremor, and stuttering.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet and methadone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  This patient demonstrates intermittent head rocking from side to side, which produces some artifact.  Photic stimulation seems to elicit this patient’s tendency to rock her head from side to side.  No significant driving response is seen.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The head rocking from side to side does not appear to be a seizure.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If additional recording is necessary to capture epileptiform activity, a sleep study may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old, right-handed woman with cerebellar degeneration, myoclonus, and hepatic cirrhosis with tremor, confusion, and encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Methylprednisolone, methadone, Fentanyl.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat poorly organized.  There is an 8 to 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm in a background with excess background theta.  There is a great deal of muscle and movement artifact and, in fact, the muscle is present even into sleep.  Underlying this, there is some intermittent arrhythmic delta activity sometimes sharply contoured in the left temporal region.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, but there remains a fair amount of muscle in sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort, but does seem to produce both generalized rhythmic frontal slowing, as well as accentuating some of the focal slowing from the left.  Photic stimulation elicits scant bilateral driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record, however, given the amount of muscle artifact noted in the background, if epileptiform activity is of importance, a repeat sleep record may be necessary.  No periodic changes were seen.  In this individual who was evaluated for Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, not all individuals demonstrate the characteristic pseudoperiodic findings initially and additional studies over a 12 week period may be necessary.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing and poor organization. Superimposed focal slowing from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 50-year-old woman with a history of herpes encephalitis and seizures starting in November 2004.  Last seizure was without loss of consciousness, but with staring for two minutes and bladder incontinence.

report:
History:	24 year old man who presents with events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	Versed this morning in the ED.
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, lethargic
Description:
During very brief wakefulness the background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm,
which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present,
maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-7Hz activity is present
during very brief wakefulness.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity,
frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes
intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Hyperventilation is not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL briefly awake and mostly asleep 23-minute portable EEG due to mild
diffuse slowing. This finding is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
nonspecific, but in this patient is at least partially secondary to excessive drowsiness.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL briefly awake and mostly asleep 23-minute portable EEG due to mild
diffuse slowing. This finding is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically
nonspecific, but in this patient is at least partially secondary to excessive drowsiness.  The lack of
epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

2.   Intermittent left temporal focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old woman status post meningioma resection in 2008.  The patient has been suffering from insomnia, had a seizure following the 4th of July with some alcohol ingestion.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, Ativan and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Technical criteria was satisfactory.  She has a breach rhythm in the right frontocentral region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Generous, frontocentral beta activity was noted.  A breach rhythm was noted in the right frontocentral region with accentuation of beta activity and some underlying, subtle focal delta.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the recording producing rhythmic frontal theta bilaterally.
Hyperventilation was followed by drowsiness with an increase in beta, particularly in the region with a breach and some shifting slowing primarily in the right central region.  Stage 2 sleep includes spindles, POSTS and some vertex waves and is a bit more symmetric.  The patient transitioned in and out of awake and drowsy state.  There is a bit of muscle or snoring artifact noted as well.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response, which was better developed on the left compared to the right.
Heart rate 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the right central region, noted primarily in drowsiness.
Asymmetric driving response.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are congruent with the previous right hemispheric resection.  The breach rhythm with the prominent accentuation of the beta activity is an anticipated finding, particularly for a patient receiving benzodiazepine.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing in the right central region, noted primarily in drowsiness. Asymmetric driving response.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old woman with recurrent meningioma, seizure-free since December 2013.

INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  The patient is noted to have a right frontal craniotomy defect.

Heart rate 78 bpm.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This was a 35-year-old, right handed female, health care worker with new onset of episodes of generalized shaking. The patient could feel her body shake at the beginning of the episodes. Afterwards, she felt quite drained and had diffuse body soreness. The patient's typical seizures involved head turning and body twisting to the right. The patient may experience black spots in her eyes before the spells.
MEDICATIONS: 	Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation  and photic stimulation were completed. The patient experienced one of her typical spells during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there was a generous amount of background beta and a small of background theta. Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record producing increase in theta.
Following hyperventilation,  the patient began to have an episode of eye fluttering. The eye flutter began at 11:10:17. This gradually moved on towards one of her typical spells. The spell began at 11:10:35. The patient arched her back, stiffened and demonstrated generalized shaking. The spell was over by 11:11:11 so the total duration was approximately 40 seconds. No post
ictal slowing was identified. The patient recalled that the tech asked her a word but did not recall what the word was. Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR: 84   BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
2. Mild excess theta.
. '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	The absence of an EEG signature as well as the absence of a post ictal state raised concerns that the behaviors recorded were not ictal in nature.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess beta. 2. Mild excess theta. . '
3. Behavioral event without clear EEG change and without post ictal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old male with post-traumatic epilepsy with last seizure three weeks ago.  No previous EEGs.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There are intermittent bursts of 4 to 5 Hz activity identified from the right frontal region, which are high in amplitude with some volume conduction to the left, but clearly maximum on the right.  There is also intermittent rhythmic 6 to 7 Hz theta activity identified from the frontal regions.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude synchronous slowing, which is sharply contoured but without definitive localization.  There are more subtle discharges identified in hyperventilation, sharply contoured, with after going slow waves, again maximum primarily in the right frontal region.
Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background slowing followed by vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS.  Stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.  The patient seems to be falling asleep during photic stimulation.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Right frontal, 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity.
Intermittent, hypersynchronous rhythmic theta from the frontal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing suggests a localization-related mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy.   Correlation with imaging may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Right frontal, 4 to 5 Hz spike and slow wave activity. Intermittent, hypersynchronous rhythmic theta from the frontal regions.

report:
History:	58 year old woman with a reported history of seizures since -1985. Medications:	Topamax
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Background voltages are low.  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low voltage beta activity that attenuates with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV,  18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  The majority of the background consists of low amplitude diffuse beta activity.   During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.   During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.   Frequent positive sharp waves occur bilaterally and independently in the occipital regions during drowsiness  and light sleep.
Occasional low voltage sharp waves are seen over the left fronto-temporal region (Fp1/F7/F3). A benign variant (BETS, benign epileptiform transients of sleep) cannot entirely be excluded.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates. A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate 54 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Sharp waves, occasional, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population

report:

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Thiamine, Zocor, Lovenox, Protonix, Lisinopril, Linezolid, Cefepime
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is intubated, unresponsive and examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates essentially continuous pattern rich in theta frequency activity. Arrhythmic delta activity is prominent in the posterior regions, right more so than the left. Some of this is sharply contoured. In addition, on 1 or 2 occasions, there seems to be a left frontotemporal sharp wave. There is intermittent attenuation and/or disruption of the theta with slower arrhythmic delta activity. Stimulation of the patient does seem to produce an increase in theta.
HR: 116 bpm
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region.
3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal.
4. Intermittent background attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a significant, bihemispheric pathology particularly in the posterior regions. The presence of reactivity is a positive prognostic finding, but the intermittent attenuation is a worrisome prognostic finding in this individual with multiple medical problems and bilateral cerebral ischemia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing. 2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region. 3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal. 4. Intermittent background attenuation.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

Hz theta. There is a small amount of background disorganization and a posterior dominant rhythm of 7-8 Hz. 1. 	Two 8 second bursts of frontally predominant 3 Hz generalized spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing in the left temporal region are of unclear clinical significance. Carbamazepine has been reported to accentuate  this form of epileptiform activity and this form of generalized epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	24-year-old female, past medical history of Wegener's granulomatosis, kidney transplant in 1999, end stage renal disease on peritoneal dialysis,  hypertension, anemia, and deep venous thrombosis, that presents with new onset seizure, generalized tonic, clonic, with loss of consciousness  and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Calcitriol, Aranesp, Senipar, Simvastatin, Mupirocin, Heparin, Moxifloxacin, Percocet, Phenergan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. The patient had a coughing spell while in the lab.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is well­ organized with 9.5, Hz 50, 50-70 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm. A normal variant is observed in the background with rhythmic mid temporal, 5 Hz activity in the temporal regions, right or left. The technologist tested the patient on multiple occasions with stimulation of the patient always terminates these strains at 5 Hz flat top shaped activity, which may be unilateral or bilaterally.
At 11: 30: 54: The patient is sitting comfortably and has a heart rate of 84. She has a coughing spell, feeling as if she cannot catch her breath, and as if she is about to lose contact. The coughing spell is associated with muscle movement artifact, followed by burst of high amplitude delta. The heart rate increases to 132 beats per minute.
By 11:31:44: the EEG has returned to normal, but the patient remains tachycardic and feels unwell. Additional coughing again produces some of the same artifact, and some burst of delta.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response. HR: 	84-132 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The rhythmic mid temporal theta described above is a normal variant, sometimes referred to as psychomotor variant. The patient had 2 episodes of coughing, with an increase in delta. The physiologic conclusion would be that prolonged coughing is the results in a hyperventilation response with the same sort of entity as would be expected to see in hyperventilation in the lab.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	18-year-old with childhood seizures characterized by absence seizures, positive family history of epilepsy. Patient was taken off Depakote a year ago because she was seizure free and had an event over the weekend with loss of awareness, falling. She recalls being confused for one-half hour to an hour afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: 	Depakote
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but the overall background is disorganized and irregular. In the awake background, there is some subtle asymmetry with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity observed from the right in comparison to the left. There is also an underlying sharp wave focus seen subtly in the background in the right posterior temporal/parietal region.
Features of drowsiness including increase in background slowing. There is some rhythmic slowing observed in drowsiness. In addition, some of the focality is accentuated in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontal delta as well as some occipitally predominant delta. Photic stimulation does elicit a bilateral driving response.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background disorganization and an irregular pattern.
2. Subtle, underlying arrhythmic slowing from the right posterior quadrant with likely associated underlying sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	The background slowing and disorganization is nonspecific and supports a diffuse
disturbance of cerebral function. The epileptiform features were subtle. They may be better identified by additional sleep recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Background disorganization and an irregular pattern. 2. Subtle, underlying arrhythmic slowing from the right posterior quadrant with likely associated underlying sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   53-year-old right-handed  female, with left-sided weakness, aphasia, twitching and headache, fever, herpes encephalitis
MEDICATIONS:   Motrin, Ativan, Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, background  EEG demonstrates an interhemispheric asymmetry. The left hemisphere is appropriately  organized with 9 Hz 50 mV posterior dominant rhythm. The right hemisphere  is characterized  by intermittent arrhythmic delta. Although, much of the faster frequency activity persists with periodic, right centrotemporal sharp waves with a field of spread essentially throughout the entire right hemisphere. These vary in terms of the periodicity, but do not evolve to seizures. If the patient becomes drowsy, they become lower amplitude with more a pattern of sharply contoured delta. Deeper stages of sleep are characterized  by an increase in beta frequency activity. The patient is easily
stimulated with an awake pattern from the left and a periodic sharply contoured  slowing from the
right.
HR: 	96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram:
1. 	Right-sided focal slowing.
2. 	Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:
This EEG supports a structural abnormality  on the right involving
gray and white matter. The periodic sharp waves support cortical irritability. This is a highly irritative pattern that raises concerns for ongoing seizures.  These results were reviewed with clinical team on 10/12/2007.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram 1. Right-sided focal slowing. 2. Periodic, high-amplitude  right temporal sharp waves.

report:

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Much of the records includes significant muscle movement artifact. The interpretable portions of the record demonstrate  an abnormal background with bursts of rhythmic delta observed bilaterally and a glimpse of a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is more delta from the right compared to the left. There is another generous field in the right temporal region both anterior and posterior. Despite the muscle movement artifact, the patient was clearly more alert than on previous occasions and was moving about.
HR: 	60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Technically limited, but abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Background slowing, bilaterally.
2. 	Intermittent rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity from either hemisphere.
3.	Right greater than left rhythmic delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The periodic activity has improved on the right in comparison to previous studies. There are no seizures, no PLEDS, and no focal spikes. A follow-up study when the patient is better able to cooperate is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically limited, but abnormal EEG due to 1.Background slowing, bilaterally. 2. Intermittent rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity from either hemisphere. 3.Right greater than left rhythmic delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	58 year-old male with a history of 2 motor vehicle accidents, 1 in 2004 and the other in 2007  sustaining a subdural hematoma. Patient is currently complaining of  headaches and dizzy spells. There is a left temporal parietal craniotomy.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background rhythm consists of 9 hertz alpha rhythm at 30 to 50 microvolts.  Increased amplitude on the left greater than right. There is evidence of breech rhythm on the left. Wicket spikes are also seen. Hyperventilation is performed which increases  the amplitude of the record and also accentuates the breech rhythm. Photic stimulation produces minimal paroxysmal driving.
HR: 	56 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG with variant of left temporal breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Breech rhythm is an anticipated finding given his history of craniotomy. Wicket spikes are a normal variant and would be expected to be more sharply contoured in the presence of a craniotomy. No epileptiform activity was appreciated. If epilepsy is an important concern, we recommend repeating the EEG with sleep recording.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG with variant of left temporal breech rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   58 year-old male with multiple motor vehicle accidents, left temporoparietal  craniotomy  with a plate. Patient was having episodes shortly after his second head trauma in December 2007 when he had episodic dizziness, double vision and drop attacks. Now, resolving post traumatic symptoms.
MEDICATIONS:   Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are preformed. This is a 1 hour Sleep-Deprived EEG. Left craniotomy defect is observed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. A prominent craniotomy defect is observed with wicked from the left central temporal region. Underneath the wicked, there is a small amount of slow delta. Hyperventilation is performed  early on in the record accentuating the focal slowing. This is followed by drowsiness  with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep followed by arousals. Possible REM sleep is observed in this record in the sleep deprived 1 hour record with a characteristic  theta and lateral eye movements in a past who does not appear to be awake. This may have been associated with an arousal. An EMG monitor was not employed. In the extended sleep recording, there is vertex activity. There is alpha frequency activity picked up on the left more so that the right into stage 2 sleep which is an unusual finding in that is it sometimes seen on the right would not be considered a clearly pathological entity. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR: 	54 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are a number of unusual features in this record including the possibility of REM sleep in a single 1 hour record. The REM sleep appeared to be fragmented.  Another usual feature was the presence of rhythmic alpha rhythmic activity from the left central temporal region into stage 2 sleep.
This could not be considered clearly pathological  as it was sometimes present on there right. In any case, the alpha frequency activity did not wax and wane as might be anticipated in an epileptiform  pathology
Given the presence of the metal plate, epileptiform  activity may be under recognized in this individual. The previous craniotomy and skull defect in this case provide a breech rhythm with accentuation of activity, but the possibility of that activity is masked could not be excluded. This individual did not experience any other his paroxysmal spells during the study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old right handed male with epilepsy since 2007, breakthrough seizure 2 weeks ago with loss of consciousness and confusion. This is an outpatient EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing and increase in amplitude of the background as well as some rhythmic delta from the right hemisphere, but without disruption of the underlying faster frequency activity. As the patient becomes drowsy again, there is a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity with subtle rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. This is seen with brief transitions into stage II sleep but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. On one occasion, in the transition to sleep there are sharp waves with rhythmic slowing out of the right temporal region followed by an arousal period. Unfortunately, there is some wick-like activity at this same time and there are some additional more subtle sharp waves without the same faster frequency activity noted. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response. During photic stimulation, a well defined right anterotemporal spike in slow-wave complex is observed. Additional spike complexes are noted at the very end of the record, again right anterotemporal.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region.
2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. 2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.
