report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 78-year-old gentlemen with tonic clonic admitted on 18th with tonic clonic
seizures responsive to 5 mg with Ativan and 5 mg of morphine but right facial twitching. The
patient was then loaded again with 3 mg of Ativan and Dilantin. Evaluate for subclinical status
epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE As the tracing opens, the patient is relatively lethargic, but
over the course of this postictal EEG, the patient is more arousable. The initial background is
low voltage, diffusely slow, but there are intermittent arousals with approximately 8 Hertz alpha
rhythm identified bilaterally right better than left. The patient waxes and wanes with some
portions of the records which are reasonably well organized with alpha and theta activity, other
which are low voltage featureless delta and others which are a mix of irregular mixed theta and
delta. Activity is slightly higher on the right. Through the course of the record, intermittent
attenuations are observed and there is a fair amount of waxing and waning although the close -
of the record does seem to be better then the beginning. There is some sharp slowing observed
in the right mid to anterior temporal region with an after going slow wave observed.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right.
3. Intermittent background attenuation.
4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function
effecting both hemispheres perhaps more significantly on the left than the right. The sharp
waves, however, were on the right. No previous EEG were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Superimposed focal slowing with disruption of fast frequency on the left relative to the right. 3. Intermittent background attenuation. 4. Rare sharp wave observed on the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 90-year-old woman with recurrent stroke on the 20th.   Increasing left-sided weakness, treated briefly with Keppra.
MEDICATIONS:  Lipitor, Aricept, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were deferred.  This is a technically acceptable EEG, although there were some electrodes with impedance greater than 5 kilo-ohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates an asymmetry.  While both hemispheres are slow, the left hemisphere includes a diffusely slow pattern with 6 hertz theta.  The right hemisphere demonstrates more significant arrhythmic delta activity with disruption of faster frequency activity.  The patient is somewhat inattentive and frequent chew artifact was noted.
Occasional sharp waves were noted in the right frontal/frontotemporal region.  These seem to attenuate with stimulation.  Arrhythmic delta activity with both notable in the right frontal central/frontotemporal region.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically somewhat challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
An asymmetry with more significant arrhythmic delta activity and more slowing on the right.
Occasional right frontal sharp waves are sharply contoured transients in the context of right frontal central focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural process on the right with a cortical stroke, the sharp waves are in the region of the ischemic deficit.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a technically somewhat challenging, but abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. An asymmetry with more significant arrhythmic delta activity and more slowing on the right. Occasional right frontal sharp waves are sharply contoured transients in the context of right frontal central focal slowing.

Description:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old lady with past medical history of subarachnoid hemorrhage in 2007, status post hypertension and asthma and also history of seizures with left-sided weakness secondary to old stroke, presents for episodes of stuttering speech and right upper extremity shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, Norvasc, Prozac, Prilosec, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 and stage 2 sleep are characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, and presence of posts, K complexes, vertex sharp transients, and sleep spindles.  There are also intermittent bursts of bitemporal slowing at F7/T3 and F8/T4 lasting for 1-2 seconds.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies, and results in a symmetric driving response.  Hyperventilation was performed and resulted in slowing of the background activity.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Bitemporal slowing is suggestive of bilateral structural abnormalities or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures. If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG or continuous bedside EEG or ambulatory, an EEG monitoring maybe helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 46-year-old woman with complex partial epilepsy, previously evaluated in 2008, now seen in the emergency room after recurrent seizures characterized by palpitations, diaphoresis, and staring occurring 1-3 times a week, lasting 3 minutes.  These are associated with fear.  Also, a feeling as if she is on a boat.  Patient was feeling almost back to herself.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, antidepressants, other medications (suboptimal adherent).
INTRODUCTION:  Extended, digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient was somewhat symptomatic during the EEG, reporting disequilibrium.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with a symmetric reactive alpha rhythm.  This is disrupted by intermittent bursts of rhythmic right temporal delta with admixed sharp waves.  The bursts of sharp waves and delta are on the order of 5-10-15 seconds in duration.  No alteration in the patient's motor or sensory symptoms were seen in association with these discharges.  The patient's responses are slowed, but the tech who spends 40 minutes with the patient, finds that the patient's responsiveness is not so significantly different than the sections of the record without the bursts.  As the recording concludes, the epileptiform activity is decreasing, but there remains some rhythmic right temporal slowing.  The sharp waves are significantly more discreet.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record.  A driving response was identified.  In the final minutes of the recording, another more brief burst of right temporal sharp waves was noted.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves.
Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta.
Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings suggest a highly irritative focus.  This may be a postictal study, but ongoing vigilance is essential (the patient was admitted to the hospital based on this result).
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves. Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta. Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features observed. The background slowing may be due to this patient's medical condition.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild  slowing of the alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	39-year-old man with history of acute renal failure, hypertension, and recent syncopal episodes.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement with 1  channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During wakefulness, a mildly disorganized background rhythm is seen with an alpha. rhythm mildly slow at 8 Hz, but does normalize to 10 Hz at 35 to 40 mV. As the record continues, rare bursts of focal left
temporal slowing is seen.  During the end of hyperventilation, a left focal temporal sharp wave is seen followed by a burst of slow activity. There is no activation of the record otherwise.  Photic stimulation is done with minimal driving. As record continues, a second left frontal sharp wave is seen.
HR:	50 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Mild disorganization of the background with minimal slowing.
2.	Rare bursts of left focal temporal slowing.
3.	Two individual sharp waves, one in the left temporal region and the second in the left frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The two independent left sided sharp waves along with the frontal temporal slowing is consistent with a possible diagnosis of epilepsy.  The mild disorganization of the slowing of the background is a nonspecific finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild disorganization of the background with minimal slowing. 2.Rare bursts of left focal temporal slowing. 3.Two individual sharp waves, one in the left temporal region and the second in the left frontal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old male With renal failure. hypertension and an episode
of syncope, evaluated for seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes a drowsy pattern with·
generous theta. In addition, in drowsiness and early in hyperventilation, there is a small
amount of shifting temporal slowing. Features of sleep include an increase in
background theta with spontaneous arousals from sleep. Photic stimulation does not
activate the record .
HR:60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess background theta for an adult of this age.
2. Occasional shifting slowing.
CLINICAL No epileptiform features were observed in this study but
the excess theta and the rare shifting slowing may be correlated clinically.
Consideration for underlying medications or other factors that might contribute to this
process is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess background theta for an adult of this age. 2. Occasional shifting slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  	40 year old male with recurrent episodes more recently described as seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG demonstrates a well-defined alpha rhythm of 10.5 Hz, a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Drowsiness produces an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. POSTS are seen at the end of the record.
HR: 	96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are identified in the record today. In  addition, in contrast to previous studies in wakefulness there is no increase in background theta. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy, and the abnormalities seen in previous EEGs should be considered as an important part of the whole record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old female with a new onset of loss of consciousness
with convulsion and tongue biting. No urinary incontinence. No history of seizures in the
past.
MEDICATIONS: Ambien, Zofran, Tylenol, Ambien
INTRODUCTION: .Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness the background EEG is
mildly disorganized with 11 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, and there is bilateral frontal
slowing in theta range. Hyperventilation was done early in the record, and it increased in
the bilateral frontal slowing. Photic stimulation was also performed. and it elicits minimal
driving. á
HR:. 70 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mildly disorganized background.
2. Bilateral frontal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record. The absence of epileptiform activity does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. Clinical
correlation is indicated.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. Mildly disorganized background. 2. Bilateral frontal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 36 year old woman with epilepsy. Last seizure was December 2008, and was characterized by loss of consciousness, confusion, tongue biting. She had another seizure March 2009. She has an aura of lightheadedness and a funny feeling in her abdomen prior to her seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Lamotrigine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and Photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness background, EEG is well organized with 10 Hz, 60 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background slowing. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

report:
History:	42 YO FEMALE WITH A HX OF SZ SINCE 2008. 2 TYPES, GTC AND ABSENCE.
LAST SZ. 4 DAYS AGO.
Medications:	ZONEGRAN
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse, frontally predominant 5-10uV, 18-25Hz activity is also seen.
During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more
prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
flash rates.  HR was 54
Summary of Findings:
No electrographic seizures
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the
medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the
medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	29 year old gentleman with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin load.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.	The patient had just come from the emergency room having received the Dilantin and he had a seizure in the EEG lab removing his EEG electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the recording starts out, the patient is awake and reasonably cooperative.  There is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm observed. As the tracing again, the patient is awake with a 9.5 Hz, 30 mV posterior dominate rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by
slow-rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation is initiated early in the record, at 13:30 the patient is in the middle of hyperventilation.  At this time, 13:30:50 there is an arousal.   This is followed by the appearance of beta at 13:30:55, with repetitive sharp activity and theta maximum in the left temporal region, but with some bilateral representation.  As this continues at 13:31:07, there is little in the way of clinical manifestations.  By 13:31:10, the patient is starting to look from side to side.  He looks somewhat startled or frightened. The technologist calls the patient.  The patient's is
observed to be chewing, at 13:31:20, with repetitive sharp waves in left temporal region. He seems to be having automatic movements, face and but the audio is not
discernable.  The EEG goes on to be obscured with muscle.  As the patient's behaviors change, at 13:31:44, as he does that he has had head turning to the right. He gets up, he rotating around and looking all the way to the right.  He starts to turn around and around and he puts his head down. At that point, he rolls back towards his back and he has tonic clonic activity with his back to the camera with tonic stiffening and then clonic by 13:32:05. he seems to be having tonic clonic activity in the right arm but the left arm is stiff. Foaming at the mouth is seen at 13:32:19.  while he has eye deviation to the left he is jerking primarily with the right arm.  The characteristic slow pattern at the close of the clonic tonic seizure as the motor activity slows, is observed at 13:32:39. This seizure  ends at 13:32:48.  This is a 2 minute seizure.  Afterwards, the patient is awake, but agitated and he starts to get up and move about. There is a caregiver present with the technologist who applies oxygen.  The patient removes all the electrodes and receives 4 mg of Ativan. The EEG concludes at 13:40:02, where behaviorally the
patient is postictal
HR:	60 to 120 at the maximum during the seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
1. 	Left temporal lobe complex partial seizure of 2 minutes duration,
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  There is a well defined prolonged scalp EEG correlate before the EEG is obscured by muscle and motion artifact.  Additional evaluation and assessment is advised.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to;
1. Left temporal lobe complex partial seizure of 2 minutes duration,

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	59 year old with cranioplasty, stroke in 1993, now with an episode of unresponsiveness 1 hour prior to this EEG.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel of EKG. This is an awake study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Background EEG is compromised primarily of diffuse rhythmic 5-6 Hz theta activity with smaller amounts of frontal central theta. Features of sleep include: The patient is awake.  He has a cortical posture of his left hand and he has a persistent automatisms in the right hand without EEG correlate.
HR: 	90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Replacement of normal background with diffuse rhythmic theta
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   In this individual with a past craniotomy there is a bit of an amplitude asymmetry compatible with a breech,  but there is no epileptiform features. The background component is most compatible with diffuse disturbance of cerebral function. In comparison to a previous EEG on August 28, 2008.  Today there was no continuous right sided slowing, no sharp  waves in the right central parietal region.  The previous studies were compatible with subclinical status epilepticus, not seen today.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old male status post a right left MCA stroke and right subdural hematoma with recurrent status epilepticus, focal motor and generalized tonic? clonic seizures earlier today.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra,  Dilantin, Trileptal, ASA, Lisinopril, Vit-B, Zocor


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel  EKG. Patient is somnolent but moving about and answering questions.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a slow pattern bilaterally with theta-delta pattern.  In addition, superimposed upon this is a rhythmic delta from the right posterior quadrant and in this region there is also a sharp wave in the right posterotemporal region.

The patient has a seizure while working with the tech. The seizure seems to begin while the tech is working with the patient and the first ictal changes are at 15:48. The ictal changes include an increase in theta frequency activity.

By 01:49:00 very clear ictal changes are noted with the patient looking, instead of at the right, he is looking at the left and blinking. He remains responsive to the technologist at
0:48:55 as this activity builds up.  He seems to be confused, but he does follow commands and closes his eyes at 0:49:14. The tech is working with the patient so she does not observe the rhythmic repetitive theta activity in the right temporal region which spreads to the parietal and occipital region as well. He stops speaking, though.  By
15:50 the physician comes to examine the patient who is clearly confused and unable to follow commands, with roving eye movements.   He does provide a few words at
15:50:33. This electrographic seizure has a clear end at 15:51:11 and likely onset gradual evolution of faster frequencies at 15:48 for a total seizure duration of approximately 3 minutes.

Afterwards, the EEG returns to its previous, slower periodic sharp wave from the right hemisphere which gradually build up at 15:54:03.   Facial twitching is noted.

The second seizure is a grand mal seizure but starts with facial twitching and actually has a complex partial component where the patient actually seems to be somewhat

responsive and uncomfortable with focal and then asynchronous twitching. The second seizure is significantly longer in duration.  The tonic-clonic section of it is still relatively prolonged and is at least4  seconds in duration.

After the second seizure which has the tonic-clonic components, the overall EEG is quite slow but the periodic complexes in the right posterior quadrant persist.

HR:	150  bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to:
1. 	Tonic-clonic seizure.
2. 	Complex partial seizure.
3 .	Continuous right posterior quadrant periodic complexes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal bedside EEG due to 1. Tonic-clonic seizure

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old man with Parkinson's disease, brain tumor, pinealoma status post radiation therapy many years ago with encephalopathy, MRI demonstrating  right temporal lobe enhancement.   The patient presented to an outside hospital with encephalopathy and white matter changes.  Evaluate for herpes encephalitis or other cause.  There is a history of craniotomy and epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Metoprolol, Mirapex, Lovenox, Zofran
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG demonstrates an intrahemispheric  asymmetry.  There is a discernible 9Hz 50 microvolt alpha rhythm on the right which is disrupted on the left.  In addition, there is a skull defect with head rocking in the right central region and overall disruption of mu activity on the right compared to the left. Features of drowsiness include a drop out of faster frequency activity which occurs on the right much sooner on the left.
A seizure occurs at 09:53:03. It begins with the subtle development of alpha frequency out of the right temporal scalp electrodes which evolve.  No definitive clinical signs are seen until 09:53:47 when he starts to blink.  He seems to be motionless looking at the camera.  There may be some switching in the neck, but nothing that the video observer can see.  By 09:53:47 he is staring and blinking, looking to the left.  There is clear frequency evolution at 09:54:37.  There is no testing performed in the seizure and postictal slowing is noted with the end of the seizure occurring at 09:55:22 to 09:56.  By
09:59 the EEG looks postictal.  It has returned to the slowing that was previously noted
on the right with the return of alpha briefly on the left.
Notable features during this relatively prolonged, 2 minute complex partial seizure, includes the appearance of alpha frequency activity bilaterally, although there previously had not been alpha frequency on the right.  This activity is clearly pathological and it is not the alpha rhythm which reacts to eye opening.  It is actually faster frequency than it is posterior dominant rhythm and it is associated with repetitive sharp activity at T2.
The postictal recording includes some sharp waves on the left.
HR:	60 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	A 2.5 minute complex partial seizure.
2. 	Focal slowing from the right.
3. 	Sharp waves from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  Correlation with imaging is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. A 2.5 minute complex partial seizure. 2. Focal slowing from the right. 3. Sharp waves from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old male with pinealoma recurrent complex partial seizures. MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Mirapex, Metoprolol,  Lovenox, Zofran
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG was performed  at bedside using 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is recorded in a routine room.
There is no seizure spike detection employed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Through the course of this EEG, there are 6 complex partial seizures recorded.  The clinical manifestations of the seizures appear to be quite subtle for those who are not familiar with epilepsy.  The patient stares, blinks, may look to the left, and has impaired responsiveness.  He has some automatic movements.
Epileptiform activity during the seizures is characterized  by rhythmic 9 Hz activity in the right temporal region, including the right posterior temporal region.  This activity shows frequency evolution transitioning  to theta and then delta with sharply contoured activity at T2, T4, and T6. Postictal features for these seizures include marked slowing from the right hemisphere, particularly the temporal region with rhythmic theta delta, and then a lower voltage more suppressed pattern.
The seizures are relatively infrequent, but reoccur at 16:20, 16:43.  That seizure is characterized by chewing activity,  02:28 to 02:48 in which there is really little in the way of clinical correlate, but there is the clear alpha frequency activity on the right with a slower pattern on the left, 03:06,
04:52, 05:09. Some of the discharges  have little in the way of a clinical correlate. The recording ends at 6:00 a.m.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
I.   Multiple complex partial seizures, but they seem to be abating at the close of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The EEG supports an irritative process on the right.  The complex partial seizures are relatively subtle.  The total number of seizures is likely 6-8 in 15 hours.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to I.   Multiple complex partial seizures, but they seem to be abating at the close of the record.

report:
History:	59 year old woman with a history of seizures, now presents with increase in seizure
frequency.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by low-to-moderate amplitude 10.5-11 Hz alpha rhythm, which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present,
maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-
7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.
Polymorphic and rhythmic delta activity (TIRDA) is frequently observed over the left temporal
region during wakefulness and increases during drowsiness.  Two focal electrographic seizures are
captured.  Each lasts ~ 1 minute.  No clinical correlate is reported by the EEG technologist.  The
patient is not formally tested during these seizures.  They occur during drowsiness.  Seizures start
with rhythmic left anterior temporal delta activity, most pronounced over F7/t1 region.  It gradually
increases in amplitude, becomes more prominent and slightly increases in frequency from ~2 Hz to
~2.5-3 Hz.  There is some reflection  to the left parasagittal leads and left lateral/ temporal leads.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, two, left temporal, anterior, each ~ 1 min long.  Occur out of drowsiness
Focal slowing, rhythmic, intermittent, moderate, left temporal, anterior
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, moderate, left temporal, anterior
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28-minute EEG due to intermittent focal left anterior
temporal slowing, often rhythmic, and 2 focal left anterior temporal seizures that occur during
drowsiness and do not have a clear clinical correlate. These findings are indicative of an
epileptogenic focus in left anterior temporal region, and given the clinical history of partial
seizures, are consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy.  These findings were
relayed to the ordering physician at the time of the record review.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28-minute EEG due to intermittent focal left anterior
temporal slowing, often rhythmic, and 2 focal left anterior temporal seizures that occur during
drowsiness and do not have a clear clinical correlate. These findings are indicative of an
epileptogenic focus in left anterior temporal region, and given the clinical history of partial
seizures, are consistent with a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy.  These findings were
relayed to the ordering physician at the time of the record review

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is actually increasingly awake and responsive during the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is remarkable for a fair amount of muscle movement artifact. There is a beta frequency background on the left with generous beta.  There is irregular activity in the right hemisphere with arrhythmic delta activity with variable maximum, including frontal temporal, posterior temporal, or right central/central temporal.  Arrhythmic delta accompanies this. Later portions in the record, when the patient is a bit more awake, seem to be associated with a bit less of this activity, but it  is relatively continuous.

3. 	Sharp waves from the right, including right central temporal.

report:

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left temporal focal slowing characterized by rhythmic and arrhythmic focal slowing. 2. Rare left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation and
hyperventilation are performed. This is a 1 hour sleep deprived record.

response. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing some background
slowing, as well as a bit of arrhythmic delta activity in the posterior temporal regions bilaterally.

dysfunction due to many etiologies, including epilepsy or HIV infection.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild slowing of the alpha rhythm. 2. Rare shifting asymmetries of vertex waves.

TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




Diffuse excess beta activity is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.







EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

A single brief burst (~1.5 seconds) of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant
moderate-to-high amplitude polyspikes is captured towards the end of the recording during stage II
sleep.




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:


1. A single brief burst of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant moderate-to-high
amplitude polyspikes is captured during stage II sleep.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This finding is suggestive of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.



Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or
barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 

1. A single brief burst of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant moderate-to-high
amplitude polyspikes is captured during stage II sleep.

DURATION OF STUDY:  21 minutes.

MEDICATIONS:  Nifedipine, glipizide, metformin, Cymbalta, Plavix, Bactrim, HIV medications, lisinopril.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated 10-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old male with chronic static encephalopathy, Dandy? Walker abnormality, and recurrent seizures with tonoclonic seizures today just prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS:  Neurolex


INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is somewhat agitated and briefly drowsing.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal, diffusely slow low voltage, and lacking the normal developmental milestones for an adult. In addition, there is an asymmetry with a bit more rhythmic alpha frequency activity on the right in comparison to the left. Features of drowsiness including increase in background slowing.

HR:	114 bpm


IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Very slow overall background.
2.	Interhemispheric asymmetry with more alpha frequency activity on the right central region and more rhythmic slowing from the left.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Very slow overall background. 2.Interhemispheric asymmetry with more alpha frequency activity on the right central region and more rhythmic slowing from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 27-year-old male with Dandy-Walker syndrome, cerebral palsy, and multiple shunts.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Although, there were multiple craniotomy defects, the patient was reasonably cooperative.

Photic stimulation did not activate the record. Heart rate: 132 BPM.

Absence of the normal awake morphologies for an adult of this age.
Diffuse generalized beta pattern.
Paroxysmal rhythmic right frontal alpha frequency activity.

IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: This EEG is remarkable for;
Absence of the normal awake morphologies for an adult of this age. Diffuse generalized beta pattern. Paroxysmal rhythmic right frontal alpha frequency activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 31-year-old woman with past medical history of seizures since
age 1. The patient with frequent seizures now with increase in seizure frequency. The
patient states that in May she had 3 seizures in one day. The events are described as
aura of dizziness and boggy stiffness, unable to speak, then generalized tonic-clonic
loss of consciousness with post ictal confusion. She also has tongue biting. The
patient's medications were changed from Tegretol to Dilantin in May.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: This video EEG is performed in the laboratory using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with one-channel of EKG. Hypoventilation and photic
stimulation were performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is continuous symmetric and
fairly well-organized. There is a 10 Hz, 13 mcV posterior dominant alpha rhythm which
well attenuates with his eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage fast beta
activity in the frontal and central area. Hypoventilation did not change his background
significantly. However, no sleeping stages were achieved in this tracing. Photic
stimulation created driving, but no epileptiform or abnormal discharges noted.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If
epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG with sleeping activation may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old woman with intracranial injury, right subdural hematoma, bilateral subarachnoid hemorrhage, mass effect, left midline shift, left basilar skull and left zygomatic fractures, some falcine extension of subdural hematoma, left midline shift.  The patient was reported to have had seizure-related trauma.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, others
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside in ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was poorly cooperative and restless.  Impedances were satisfactory.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a diffusely slow pattern.  The left hemisphere demonstrates primarily theta frequency activity with a glimpse of a 7 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and generous 4-6 Hz activity.  The right hemisphere demonstrates attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right with lower voltage slow activity.  The patient is not able to cooperate and is frequently shifting throughout the EEG.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Essentially continuous focal slowing with delta on the right, particularly in the right posterior quadrant.
Attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right.
Diffuse background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive sharp waves were noted in this record.  Previous EEGs are not available for this patient at this time.  A previous EEG was recorded in 2009 if comparison is needed.  This EEG supports a structural process on the right, congruent with the surgical history as well as the diffuse disturbance of cerebral function, congruent with an acute CNS injury.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Essentially continuous focal slowing with delta on the right, particularly in the right posterior quadrant. Attenuation of faster frequency activity on the right. Diffuse background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old female with hypertensive with multiple syncopal episodes in the last few weeks to months.
MEDICATIONS: Pravastatin,  ASA, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake and sleep study.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During wakefulness, there is a disorganized background. The posterior dominant rhythm reaches at the start 6 Hz and up to 35 microvolts. As the record continues and patient reaches maximal wakefulness during stimulation, the background rhythm reaches at its maximum 9 Hz. There is an interhemispheric asymmetry seen with some focal slowing of the right hemisphere.  Sleep is seen with vertex waves and spindles and a little epochs of sleep, where the patient quickly awakens.  Hyperventilation accentuates the focal slowing in the right hemisphere.  Photic stimulation shows some scant driving, which is seen a bit better on the right posterior hemisphere.
HR:  66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized slowing of the background, which does reach 9 Hz, but the majority of the background is slow.
2. 	More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere.
Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no epileptiform activity seen in this record. The generalized slowing of the background is nonspecific.  Initially, the focal slowing is seen in the right hemisphere,  but the driving is actually better in the right hemisphere,  which is incongruent and not initially expected.  The focal differences could be secondary to a structural abnormality and could get imaging this patient.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized slowing of the background, which does reach 9 Hz, but the majority of the background is slow. 2. More focal slowing seen in the right hemisphere. Scant driving seen asymmetrically  and better in the right posterior region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 26 year old man with migraines and epilepsy for five years. Last seizure
06/14/09.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Butalbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode
placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation, hyperventilation performed. Awake through
stage 2 sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: During wakefulness, a minimally disorganized background
is seen. The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 8.5 to 9 hertz and up to 20 microvolt's.
Throughout the record wicket waves are seen. Throughout the record bursts of irregular theta
activity is seen which is higher amplitude on the left especially when the patient becomes
drowsy or during hyperventilation. These bursts are sharply contoured with a question of an
underlying sharp wave but none is ever seen. During stage 2 sleep vertex waves, K complexes
and spindles are seen. During hyperventilation there is bilateral slowing and the increase in the
sharply contoured bursts, irregular bursts theta. During photic stimulation driving is seen.
HR 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slowing of the background
2. Bursts of sharply contoured irregular theta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Compared to the patient's previous study done here in 2005, the
background slowing has improved. There was a question of an underlying sharp wave that
never develops even through stage 2 sleep. A prolonged sleep EEG may be considered.
There is no overall epileptiform activity or seizures, however, found in this record.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Slowing of the background
2. Bursts of sharply contoured irregular theta activity.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old woman with change in mental status and recent seizures with a history of epilepsy, schizophrenia, EPOC, and left mesial temporal sclerosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The EKG electrode does not show a very good rhythm, a very low amplitude rhythm.  In addition, the impedances on the occipital electrodes and the right frontal and central electrodes were very high due to difficulty with the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a recording that is mainly in sleep.  The patient is aroused at one point during the study and there appears to be a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8 Hz, mainly seen over the right hemisphere, but for a short duration, again in the setting of electrode with a high impedance.  Overall the record is recorded during stage I and stage II and the first stages of sleep.  The patient falls asleep fairly quickly throughout this study.
Heart rate:  78 and appears to be regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-50 mV, at times with a very sharply contoured component.  Sometimes they appear to become rhythmic, but not clearly evolved or become continuous.
Focal slowing seen intermittently at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness and limited wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG in limited wakefulness reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region and independently in the right mid temporal region, both of which are nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the patient appears to have some mild diffuse generalized dysfunction, which is also nonspecific in regard to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal focal slowing, as well as right mid temporal focal slowing and mild excessive theta in limited wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 55-year-old woman with schizophrenia, epilepsy with tonic-clonic seizures, and recurrent hospitalizations for status epilepticus.  Currently, seizure-free for nearly 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  There is some electrode placement issues with this EEG, but it is technically acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is very low voltage with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
There is significant muscle twitch artifact noted in the background.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult with a history of refractory epilepsy.  No epileptiform features were noted today, but complex epileptiform activity has been noted with many different patterns over the past 4 years.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.

History:	56 YR FEMALE WITH CHANGE IN MS. AND WITNESS GTC SZ. PMHX: SZ, SCHIZOPHRENIA,
PT IS WELL KNOWN PT TO NEURO. MISSES CLINIC APPT.   PT HAIR MATTED (ALWAYS MATTED HEAD, NOT MEASURED, ELECTRODES GUESSED)
Medications:	LACOSEMIDE, KEPPRA, PHENOBARBITAL, ATIVAN
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, asleep, lethargic, obtunded
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for hours from 03/23/2015 to 03/25/2015. Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns. All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events	0
Description of pushbutton events None
Description:
No posterior dominant rhythm was present. Background activity was characterized by diffuse low voltage delta and theta activity with absence of the expected anterior to posterior gradient of frequencies. No normal sleep architecture was present.
Nearly continuous polymorphic delta activity is present in the left hemisphere. Occasional focal spike-, polyspike and sharp waves are present with phase reversal and amplitude maximum at F7, F8, F4 and C4. Some have a very large field spreading bilaterally frontally maximal with a polyphasic complex morphology. No clinical or electrographic seizures were present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  There was no reactivity to auditory, tactile, or painful stimuli.  Hr was 120
Summary of Findings:
Sharp waves, frequent, bilateral frontal
Sharp waves, frequent, bilateral temporal, anterior
Focal slowing, polymorphic, nearly continuous, left hemispheric Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, continuous, severe diffuse
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG because of frequent epileptiform discharges in the bilateral frontal region and anterior temporal regions. These findings are indicative of a potentially epileptogenic foci in these regions. In addition there is nearly continuous focal slowing in the left hemisphere region. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction,which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin
or may be a post ictal effect. Lastly there is severe  diffuse background slowing and absent alpha rhythm. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators	severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG because of frequent epileptiform discharges in the bilateral frontal region and anterior temporal regions. These findings are indicative of a potentially epileptogenic foci in these regions. In addition there is nearly continuous focal slowing in the left hemisphere region. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction,which is etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin
or may be a post ictal effect. Lastly there is severe  diffuse background slowing and absent alpha rhythm. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicatorssevere diffuse cerebral dysfunction

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old gentleman with history of COPD, hypertension, diabetes, tooth cancer, status post treatment, who presents with left focal seizures described as a left arm shaking lasting for a few minutes, resolved by administration of Ativan 2 mg IV.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-7.5 Hz in frequency, well-formed on the left side, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 5-7 Hz diffuse theta activity noted during wakefulness.  There is attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the right hemisphere, most pronounced in posterior quadrant with intermittent slowing in the left cerebral hemisphere.  The lethargic state is characterized by further slowing of the background and disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm.  Heart rate was 90 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness.
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of either metabolic, toxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the left cerebral hemisphere is likely due to the patient's history of stroke.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures is captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG recording due to Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness. Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.

INTRODUCTION:
An EEG is performed using standard the 10-20 electrode placement system with an EKG electrode. Awake and stage I sleep is recorded. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were used.
MEDICATIONS:
Vimpat and Tegretol.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:
None.
HISTORY:
A 37-year-old female who presents for followup EEG with past medical history significant for generalized epilepsy. Last seizure was reported in February 2011, with fall and loss of consciousness with urinary incontinence and postictal confusion lasting for an hour.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
Posterior dominant alpha rhythm is seen at 9 to 10Hz frequency and 20 microvolt amplitude which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. Frontocentral beta rhythm is also seen. Stage I sleep is seen and is normal. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed, which are also normal.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized spike and wave at 4 to 4.5 Hz and 70 to 100 microvolts amplitude is seen, which is located maximum anteriorly. This generalized pattern is asymmetric with slight predominance in the left hemisphere. No seizures are seen.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The EEG findings can be seen in generalized epilepsy; however, a sight asymmetric pattern raises the possibility of a focal epilepsy with secondary bilateral synchrony.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.

report:

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and early drowsiness due to Left temporal focal slowing with a component of left frontal central focal slowing
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 28 year old woman with recurrent episodes which appear to be seizures. Past medical history: Post traumatic stress disorder, assault victim, others.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital Video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a vigorous, 50-70 microvolt 10 Hertz upper rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, fronto-central beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude data background. Photic stimulation elicits harmonic and spur harmonic driving. As the photic stimulation begins the patient looks to the left and covers her face. She has her hands over her eyes and appears to be crying. When the technologist turns towards the patient at 10:18:08 the technologist interacts with the patient who begins to have jerking. The patient exhibits pelvic thrusting and neck thrusting and involuntary jerkins. The jerking of the right arm persists even as the study ends at 10:21 but the patient is able to look and interact with the physician. The EEG demonstrates a normal awake pattern throughout the entire event. There is no spike in wave activity and a well defined alpha rhythm is observed.
HR: 60-120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The behavior recorded was not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, the behavioral features of the event would be very unusual for a seizure. These findings were discussed with the clinical team.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

Sedation:
EEG Type: Technique:
Routine, awake & drowsy
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:

Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation is performed from 1-7 fps. Video review (no sound captured and only patient's chest and head are visible) and EEG technologist's notes review show that patient develops diffuse low amplitude shaking and pelvic thrusting. She is able to answer questions correctly and recalls a code word. The event ends abruptly.
Summary of Findings:
Event, one, No EEG correlate Beta, excessive
No epileptiform discharges No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG,awake and drowsy. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information. A single event that occurs during photic stimulation has no abnormal EEG correlate. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27-minute EEG,awake and drowsy. No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information. A single event that occurs during photic stimulation has no abnormal EEG correlate. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Some sections of the records are well organized with rhythmic 8 Hz alpha rhythm, others demonstrate a little bit more disorganization with rhythmic slowing, particularly in the posterior regions. This is accentuated by hyperventilation. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta, again with slight accentuation of the theta seen in the posterior regions, somewhat left more so than the right. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep. Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response, although the patient is drifting off to sleep. Vertex waves are noted at the close of photic stimulation.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess theta.
2. Posteriorly predominant slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive epileptiform features were observed, although the posteriorly predominant slowing was sometimes more remarkable on the left than the right. These findings may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess theta. 2. Posteriorly predominant slowing.

report:
HISTORY:

67 y.o. male with a history of GSW to head 1995, presenting w/ episode of loss of
awareness and shaking 2 wks ago after drinking; had similar episode in 2010; referred for routine
EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.




MEDICATIONS: Keppra



SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




Drowsiness and sleep are not captured



No generalized slowing is present.


Frequent left temporal polymorphic and quasi-rhythmic slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and
accentuates focal slowing in the left temporal region



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 48 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to:


1. Frequent left temporal polymorphic and quasi-rhythmic slowing


CLINICAL CORRELATION:



These findings indicate the presence of left temporal cerebral dysfunction, either structural or
physiologic.


If clinically warranted, a recording with sleep may be helpful.

Tech notes a prior EEG was done in 2010; results were not available via EMR at time of report
generation.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to 

1. Frequent left temporal polymorphic and quasi-rhythmic slowing

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old woman who is not able to provide a detailed history, even with a certified Spanish-speaking translator present.  She did describe chronic headaches lasting 1 to 2 hours for the last 3 years, following assault on the head with a gun.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal, metformin, TriCor, sertraline, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  It was difficult to get the patient to relax, even with a translator and a family member present.  There was a fair amount of muscle noted in the background.  Impedances were acceptable, aside from the T1-T2 electrodes.  This was a 20-minute EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  The background EEG has a small amount of theta and rare bursts of shifting slowing in the transition to sleep.  Despite the muscle artifact described above, the patient does appear to be drowsy, transitioning rapidly in and out of stage 2 sleep with K complexes.
Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was challenging but did demonstrate a driving response.  The patient was also drifting into stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.
Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
A mild excess in background theta.
Rare bursts of shifting slowing in the transition to sleep noted in the temporal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The background theta may be associated with this patient's medications.  The shifting slowing is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in the context of underlying medical problems or with underlying cerebrovascular disease.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to A mild excess in background theta. Rare bursts of shifting slowing in the transition to sleep noted in the temporal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 18 year old right handed woman with a first ever tonic clonic seizure. This seizure began with staring followed by tonic clonic activity, incontinence and 30 minutes of postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial sections of much of the waking record unfortunately includes head rocking artifact in the posterior regions. There is a 10.5 hertz alpha rhythm which is higher amplitude on the right than the left and posterior activity is always higher amplitude on the right than the left in this individual. Brief stage II sleep includes vertex waves, spindles and POSTS. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the driving response is somewhat asymmetric, more vigorous on the left compared to the right. In addition, there is also a suggestion of a subharmonic driving response elicited on the left more so than the right.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to:
1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The head rocking artifact is in the same region as the area of potential abnormality. A somewhat asymmetric photic stimulation is not necessarily pathological and some of the features that this patient demonstrated are compatible with normal variant. To more completely evaluate her epilepsy, a follow up study with more extended sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Equivocally abnormal EEG due to 1. Asymmetric photic stimulation described above.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no epileptiform activity seen in this study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 22 year old female with a history of seizures since age 17. Seizure free since 2010, Diagnosed with lupus  2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Topiramate, prednisone, Plaquenil, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 40-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but the overall background is somewhat disorganized.  There is a small amount of shifting slowing and a small amount of background theta.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic theta.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Notable in this record are paroxysmal bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude theta, some of which demonstrate frequency evolution.  In addition, there are irregular bursts of 4-5 Hz spike and wave activity noted in the frontal regions.  On occasion, some of these seem to be a bit more prominent in the right.  These bursts are overall, relatively asynchronous.
Hyperventilation produced 1 of these bursts of high amplitude, theta frequency activity with a questionable right frontal spike and slow wave complex as well as some rhythmic theta.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.  The photic stimulation may also have accentuated some of the epileptiform activity, although on the whole.  The epileptiform activity was pre or post the photic stimulation.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to.
Small degree of background disorganization for an adult of this age.
Somewhat irregular asynchronous bursts of high amplitude spike and wave activity as well as paroxysmal theta.
Occasional bursts of shifting, slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual.  Previous studies have demonstrated 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity, or independent right or left temporal lobe sharp and slow wave activity.  The findings today are similar to this patient's original EEGs in 2010.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to. Small degree of background disorganization for an adult of this age. Somewhat irregular asynchronous bursts of high amplitude spike and wave activity as well as paroxysmal theta. Occasional bursts of shifting, slowing.

report:
HISTORY:

24 y.o. female with a history of teen onset epilepsy, then SLE  referred for
routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.


Now with excessive drowsiness, vertigo, fatigue.

MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

omeprazole (PRILOSEC) 20 mg capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth daily.

ibuprofen (ADVIL,MOTRIN) 600 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth every 6 hours as needed for Pain.


hydroxychloroquine (PLAQUENIL) 200 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.

Calcium Carbonate-Vitamin D3 (CALCIUM 500 WITH D) 500 mg(1,250mg) -400 unit Tablet, Take 1
tablet by mouth 2 times daily (with meals).


azaTHIOprine (IMURAN) 50 mg tablet, Take 3 tablets by mouth daily.

albuterol (PROAIR HFA) 90 mcg/actuation inhaler, Inhale 1 puff into the lungs every 6 hours as
needed for Wheezing.


prochlorperazine (COMPAZINE) 10 mg tablet, Take 10 mg by mouth every 6 hours as needed.

topiramate (TOPAMAX) 100 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.


folic acid (FOLVITE) 1 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.


Biotin 10,000 mcg Capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth daily.

PARoxetine (PAXIL) 10 mg tablet, Take 10 mg by mouth at bedtime.





TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory
record and included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.

Sleep is not sustained



No generalized slowing is present.  Rare shifting frontal focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

Rare irregular frontally predominant bursts of 3-4 spike and wave with bursts of 2-2.5 seconds duration
are noted in wakefulness.


Focal sharp waves were seen in early drowsiness at T3 and P3. Infrequent.

OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

There are bursts of frontal 4 Hz activity with slight R frontal maximum, but without a definitive spike.



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:

Hyperventilation: elicits bursts of sharply contoured and at times asynchronous slowing, but no
definitive spikes.


Photic Stimulation: in addition to a driving response, 4 Hz frontal high amplitude theta occurs in
brief 1 second burst with 11 Hz stimuli


EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of  54bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:



This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG.

1. Irregular  bursts of 3-4 spike and wave activity


2. Irregular bursts of frontal theta, slightly asymmetric

3. Rare focal sharp waves T3  Or P3


CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These finding have been been previously identified in this adult with teen onset epilepsy but were
not seen in 2015.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 


This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG. 
1. Irregular  bursts of 3-4 spike and wave activity


2. Irregular bursts of frontal theta, slightly asymmetric

3. Rare focal sharp waves T3  Or P3

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   61 year old right handed female for follow up EEG after a right frontal meningioma resection.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Neurontin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a mainly asleep patient, but when awake has a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a slightly increased frontal central beta bilaterally, but slightly more seen on the left than the right.  Normal sleep architecture in stage I and stage II sleep is seen. Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   Intermittent F7/F3 focal slowing occasionally, in the setting of a breach.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontal slow waves in breach.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontal region which is possibly related to her surgery for the meningioma resection.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Left frontal slow waves in breach.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old right handed woman with 3 episodes of right arm shaking which spread to have bilateral arm shaking and then the legs were shaking and then she had right-sided weakness. Past history of a stroke followed by epilepsy 12 years ago. Normal MRI with stable 3-4 mm aneurysm at the left carotid ophthalmic junction.
MEDICATIONS: Alprazolam, Pantoprazole, Atenolol, Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving. After photic stimulation is over, the patient had some jerking of her shoulders but not in association with the flashing lights. After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards.
The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events.
As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends.
The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a 7-minute behavioral episode without EEG change. This recording suggests a behavioral event rather than an electrical seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 51-year-old, right-handed gentleman with history of aneurysm clipping, with history of seizures.  The patient has been seizure free for 5 years.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Topamax.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background activity was characterized by absence of a clear posterior dominant rhythm and a very low amplitude voltage recording.  There is a diffuse beta activity seen throughout the recording.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of a muscle and eye blink artifact and the presence of vertex sharp waves.  Stage 2 sleep is characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.  Some focal slow waves are noted at anterior, temporal, and central area on the left side with some increase in faster frequencies at times.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to left frontocentral slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontocentral region, which is consistent with the known surgery.  The absence of a normal posterior dominant rhythm, although atypical could be a normal variant.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to left frontocentral slowing.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This was a technically unsatisfactory EEG with most impedances below 5 kilo ohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.  This was a 40-minute EEG capturing wakefulness and sleep.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.

Hyperventilation produced an increase in amplitude of the background and slightly accentuated the rhythmic slowing on the left frontal region.

Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in the rhythmic slowing in the left frontocentral region and an increase in beta.  Muscle artifact was noted throughout the record.

Heart rate 66 bpm.

IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to,
1. Low voltage pattern.
2. Generalized background slowing.
3. In the context of a breach rhythm, left rhythmic frontal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this individual.  The last 3 EEGs have demonstrated epileptiform activity.  If additional information is needed, consideration for an alternative monitoring strategy may be appropriate.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to,

times there is some slowing. There was theta activity seen as well. During photic stimulation there was scant driving. Hyperventilation was not attempted.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There was no focal epileptiform discharge seen; however,
this study lacked stage II sleep. A follow up, EEG should be done capturing stage II sleep for this patient because of excessive sleepiness. Excessive sleepiness could explain the findings.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing.
