report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old male with new onset seizures.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was preformed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient keeps a log. He is able to push the button for all of the events that he experiences. He has multiple episodes of dizziness or disorienting feeling.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz posterior dominant rhythm which is symmetrically reactive. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background theta with vertex waves, spindles and stage II sleep. There is an epoch in which REM sleep is seen.
In the interictal EEG, there is a single left temporal sharp wave.
Events: The patient has multiple dizzy spells including 129, 125, 312, 336, 536, 546 and then there are no additional push buttons noted.
Although not all of the seizures have a clear clinical correlate and some have only either subtle theta or subtle disruption of faster frequency activity in left temporal region, some have clear, rhythmic 4 hertz theta from the left temporal region with some spread to the frontocentral region bilaterally, typically lasting 20-40 seconds. The patient receives Depakote at 2:20p.m., the discharges are briefer, more evanescent more allusive.
Event time 12930: the patient has a dizzy spell characterized by decreased alpha frequency activity from the left temporal region and a brief burst of left temporal theta.
Event time: 2:32 p.m.: There is a brief burst of left temporal theta which differs from the background.
Event time: 3:12p.m.: Aura of dizziness, left temporal theta.
Event #3: Aura characterized by dizziness time 335 to 33729, rhythmic temporal theta as described above.
Event #4: Subtle left temporal theta at 3:53:52.
Event #5: 536, very subtle left temporal theta.
Event #6: Aura 5:46:13, brief burst of left temporal theta.
HR: 100 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region.
2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread.
3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is diagnostic of a localization related
mechanism for epilepsy. These findings were reviewed with the patient during the hospitalization.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to 1. Subtle, intermittent attenuation of alpha frequency activity in the left temporal region. 2. A handful of well defined auras characterized by rhythmic 4 hertz theta with clear frequency evolution. The characteristic seizure pattern for this patient includes attenuation of alpha in the region, then the theta and then some bilateral frontocentral spread. 3. Rare interictal findings including sharp waves in the left temporal region and sharply contoured theta. An example of this is at 4:35:37 a.m. on the morning of the second.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed gentleman admitted with new onset
tonic-clonic seizures, tachycardia. History of motor vehicle accident 1 year ago.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz 30 microvolt
posterior dominant rhythm. Central mu activity is observed but testing is not performed
to confirm this. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with slow
rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the
background. Photic stimulation is remarkable for a driving response and a bit of
photoelectric artifact.
HR: 140 bpm and irregular.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. A normal EEG
does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration,
a follow-up study may be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed male with a history of seizures started
on Depakote which produced an increase in facial twitching compatible with a tick.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The individual seems to be relatively drowsy but
when maximally awake, there is a 9Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Frequent facial
twitch artifact is noted. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha
rhythm and other features of drowsiness include slowing of the background with slowing
of the alpha rhythm.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abundant twitch artifact was identified but there were no
epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 26-year-old right-handed male with epilepsy, seizures characterized by dizziness followed by tonic clonic activity for 5 minutes.  Previous MVA.  Chronic, severe headaches.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenobarbital and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and brief attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy and if necessary a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.

report:
DATE OF STUDY:  08/18/2012-08/19/2012 for 24 hours.


CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation/flutter, congenital heart disease, obstructive sleep apnea, hypertension, diabetes, and epilepsy since age 12 described as tonic-clonic seizures during sleep, tongue biting, she is slightly confused for a few minutes.

MEDICATIONS:  The patient is currently off Dilantin and on Topamax and phenobarbital.

INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.

TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep stage I and stage II and deeper stages of sleep.  Please note that during sleep, even though she is using a CPAP on video, she has multiple arousals.

ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen at F7/T3 intermittently at 2-4 Hz and at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.

SEIZURES:  None.

EVENTS:  None.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a 4 day study revealed evidence on the left anterior temporal dysfunction, which is non-specific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform activity was captured.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal slowing.

report:
History:	52 yr old female with pmhx of afib and flutter, congenital heart disease, osa, htn, dm and epilepsy since the age of 12. szs. described as tonic clonic during sleep and awakens with tongue bite, feel slightly confused for a few minutes. presents for seizures
Medications:	Topamax, Phenobarbital
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 8.5-9.0Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Excessive diffuse 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes. Occasional polymorphic delta activity is present in the F7/T3 region during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  Single left frontal sharp transient followed by a K complex. Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  HR was 72 and irregular.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, left frontotemporal
Other, left, sharp transient
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of occasional focal slowing in the left frontotemporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific.  The single left frontal sharp transient prior to the K complex is of unclear significance. However the morphology is suspicious for a frontal epileptiform discharge and prolonged EEG may aid in clarifying its nature.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of occasional focal slowing in the left frontotemporal region.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific.  The single left frontal sharp transient prior to the K complex is of unclear significance. However the morphology is suspicious for a frontal epileptiform discharge and prolonged EEG may aid in clarifying its nature

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  68-year-old right-handed gentleman with hypertension, DM.  The patient had an episode of confusion with incontinence and FS=500.  Past history of staring spells. Recent Dx epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Insulin, GBP, many others
ROOM NUMBER:  550B.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.  This is primarily a drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with a glimpse of an 8 Hz alpha rhythm and excess beta and theta. Generalized background slowing.
Disorganization.
Shifting asymmetries including rare delta on the left and a decrease in amplitude on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this bedside recording, the amplitude asymmetry may be artifactual.  The infrequent left slowing may be correlated with imaging, but is an unremarkable finding in an adult of this age. PRIOR EEGS WERE NOT AVAILABLE FOR COMPARISON
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to,
Generalized background slowing. Disorganization. Shifting asymmetries including rare delta on the left and a decrease in amplitude on the right.

report: HISTORY: 69 y.o. male with a history of epilepsy ("strange sound, followed by tonic-clonic convulsion"), admitted with renal failure, referred for EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.  MEDICATIONS: Valproic acid  SEDATION: None listed  TECHNIQUE: A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.   DAY 1 (6/17/2016, 11:30 - 6/18/2016, 11:36)  BACKGROUND: The waking background is continuous, symmetric, fairly organized, and reactive.  Wakefulness consists of low amplitude theta and delta with fragments of a posterior dominant rhythm that approach 6.5 Hz.   Frequently, there are bursts of theta activity (lasting 1-5 seconds) seen most prominently over the left temporal region, and to a lesser extent the left parasagittal region, and less so over the right hemisphere. There is a >50% difference in amplitude between the hemispheres during these bursts, with higher amplitude over the left hemisphere.  There is no evolution.  Sleep is characterized by further slowing of the background. Sleep transients are not seen.  There is moderate generalized slowing.  As the study progresses the leads become increasingly degraded by artifact, rendering full interpretation of the background suboptimal.  PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  See "background" above  EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:  Occasional (1/hour to <1min) left fronto-temporal (F7>T1/T3 max) sharp waves  EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected  EKG: A single lead captured a heart rate in the 60s-70s  IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal long term video EEG due to: 1. The significance of the bursts of theta activity maximal over the left temporal region is unclear. They may represent right hemispheric dysfunction as they are seen with lower amplitude on that side. report:
HISTORY:

69 y.o. male with a history of epilepsy (semiology: "strange sound, followed by
tonic-clonic convulsion"), admitted with renal failure, referred for EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal
events.




MEDICATIONS: Valproic acid



SEDATION: None listed


TECHNIQUE:


A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.





BACKGROUND:





The waking background is continuous, symmetric, poorly organized, and not clearly reactive.  There
is no definite posterior dominant rhythm.  Background consists of low amplitude delta with admixed
theta.


Frequently, there are bursts of theta activity (lasting 1-5 seconds) seen most prominently over the left
temporal region, and to a lesser extent the left parasagittal region, and less so over the right
hemisphere. There is a >50% difference in amplitude between the hemispheres during these bursts,
with higher amplitude over the left hemisphere.  There is no evolution.





State change is not definitely present.


There is severe generalized slowing



PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

See



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

Occasional (1/hour to <1min) left fronto-temporal (F7>T1/T3 max) sharp waves



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.



EVENTS: No clinical or electrographic events reported or detected


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal long term video EEG due to:

1. Severe generalized slowing and suboptimal organization

2. Frequent bursts of theta activity seen most prominently over the left temporal region


3. Occasional (1/hour to <1min) left fronto-temporal (F7>T1/T3 max) sharp waves


CLINICAL CORRELATION:


These findings are indicators of left fronto-temporal epileptogenic potential superimposed on severe
diffuse cerebral dysfunction. The significance of the bursts of theta activity maximal over the left
temporal region is unclear. They may represent right hemispheric dysfunction as they are occur with
lower amplitude on that side. Alternatively, they may represent an abnormal rhythm over the left
temporal region. They do not meet electrographic criteria for seizure activity.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal long term video EEG due to 
1. Severe generalized slowing and suboptimal organization

2. Frequent bursts of theta activity seen most prominently over the left temporal region


3. Occasional (1/hour to <1min) left fronto-temporal (F7>T1/T3 max) sharp waves

multivitamin capsule, Take 1 capsule by mouth daily.

Insulin, Hydralazine, Heparin, Famotidine, Plavix, ASA, Atrovastatin, Theragran, Depacon Valproate,
Isordil,

TECHNIQUE:

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and verbal stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The  patient is somnolent throughout the study.  The background is characterized by the presence of

None

1. low-voltage, diffusely slow pattern

These findings are similar to the previous EEGs of June 17, 2016.  No seizures were recorded in this

I have personally reviewed this study, and this report represents my findings and conclusions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old gentleman with severe hypertension, right subcortical infarct of unknown age. The patient has intermittent, paroxysmal spells of right hemi body numbness followed by blacking out or lightheadedness. He has previous history of clonidine overdose.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Clonidine
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake through stage II sleep record. Sleep is relatively fragmented for this individual. He rapidly transitions from wakefulness to stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Vertex wave, K complexes, spindles and posts are noted in stage II sleep.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in a very drowsy subject.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal epileptiform features identified in this EEG. Additional evaluation of this individual's right-sided numbness may be evaluated.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in a very drowsy subject.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed gentleman with history of heroine addiction, one year history of palpitations, numbness right arm and leg, intermittent loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Clonidine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing, particularly in the right central region.  Wicket activity is noted, particularly on the left. Features of drowsiness include an increase in theta.  Vertex waves and spindles are noted in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmic slowing.   Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. There are rare, right central sharp waves noted, as well as a single posteriorly predominant spike at P4.  There are really only the two C4 spikes and the posterior spike.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left.
Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The sharp waves are in the region of this patient's cerebrovascular disease.  The shifting slowing is a nonspecific finding which can be
seen in the context of underlying ischemic cerebrovascular disease.  Overall, this was otherwise a sharply contoured, but otherwise unremarkable background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left. Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed woman with a tonic clonic seizure after Benadryl ingestion.
MEDICATIONS: Prozac, Lamictal, Abilify, Wellbutrin, Adderall, Fentanyl patch, Motrin, Caffeine, Loratadine, B12, Vitamin C.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.7 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of excess background theta. There is a slight amplitude asymmetry noted in the left parietal occipital region. Hyperventilation produces generous background rhythmic theta. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing followed by vertex waves and then POSTS and stage I sleep.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess theta.
2. A suggestion of an amplitude asymmetry noted in the left posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. The excess theta may be due to this patient's medication. The amplitude asymmetry with a bit of head rocking in the left posterior quadrant may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Excess theta. 2. A suggestion of an amplitude asymmetry noted in the left posterior quadrant.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  40 year old right handed female with 1 episode of generalized tonic clonic activity with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.  Her medical history is significant for severe headache, short term memory loss.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG and anterior temporal electrodes.  Awake record, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep records were seen.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is symmetric reactive to opening and posterior dominant alpha rhythm is present at 9 Hz with frequency of 22-70 microvolt amplitude.  Beta rhythm is also seen with 15-25 Hz frequency and 10-15 microvolt amplitude in the frontal central region in small amounts.  Stage 1 and stage 2 sleep records are also seen. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are normal.  There is focal slowing noted at F8, T4, and T4 electrodes of 2-4 Hz frequency and 20-70 microvolt amplitude, however, seen occasionally.  No seizures are seen.
HR:  N/A
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional focal slowing seen in the right mid and anterior temporal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with focal cerebral dysfunction in the right temporal lobe which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Occasional focal slowing seen in the right mid and anterior temporal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 58 year old left handed male with intractable epilepsy, complex partial seizures, last seizure unclear.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Xanax, Prozac, Celexa, Prilosec, Citalopram, Ambien
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake record with hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9Hz, 40 microvolt posterior-dominant rhythm. The alpha rhythm is sometimes disrupted from the right hemisphere. There is some shifting arrhythmic delta activity identified bilaterally. High amplitude right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes are observed most of which are maximum at T-2 but some of which are maximum T4 and T6. All are high amplitude, sometimes exceeding 100 microvolts with a generous field of spread within the right hemisphere and disruption of faster
frequency activity. Hyperventilation clearly accentuates the epileptiform activity. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. There is some bilateral posterior slowing and drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. The focal right greater than left posterior slowing is noted in photic stimulation. Stage I sleep starts to emerge at the end of the EEG but sleep is not sustained.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. High amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes.
2. Right hemisphere and right temporal focal slowing.
3. Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum but most of which are maximum in the temple regions
4. A modest degree of background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a structural process as well as a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. High amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes. 2. Right hemisphere and right temporal focal slowing. 3. Sharp waves in the right hemisphere with variable maximum but most of which are maximum in the temple regions
4. A modest degree of background slowing.

report:
History:	63 YO MALE WITH HX OF SZ. PT IS COMPLAINING OF NOT SLEEPING AT
NIGHT AND FEELING DIZZY IN THE MORNING. PER PT BROTHER LAST SZ WAS
THIS MORNING.
Medications:	CARBAMAZEPINE, ZONISAMIDE, RANITIDINE, MELOXICAM
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and ekg
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
flash rates from ___ to ___ fps.  HR 66
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present, but stage 2
sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide
additional information

report:
History:	34 year old woman with a reported history of seizures for ~ 10 years.  Last seizure 
	occurred ~2 years ago. 
	
	Patient is about 3 months pregnant.  Patient has braids, so distances may not be 
	accurate.
Medications:	Dilantin
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG 
	electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9-9.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates 
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over 
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal 
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.

	No focal slowing or epileptiform discharges
	Sleep, stage 2
	POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients of sleep), prominent
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 21-minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 35year old right handed woman with epilepsy until age 15, now 3 tonic /clonic seizures this past month. Family history of epilepsy .She previously had 1 to 2 seizures per year.
MEDICATIONS: Lamotrigine, Tegretol, Klonopin, Albuterol
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of  electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG Is well organized with  a 10.5Hz alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of theta. At the end of  hyperventilation, there is a high amplitude frontally predominant paroxysmal burst. There  appears to be an underlying spike or fast component prior to 4 bursts of 3to 4 Hz activity. A  second burst is noted at the close of t he hyperventilation, and this burst is a bit more posteriorly  predominant with a discrete either spike or fast activity prior to again 3 Hz discharges. The  background Immediately returns to a relatively awake pattern. Following this, another  paroxysmal burst without as clearly defined spike activity is noted, but there is some faster  frequency activity, similar to paroxysmal fast activity, noted prior to this with some both 13 and 19Hz activity. Features of drowsiness include stow-rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 3 to_4 Hz paroxysmal higher amplitude delta with suspicious underlying spike activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The activity was sometimes frontal but sometimes occipital. It is  not classic spike and wave activity but is likely an adult form of the generalized spike and wave  activity. If additional information is needed, a followup study can be considered.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. 3 to_4 Hz paroxysmal higher amplitude delta with suspicious underlying spike activity.

report:
History:	38 year old woman with a history of seizures for the last ~15 years.  Her typical
seizure frequency is ~ 1-2 seizures per year with no seizures in over 1 year.
Medications:	Tegretol, Lamictal, Klonopin, Zonegran
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10.5-11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Sleep, stage 2
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 1-hour EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on
a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 1-hour EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. The lack of epileptiform discharges on
a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be
secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
HISTORY:
A 47-year-old woman found in a drug house with seizure-like activity. Abnormal MRI suggesting encephalitis but no cells in
CSF
ROOM NUMBER:
Emergency room.
MEDICATIONS:
Ativan 8 mg.
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement
with one channel of EKG. The patient is examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
The background EEG begins With a marked asymmetry between the two hemispheres. It is very low-voltage suppressed
with a paucity of beta activity on the left. In contrast, the right includes generous beta, diffusely. In this relatively
low-voltage pattern on the left, there are subtle, periodic sharp waves or sharply contoured delta at C3-P3. As the
recording continues, the patient is starting to move about, there is additional beta activity noted from both hemispheres.
The periodic complexes are still apparent underneath the muscle and movement artifact. Stimulation of the patient
produces an increase in muscle artifact. As the recording continues, the epileptiform activity transitions to a bit more of a
frontotemporal broadly contoured discharge with a broad field of spread.
Heart rate 104 BPM.

IMPRESSION:
Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1.
Initially, a markedly slow and suppressed pattern on the left.
2.
An asymmetry that persists throughout the record with a much slower pattern on the left.
3.
A periodic complex seen intermittently from the left. The patient was a bit more agitated by the end of the record, but
on the video, no jerking can be discerned during the video to correlate with the periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
In this individual with recent seizures characterized by right-sided jerking, the periodic complexes and focal slowing should
be correlated with imaging to exclude a structural pathology. No prolonged seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Initially, a markedly slow and suppressed pattern on the left. 2. An asymmetry that persists throughout the record with a much slower pattern on the left. 3. A periodic complex seen intermittently from the left. The patient was a bit more agitated by the end of the record, but
on the video, no jerking can be discerned during the video to correlate with the periodic complexes.

of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  70 year old right handed female with complaints of seizure last year, CVA, diabetes, hypertension, not taking medications for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Zantac, Metoprolol, Nifedipine, Hyzaar, Lipitor, Insulin, Omeprazole, Gabapentin, Metformin, Furosemide, not taking the prescribed Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedure including photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 8.5-9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedure was photic stimulation, produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T3 rarely throughout the study.
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts and a frequency of 2-4 Hz.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.   Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region.
2.   Focal slow waves in that region.

were seen.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region. 2.   Focal slow waves in that region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old man right handed with history of seizures as a child, now with recurrent seizures and concurrent insomnia, anxiety, depression and migraines.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Lamictal, Temazepam, Seroquel, Effexor, Letherezia (?)
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement as well as anterotemporal electrodes and EKG electrodes.  The EEG was recorded with photic stimulation and hyperventilation was performed.  Sleep stage I and stage II were recorded.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Frequent bilateral temporalis muscle artifact seen during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontal central beta.  Sleep stage I and stage II is recorded.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation presented no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
There are 2 short bursts of less than 400 milliseconds seen with left frontal predominant sharp waves and slow waves which appeared to have a bilateral component and distribution more consistent with fragment of general spike and wave, however, a focal left frontal spike cannot be excluded.
SEIZURES:   None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with evidence of cortical irritability which is suggestive of an idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  However, the slight asymmetry of the spike and wave fragments may also suggest a focal origin with secondary bilateral synchrony.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Left frontal asymmetric spike and wave discharges likely fragments of generalized spike and wave

report:
History:	29 YR WOMAN WITH CHANGE IN EVENTS. PT NOW WITH EVENTS THAT SHE
TALKS INCOHERENTLY, BUT NOT AWARE HAPPENS 1-2 DAY. PRIOR EEGS.
Medications:	NONE
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
During maximal wakefulness, the background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm,
which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present,
maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta
activity and becomes more disorganized, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes
intermittent.  Vertex waves appear that are at times asymmetric, and frequent generalized bursts of
high amplitude theta and delta activity are seen.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to
moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is present in the left temporal and rarely in the right
temporal regions during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  Predominately during
drowsiness, polymorphic high amplitude left temporal sharp waves appear with variable fields with
phase reversal at F7, T3, T5 and at times develop into a pseudoperiodic pattern.  Rare right
temporal sharp waves are also present with phase reversal F8 and T4.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce additional
abnormalities.  HR is 66.
Summary of Findings:
Sharp waves, frequent, bilateral (L>R) temporal
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, left temporal
Focal slowing, polymorphic, rare, right temporal
Disorganization, intermittent, bilateral (L>R) hemispheric
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of frequent epileptiform discharges
over the left temporal region and rarely over the right temporal region.  These findings are
indicative of a potentially epileptogenic foci in these regions.In addition there is  intermittent focal
slowing in the left temporal region and rarely in the right temporal region.  These findings are
indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific.  No clinical or
electrographic seizures are present.  In the setting of multiple prior EEG without clear epileptiform
features, this record now supports a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy, and clinical and neuroimaging correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of frequent epileptiform discharges
over the left temporal region and rarely over the right temporal region.  These findings are
indicative of a potentially epileptogenic foci in these regions.In addition there is  intermittent focal
slowing in the left temporal region and rarely in the right temporal region.  These findings are
indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-specific.  No clinical or
electrographic seizures are present.  In the setting of multiple prior EEG without clear epileptiform
features, this record now supports a diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy, and clinical and neuroimaging correlation is recommended

Medications:	KEPPRA, MORPHINE, DILANTIN
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, obtunded
Description:
There is no PDR and no AP gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of attenuated
polymorphic delta>> theta activity with increase in theta activity with stimulation.  Low amplitude
sleep spindle-like waveforms are noted.  They are slightly more prominent over the right.
Frequent brief bursts of higher amplitude polymorphic sharply contoured delta activity are present
over the left, maximal over temporocentral regions.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is reactivity to visual, auditory,
tactile, or noxious stimuli.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate up to 120 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, moderate-to-severe
Focal slowing, polymorphic, frequent, severe, left hemispheric, most prominent over
No electrographic seizures
Other, reactive
Interpretation:
This is an is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to moderate-to-severe diffuse slowing, voltage
attenuation and frequent focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the left
temporocentral region. Diffuse slowing is etiologically nonspecific indicator of moderate to severe
diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction,
likely structural in etiology and is consistent with a history of focal subdural hematoma status post
evacuation.  No clinical or electrographic seizures are present.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to moderate-to-severe diffuse slowing, voltage
attenuation and frequent focal left hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the left
temporocentral region. Diffuse slowing is etiologically nonspecific indicator of moderate to severe
diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction,
likely structural in etiology and is consistent with a history of focal subdural hematoma status post
evacuation.  No clinical or electrographic seizures are present

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with traumatic brain injury, failure to thrive, status post PEG and trach.  The patient now awake and alert after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Trileptal.  Others, metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is quite fragile, but awake.  He is responsive to questions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The right hemisphere is low voltage and relatively featureless.  The left hemisphere is remarkable for a craniotomy defect, but also periodic, high amplitude delta activity with a left central parietal spike and wave complex.  The spike and wave complex is periodic in nature and has the periodicity of about 8 per 10 seconds.  There is a small amount of waxing and waning of the epileptiform discharge, but no clear ictal pattern.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta in the left hemisphere as well as eye movement.
Heart rate:  80 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region.
Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient seems to be awake and interactive despite the discharge described above.  In addition, stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response on top of the periodic complex.  The discharge described above may be a chronic finding or a post-ictal finding, but does not appear to be to be a true seizure.   Ongoing vigilance is suggested. No clinical seizures noted at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region. Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 61-year-old male with epilepsy.  Has complex neurosurgical history including traumatic brain injury, subarachnoid hemorrhage, subdural hematoma, aphagia, skull defect, and past left-sided edema.  Past history of recurrent seizures in July 2014, recently admitted to the hospital in February 2015.  No recent reported seizures, but previous status epilepticus and pleds from the left.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, atorvastatin, Keppra, metoprolol, phenobarbital, and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with acceptable impedances, although there is a prominent craniotomy defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background from the right hemisphere includes a low voltage, continuous, primarily beta frequency pattern.  The left hemisphere demonstrates a prominent breach rhythm.  There are bursts of rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity of 1 to 3 seconds duration.  Some of these are associated with a sharp waves.  The bursts of rhythmic slowing with left mid temporal sharp waves are more prominent as the patient became drowsy.
Heart rate: 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A marked interhemispheric asymmetry.
A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity.
A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult, who has been evaluated for status epilepticus and seizures.  The epileptiform activity today is primarily left mid temporal, which in some ways is similar to the continuous EEG monitoring.  A contrast to February 2015 EEG monitor, which identified epileptiform activity from the left hemisphere, but that epileptiform activity was much more prominent in the central parietal region.
This EEG continues to support a focal mechanism for this patient's seizures.  The epileptiform activity is in the region of the patient's head trauma.  The bilateral background slowing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to A marked interhemispheric asymmetry. A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity. A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 61-year-old male with traumatic brain injury, left skull fracture, the patient presented with recurrent seizures today, some of which were prolonged.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, oxybutynin, Trileptal, Keppra, phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Impedances were generally under 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.  The skull defect was as described above
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is quite drowsy.  Generous beta is noted but there is no well-defined alpha rhythm.  Breach rhythm is noted on the left with higher amplitude activity in this region.  Sharply contoured slowing was noted with T1 and T3 phase reversal with most bursts about 500 milliseconds in duration.  Tactile stimulation of the patient produces an arousal response with a glimpse of a 10 Hz alpha rhythm on the right and more of a theta pattern on the left.  The patient then returns to a drowsy state.
Heart rate 96 BPM
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal EEG due to continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
Sharply contoured delta from the left maximum mid temporal.
Continuous
Mild slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is supportive of a structural or functional process on the left.  For this patient with recurrent status epilepticus, this record demonstrates an ongoing irritative process.  This EEG is similar to previous studies of April 2015.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION Abnormal EEG due to continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere. Sharply contoured delta from the left maximum mid temporal. Continuous
Mild slowing on the right.

report:
History:	60 year old man with a history of seizures and TBI. Patient with a recent
breakthrough seizure.
Medications:	BACLOFEN, CELEXA, KEPPRA, DILANTIN, ,
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Voltages are diffusely very low.  The background consists of a very low amplitude 10.5 Hz alpha
activity posteriorly with expected AP gradient.  Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.
Symmetrical vertex waves and sleep spindles are present.
Continuous subtle polymorphic delta activity is present in the right frontotemporal region during
wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, right frontotemporal, subtle continuous delta
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Low voltage
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep 26 minute EEG because of continuous subtle focal
slowing in the right frontotemporal region.  This finding is indicative of a focal structural lesion in
this region.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical
diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep 26 minute EEG because of continuous subtle focal
slowing in the right frontotemporal region.  This finding is indicative of a focal structural lesion in
this region.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical
diagnosis of epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as
benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
History:	50yo M with refractory localization-related epilepsy due to right mesial temporal
sclerosis. Admitted yesterday for breakthrough seizures. Now here for EEG
monitoring for pre-surgical evaluation.
Medications:	tegretol XR 800mg BID, phenobarbital 60mg HS, lisinopril, nicotine patch
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 8.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows
further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Intermittent, independent bilateral anterior temporal focal slowing, right more than left.  No
epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does
not produce any effect.  HR 90
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, bilateral (R>L) temporal, anterior
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and asleep due to intermittent, independent bilateral anterior
temporal focal slowing, right more than left.  These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators
of mild focal cerebral dysfunction in those regions.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake and asleep due to intermittent, independent bilateral anterior
temporal focal slowing, right more than left.  These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators
of mild focal cerebral dysfunction in those regions

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old right handed male with complex partial epilepsy described as a feeling of spinning, hot flashes with loss of consciousness, and bowel and bladder incontinence.  Past history of closed head injury.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  With testing the alpha improves to 10 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Wicket is noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record.  The patient is falling asleep during hyperventilation with vertex waves and spindles.  There are some normal variants, including small sharp spikes of sleep, but there is also some left temporal focal slowing.  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Again, subtle left temporal focal slowing is noted.  Simple sharp waves, as are common in normal variants, are also noted in the left temporal region. These are again noted with photic stimulation.  The patient is once again falling asleep during photic stimulation.

HR:    60 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Subtle left temporal focal slowing.
2. Left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The left temporal sharp waves have a simple morphology as can be seen in a normal variant.  However, they occur in the context of focal slowing and are more suggestive of a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  In comparison to a previous EEG, both EEGs demonstrate some of the same normal variants and some of the same unique challenges.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at T1/F7-T3 with an amplitude of 20-80 microvolts seen very frequently throughout the recording.
Focal slow waves seen almost continuously over the left hemisphere at F7/T1 and very infrequently in the right hemisphere at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal sharp waves in the left anterior temporal region.
Independent bitemporal slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization-related epilepsy with seizures likely arising from the left anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of bilateral independent anterior temporal focal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed woman with new-onset seizures and end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, Hydralazine, Plavix, Metoprolol, ASA, Lipitor, Lisinopril.
REASON FOR STUDY:  New-onset seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that best reaches 7 Hz and which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is a lack of normal frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.  Throughout the recording, there appears to be diffuse generalized theta, 5 to 7 Hz discharge, that is intermixed with bursts of high-amplitude delta seen bilaterally with multiple sharp components throughout those discharges that last, at times, up to 30 to 40 seconds.  There is no clear evolution or change during these discharges.  The morphology is consistent with triphasic waves, but there are some intermixed sharp waves that we will discuss in "abnormal discharges" below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen independently at F7/T3, as well as F8/T4, and at times FP2.
Bursts of generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Triphasic waves.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Multifocal sharp waves.
Bursts of generalized slow waves.
Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of multiple focal cerebral irritability and dysfunction, in addition to diffuse cerebral dysfunction which may be, at least in part, due to a metabolic derangement.  No seizures were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Multifocal sharp waves. Bursts of generalized slow waves. Triphasics in the midst of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 20-year-old male with meningitis at age 2, associated stroke, epilepsy and brain injury.  History of brain injury at age 1.  He is seizure free for the last 5 years.  History of high lipoprotein A.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Flovent, albuterol, aspirin.

INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  Impedances were less than 5 kilo-ohms with the exception of the T1 and T2 electrodes, 5.9 and 5.2 respectively.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is low to medium amplitude with a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm.  Prominent lateral rectus eye artifact was noted.

Hyperventilation was performed early in the record.  The patient seemed to be falling asleep during hyperventilation.

During hyperventilation, and just following hyperventilation, high amplitude right anterior temporal spike and sharp waves were noted.  In addition, there is some subtle focal slowing in the right to mid anterior temporal region noted as the patient becomes drowsy following hyperventilation.  The remainder of the EEG is relatively symmetric but there is also some variable voltage subtle slowing noted at F3.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, rare right anterior spike and slow wave complexes were identified reaching 70 microvolts.  These were noted as the patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep.

Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.  In addition, in photic stimulation, there is some subtle, lower voltage left frontocentral sharp waves with fast activity.  The patient seemed to be drifting off to sleep at the end of photic stimulation and again the right anterior temporal, well defined spike and slow wave complexes were noted.

Heart rate:  Irregular, 60 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
1. Well defined higher amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and drowsiness.
2. Subtle, intermittent focal slowing in the same distribution.
3. Additional area of the brain with lower voltage, fast activity or a lower voltage spike in the left frontocentral region with, at times, some associated focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous EEG which captured only wakefulness, epileptiform activity was identified in hyperventilation and drowsiness.  Some of this was in the region of the previous right hemispheric infarct but there was also some lower voltage activity in the left frontocentral region.

Additional evaluation for the irregular heart rate, noted in 2012 and 2013, may be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to 1. Well defined higher amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and drowsiness. 2. Subtle, intermittent focal slowing in the same distribution. 3. Additional area of the brain with lower voltage, fast activity or a lower voltage spike in the left frontocentral region with, at times, some associated focal slowing.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is well organized, but there is an asymmetry of the alpha rhythm.  The alpha rhythm is 50 to 60 microvolts, approximately 10 Hz on the left and consistently 0.7 Hz faster on the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in amplitude of the background.  Hyperventilation produces bilateral slowing.  Wicket study was identified, but no sharp waves were noted.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted. Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.

HR:    60 to 72 bpm and irregular.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A slower alpha rhythm on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The slower alpha on the left suggests pathology in that hemisphere.  No sharp waves were identified, although Wicket was noted.  A repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. A slower alpha rhythm on the left.

report:

Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
Heart:  64 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Shifting slowing from the right or left hemisphere in relaxed wakefulness.
A subtle asymmetry with somewhat slower activity in the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  Wicket activity was present.  A follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested to exclude epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Shifting slowing from the right or left hemisphere in relaxed wakefulness. A subtle asymmetry with somewhat slower activity in the left hemisphere.

report:

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old man status post craniectomy and C1-C2 laminectomy with a history of cryptococcal meningitis, now evaluating for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, insulin, metoprolol, Lovenox, ceftriaxone, Risperdal, and dexamethasone.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead  EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while poorly responsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Heart rate 110 to 120.
The record opens to an abnormal, diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontal central beta.  At times as the patient blinks or moves there appears to be some artifact and there appears to be slight improvement in the frequencies, but overall he remains generally slow at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  No activating procedures were performed.  No clear sleep architecture is seen.
Abnormal discharges:  Generalized slowing at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous moderate to severe generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of moderate to severe diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous moderate to severe generalized slowing.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 34-year-old male with history of alcohol withdrawal seizure, was discharged, when he had a general tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Serax, thiamine, Lovenox, nicotine patch, folic acid.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches at 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Bursts of generalized spike and waves which is anterior predominant and symmetric, and bursts of 3-4 Hz were seen intermittently, at times with preceding polyspikes throughout the recording.  Some of them appeared more asymmetric on the right than the left, but the majority appear symmetric.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The discharges seen above are most commonly seen with a generalized type of epilepsy.  However, some of them appeared slightly asymmetric and may suggest a possible focal onset with secondary generalization.  Repeated EEG capturing seizures or clinical followup may aid in elucidating the clear classification.  These findings were reported to the consult team as soon as the EEG was read.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed female with left carotid stenosis and left CEA with a history of left stroke in June of 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Percocet, Fentanyl, Vecuronium, Isoflurane
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left carotid endarterectomy.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed during left carotid endarterectomy using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during the entire operation.  Feedback was given to the surgeon as well as discussions with Anesthesia was had throughout the procedure.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The baseline record revealed a posterior dominant rhythm that reached 9-10 Hz which was reactive to eye opening.  At times there was some focal slowing seen at F7/T3 at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  Otherwise, there was nice frontocentral beta. During the procedure the common carotid was clamped at 10:32:36 and the internal carotid was clamped at 10:31:50.  After clamping no change in the faster frequencies over the left hemisphere were noted and this was informed to the surgeon at 3 and 5 minutes.  The recording continued to be monitored and there continued to be no change at 11:48:13 a.m.  The carotids were unclamped and again there was no change in the faster frequencies in the recording.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This was an uneventful left carotid endarterectomy with no changes.  Feedback was given continuously to the surgeon about the EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG consistent with symmetric background of 9 Hz with no change in the background upon carotid artery clamping.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status and seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old female with history of mental illness, migraines, and seizures who presented to the hospital with 3 episodes of seizures described as tonic clonic and confusion after stopping her Xanax for 2 days.
MEDICATIONS:  Lorazepam, phenobarbital, Tylenol, vitamin B12.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, drowsiness, and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of diffuse beta.  The patient is mainly in drowsiness or sleep, stage I.
Hyperventilation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at T3 and at times at T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Excessive theta in wakefulness.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  78 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral mid temporal regions, but of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  In addition, there was evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect.  The excess beta supports a possibility of benzo or barbiturate use as a cause of the diffuse dysfunction.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral independent mid temporal slowing, as well as excessive theta in wakefulness with superimposed diffuse beta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old man who presented with a chief complaint of left-sided numbness and shaking.  While in the emergency room he was observed having shaking while in the CAT scan.  Past medical history is notable for diabetes, hypertension and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zolpidem, lisinopril, aspirin, insulin, and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were  performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well modulated low amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No clear sleep is captured.  Intermittent polymorphic delta activity is captured over the right anterior temporal region.  Hyperventilation produces no change in the background.  Photic stimulation induces symmetric occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent moderate right anterior temporal slowing.
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal awake only, 24 minute EEG due to intermittent moderate anterior right temporal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction and this case could be structural in etiology.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal awake only, 24 minute EEG due to intermittent moderate anterior right temporal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction and this case could be structural in etiology.  No epileptiform discharges are captured, however, stage II sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indication for seizures persistent a repeat study with stage II sleep may be of benefit

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old man with a history of left-sided numbness and weakness and shaking and falling down stairs.  History of diabetes, hypertension, and neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Altace, Ativan, and Oxycontin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a background, which appears to have diffuse beta and mainly in sleep.  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm, but this may be obscured by the diffuse beta.  Overall, the patient easily drowses off and is in limited wakefulness.  During hyperventilation, there appears to be some bursts of rhythmic bifrontal slowing.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient reaches stage I and stage II sleep.  Please note that at times there is also rhythmic bursts of theta, which are anterior maximal, which are most consistent with drowsiness, however, some of them have a slightly suspicious appearance.
SEIZURES:  None.

function.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 21-year-old woman with an unknown early developmental history, depression, and posttraumatic stress syndrome.  The patient has been having an episode to right arm rotation and had a seizure with loss of consciousness and incontinence.  She continues to feel, as if she is experiencing myoclonic jerks.  I got interrupted and I did not do the history.

MEDICATIONS: Lorazepam, Remeron

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is a bedside record without hyperventilation and photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there was a 10Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta.

In wakefulness, there were bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic high amplitude 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.

No impairment of awareness was noted with the events.  The patient was able to answer questions even with very brief discharges, but again discharges are typically 1 to 1.5 seconds after going slow activity, lasting an another second at maximum duration.

The technologist notes 1 or 2 movements of the patient, but no definitive myoclonus was captured.

Heart rate 84 BPM.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  For this young adult with unclear medical history and a 1st ever seizure and myoclonus, this EEG is most compatible with a inherited, generalized mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1. frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike in wave activity occurring in brief bursts.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old right-handed male who has a history of epilepsy since 2007, has about 1 seizure every 1-2 years, presently not on any medications.  Last seizure was several nights ago.  The seizure was preceded by a severe headache.

MEDICATIONS:  None.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  There was a technical limitation with the T6 electrode which persisted even after it was fixed by the technician.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9.5 Hz in frequency and 20-40 microvolts in amplitude best seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  In drowsiness there is diffuse rhythmic theta bursts in all the channels.

There is an occasional burst of focal slowing seen in the left frontocentral region.

Hyperventilation was performed which showed a diffuse slowing of the record and increase in amplitude.

Photic stimulation showed minimal driving at 13 Hz but no abnormalities.

Heart rate 60 beats per minute.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is suggestive of a possible underlying structural abnormality in the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.  No epileptiform discharges were identified.  A more prolonged EEG recording may be more helpful to identify spikes or sharp waves.

Attestation: I personally reviewed the EEG with the trainee and agree with the report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to occasional bursts of focal slowing on the left frontocentral and frontotemporal regions.
