report:
History:	22 year old woman with new onset seizures.
Medications:	None
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10-10.5Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions. Brief (1-3 seconds) bursts of diffuse moderate-to-high amplitude 6 Hz theta activity are noted during wakefulness. Their frequency and duration increase in drowsiness and they are no longer present during sleep. During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present. No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates. An episode of left pinky twitching occurs from ~7 min 45 sec till ~ 10 min 15 sec into the recording. This is not associated with an abnormal activity on the scalp EEG.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
Other, episode of left pinky twitching without EEG correlate Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 27 minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Patient rapidly transitions into sleep. Bursts of diffuse theta activity likely represent intrusions of sleep architecture into drowsiness. This could be explained by an excessively drowsy patient. An episode of left pinky twitching is captured (it lasts ~ 2 min 30 sec). There is no abnormal activity captured on a scalp EEG. However, only ~ 25% of simple partial seizures are captured on a scalp EEG.
.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a NORMAL 27 minute EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep. Patient rapidly transitions into sleep. Bursts of diffuse theta activity likely represent intrusions of sleep architecture into drowsiness. This could be explained by an excessively drowsy patient. An episode of left pinky twitching is captured (it lasts ~ 2 min 30 sec). There is no abnormal activity captured on a scalp EEG. However, only ~ 25% of simple partial seizures are captured on a scalp EEG

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Recent onset refractory, recurrent seizures, all of which began with left arm numbness or movement.  Patient describes bilateral upper extremity movements without loss of consciousness, but now has began to have events during sleep with incontinence and confusion.  Recent allergic reaction to oxcarbazepine.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage 2 sleep record.  It was technically acceptable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  In early drowsiness, the background EEG demonstrates background slowing with slowing of the alpha rhythm, a small degree of disorganization and background theta.  Vertex waves, spindles, and posts were noted in stage 2 sleep.
Hyperventilation was performed with good effort producing some background rhythmic slowing.  Photic stimulation was remarkable for eye movement artifact, but no significant pathology.
Heart rate 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  This is the 2nd normal EEG at this institution.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
HISTORY:

49 y.o. female with a history of multiple daily seizures which are
uncontrolled, referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Valproic acid, Topamax, Ativan


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.




EEG BACKGROUND:







The waking background during early portions of the tracing demonstrated a large amount of
generalized beta activity, muscle and eye blink artifact along with moderate amounts of low to
medium amplitude 10-11 Hz posterior rhythmic activity. Soon after the recording started, 4-5/s
rhythmic muscle artifact was seen in left ear reference montages. At about 1:44:05, rhythmic 4-5/s
muscle artifact increased in amplitude and rapidly generalized, associated with increased heart rate
from 75/m to 132/m. Video monitoring demonstrated the patient to have side to side and less
frequent back and forth head movement along with shaking of her upper body, with head slightly
rotated more to the right than left. This activity persisted until about 1:47:50 and then rapidly
subsided, although slight movements of left hand could be seen intermittently on video recording.
During abnormal shaking movements and afterwards, EEG technologist and physician were at the
bedside examining and speaking with the






patient. She had occasional eye opening and closing and slow head nodding in response to
questions, with EEG background demonstrating a mixture of generalized beta activity, muscle
artifact, EKG artifact and frontal eye movement artifact.




Sleep is not captured



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.


HEART RATE:


EKG monitor revealed variable heart rate from 75-132 per minute, as detailed above.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal EEG due to an apparent clinical seizure associated with 4-5/s rhythmic muscle
and movement artifact on EEG along with upper body and side to side shaking head movements. No
pathologic spikes or sharp waves were seen in the recording. A subcortical seizure focus which was
not detected on surface EEG is a possible consideration, although nonepileptic pseudoseizure will
need to be excluded with further neurologic evaluation.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal EEG due to an apparent clinical seizure associated with 4-5/s rhythmic muscle
and movement artifact on EEG along with upper body and side to side shaking head movements. No
pathologic spikes or sharp waves were seen in the recording. A subcortical seizure focus which was
not detected on surface EEG is a possible consideration, although nonepileptic pseudoseizure will
need to be excluded with further neurologic evaluation

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 81-year-old woman for EEG monitoring for possible hypothermic protocol.  Temp 34.6.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, fentanyl, and midazolam.
INTRODUCTION:  Intraoperative monitoring was recorded from 7:21 a.m. until 9:48 a.m.  This recording was performed in anticipation of possible utilization of hypothermic protocol.  Physician was available for remote review and physician remote review was employed for 50 minutes, from 8:10 until 9 a.m.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG begins with the patient somewhat sedated.  The patient is awake with a posterior dominant rhythm with a generous beta, theta, and occasional shifting slowing.  An 8.3 Hz alpha rhythm was noted.  At 7:42, anesthetic medications are employed and EEG demonstrates an increase in background slowing.
Anesthetic medications are adjusted from 9 a.m. and EEG recording is intermittently pause for Bovie and other maneuvers.  The EEG demonstrates an intermittently discontinuous pattern.
Shortly after 9 a.m., the surgeon changes the operative strategy and EEG monitoring was not required.  The team signed out of the OR at 9:48, at which point there was a discontinuous pattern, compatible with anesthesia.
HEART RATE 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Limited intraoperative monitoring demonstrated symmetric, relatively normal awake baseline and the appearance of a burst suppression pattern with the utilization of anesthesia

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 25-year-old right-handed woman with adult-onset recurrent seizures with previous normal EEG, events without aura, loss of consciousness, and associated injury.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  Stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTs.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background as well as a focal response.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Notable findings in this EEG include rhythmic left temporal theta which waxes and wanes, increasing in drowsiness.  In addition, occasional left anterior temporal sharp waves with after-going slow waves, medium to high amplitude were noted in wakefulness around the time of photic stimulation.  Photic stimulation also seems to accentuate the rhythmic slowing and sharp waves.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Rhythmic left temporal slowing.
Left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These are new findings for this individual and support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Rhythmic left temporal slowing. Left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 23-year-old woman with bipolar disease, limited education, 5 weeks postpartum.  Mother reports abrupt onset of head bobbing, arm shaking, and episodes with loss of consciousness for the past 48 hours.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A 30-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient had limited communication skills and a translator was used during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is awake with a 12 hertz alpha rhythm generous, low voltage, frontal central beta.
In wakefulness and early drowsiness, brief bursts of high amplitude, generalized spike and wave activity were noted.  Some of these seem to begin with a burst of fast activity in the occipital regions with a 3-5 Hz spike and wave complex.  The complexes vary in the frequency, many of them are 3 hertz with a polyspike, but the later spikes in the complex are always consistently slower.  Generally, these are frontally predominant spike and wave complexes and those that occur out of drowsiness do not have this beta buzz prior to the spikes.  The patient is noted to have a subtle head bob and sometimes some movement of her legs during the bursts.  She seems to have clinical symptoms with bursts that are 2 seconds in duration.  The bursts are present in wakefulness and early drowsiness.  Hyperventilation may have increase the duration of the spike and wave and polyspike and wave complexes.  In addition, during hyperventilation, there may be a little bit more fast activity.  The patient was otherwise able to answer questions, before and after the discharges.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  Spike and wave activity was noted with a 21 hertz discharge, but was not prolonged relative to other sections of the record.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The EEG pattern described above is most compatible with generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  The patient's behavior of the head bobbing and sometimes the leg movements are not outside of normal for a absence seizure.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave activity with bursts of 3-5 Hz frontally predominant spike and wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old gentleman status post acoustic neuroma resection, June 2014.  The patient treated briefly with Keppra, which was resumed after the patient had a recurrent seizure.  Episode in 2015 with seizure characterized by impairment of awareness.  Chronic left headache, left facial twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 8.5-9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  A clear breach rhythm was noted from the left with higher amplitude alpha on the left in comparison to the right.  There is prominent muscle artifact noted in the left frontal temporal electrodes with fast activity of approximately 35 hertz.  As the patient becomes drowsy, focal slowing is identified in the left mid temporal region.  The patient does not sustain deeper stages of sleep.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving response.  Hyperventilation was deferred.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
intermittent focal slowing noted in drowsiness from the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The breach rhythm identified above is an anticipated finding following craniotomy and is congruent with the previous left cranial surgery.  There is prominent 35 hertz fast activity noted in the left temporalis/ scalp over congruent with the patient's clinical symptoms and he has complaint of an ongoing muscle spasm in that area.  (Muscle artifact)
This is the 3rd EEG for this individual.  It demonstrates significant improvement in comparison to the immediate postoperative study in June 2014.
No epileptiform features were noted in the last two EEGS.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
intermittent focal slowing noted in drowsiness from the left temporal region.

A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with Tl/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.

report:
History:	53 year old woman with new onset episodes of right arm shaking.


Medications: Sedation: EEG Type: Technique:


None


Routine, awake & drowsy
International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation




Description:
The background consists of low-to-moderate amplitude polymorphic 8 Hz theta activity and weak AP gradient.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-7Hz activity is present throughout the recording and increases during drowsiness.   During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.

Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity is present in the left frontocentral region during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.   Frequent left frontocentral sharp waves are present.  Maximal scalp negativity occurs over F3/C3 electrodes.   Frequency of sharp waves increases during drowsiness.  They are often periodic and semi periodic (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), 1-2 Hz,  occurring in brief runs (up to 20 seconds long).  Two seizures are captured at - 7 min 17 seconds and 22 min 42 seconds into the recording.  They last - 12 seconds and 43 seconds, respectively.  The first seizure does not an obvious clinical correlate.  The second seizure is associated with rhythmic right hand shaking.

Electrographically seizure #1 is characterized by rhythmic left frontocentral sharp waves that rapidly increase in frequency (up to 2 Hz) and amplitude.  Onset of seizure #2 is obscured by EMG.  There is appearance of rhythmic F3/C3 sharp waves that gradually increase in frequency (up to 4 Hz) and amplitude and speed to Cz electrode.  Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces diffuse symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation is not performed.

Summary of Findings:
Seizure, two, left, frontocentral: sz #2 associated with right arm shaking
PLEDs {periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges), occasional, left, frontocentral; also quasi-PLE Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, moderate, left, frontocentral

Interpretation:
This is a very abnormal awake and drowsy 24 minute EEG due to left frontocentral focal slowing, left frontocentral semi-periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges and 2 brief focal left frontocentral seizures. These findings are indicative of a structural lesion and an epileptogenic focus in the left frontocentral region.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review. Patient will be placed on continuous EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is a very abnormal awake and drowsy 24 minute EEG due to left frontocentral focal slowing, left frontocentral semi-periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges and 2 brief focal left frontocentral seizures. These findings are indicative of a structural lesion and an epileptogenic focus in the left frontocentral region.  These findings were conveyed to the primary team at the time of the record review. Patient will be placed on continuous EEG monitoring

report:
History:	53 year old woman with a history of seizures.
Medications:	Lorazepam, Dilantin
Sedation:
EEG Type: Continuous (inpt, video}, 24 hrs, portable
Technique: International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 24 hours from 8/28/2014 till 8/29/2014.  Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.  All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
There is right-to-left intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms over the left. The background over the right consists of polymorphic 8 Hz theta posteriorly, weak AP gradient and excess polymorphic theta activity.  There is no PDR or AP gradient over the left. The background over the left consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity with most pronounced delta over the left posterior quadrant.  Excess beta activity appears in the second half of the recording. Sleep spindles are captured. They are better formed over the right.
Continuous variable amplitude complex sharp waves are captured over left parietal region. These discharges frequently occur in brief 1-5 seconds (up to 10 sec} non-evolving runs. No clear electrographic seizures are captured.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild-to-moderate: more so by the end of the recording Beta, excessive, in 2nd half of the recording
Sharp waves, continuous, left parietal, variable amplitude; frequently occurring in 1-5 sec runs No electrographic seizures
Focal slowing, polymorphic, moderate
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 24 hour continuous video EEG due to (1) mild-to-moderate diffuse slowing; (2) focal moderate left hemispheric slowing (especially over the left parietal region} and continuous left parietal epileptiform discharges. There is a highly irritative epileptogenic likely structural focus in the left parietal region. Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific, but in this case is at least partially related to the effect of CNS-active medications due to increase in the degree of slowing as the recording progresses.  No clear clinical or electrographic
seizures are present. These findings were conveyed to the consult team.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL 24 hour continuous video EEG due to (1) mild-to-moderate diffuse slowing; (2) focal moderate left hemispheric slowing (especially over the left parietal region} and continuous left parietal epileptiform discharges. There is a highly irritative epileptogenic likely structural focus in the left parietal region. Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific, but in this case is at least partially related to the effect of CNS-active medications due to increase in the degree of slowing as the recording progresses.  No clear clinical or electrographic
seizures are present. These findings were conveyed to the consult team

dominant rhythm, and bursts of sharply contoured theta and delta

No focal slowing is present.

None

flashes per second (fps) does not produce any EEG changes.

this study.

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:


1. Suboptimal organization

This finding is an etiologically nonspecific indicator of mild

diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

None

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 74-year-old male admitted to the Medicine service recently for episode of loss of consciousness with postictal confusion, cardiac pathology.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Requip, metoprolol, aspirin, Mevacor, Plavix, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a followup EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness was characterized by slow rolling eye movements.
Notable in this record, hyperventilation seems to elicit a somewhat asymmetric hyperventilation response with drop out of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right and a bit of slowing on the left, although there is some movement artifact.  In addition, in drowsiness, the alpha rhythm drops out on the left a little earlier than the right.
Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
Heart rate irregular, 60-80 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing noted on the left, seen in hyperventilation and in the transition to drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are some technical limitations to this record, but the left focal features appear to be genuine.  The irregular heart rate may be a new finding and the patient's outpatient physician will be contacted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing noted on the left, seen in hyperventilation and in the transition to drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 30-year-old woman who had an abrupt, generalized tonic-clonic seizure, falling forward with scalp laceration 4 days ago.  No prior history of epilepsy or epilepsy risk factors, but for the last 6 weeks has been having intermittent myoclonus throughout the day.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is a technically acceptable 20-minute EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Tramadol.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing bursts of rhythmic theta.  There is a single, notched, frontal generalized burst noted in the 1st 2 minutes of hyperventilation, but there are no definitive spike and wave complexes noted in hyperventilation.  As the patient became drowsy following hyperventilation, there is an increase in frontal theta.  The patient waxes and wanes in and out of a drowsy state.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
HEART RATE 72 BPM.
There were some shifting asymmetries noted in the hyperventilation response as well.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although, there is a prominent hyperventilation response with some bursts of slowing, there is 1 suspicious burst, but no definitive spike and wave complexes.  Additional recording may be of value in search of definitive epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within the limits of normal.

report:
History:	31 YR OLD FEMALE PRESENT WITH H/O UNCONTROLLED SZ
Medications:	Keppra and Dilantin. Also received ativan on 09/28/2014 in AM
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 39 hours from 09/27/2014 to 09/29/2014.   Nursing-initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events	0
Description of pushbutton events
Description: Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent. During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric region. No focal slowing is present.  Frequent focal sharp waves are present with phase reversal and amplitude maximum at P3 and large central field. At times they appear rhythmically in runs for up to 15 seconds.  There were 4 seizures during this record. Lasting from 30 to 55 seconds. Thet start with rhythmic left parietal (P3) sharp waves that increase in frequency and amplitude.The field spreads centrally but remain mainly in the central and parietal region.  She may look initially to the left and seconds later she has right with head version while lifting her right arm, her eyes also jerk to the right. She continues this behavior until she suddenly stops.  She does not follow commands during the event. She is post ictally confused for 1-2 minutes.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce any effect.  Hr was 66.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, left parietal
Sharp waves, left parietal
Interpretation: This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of four electrographic seizures arising from the left parietal region.  These findings are indicative of an epileptogenic focus in this sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation: This is an ABNORMAL awake, drowsy, and sleep EEG because of four electrographic seizures arising from the left parietal region.  These findings are indicative of an epileptogenic focus in this sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

report:
MEDICATIONS:  VPA, LEV, PHT
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 32-year-old woman, transferred from outside hospital with repetitive seizures, head turning and persistent left-sided weakness.
INTRODUCTION:  Routine 20 minutes digital EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is primarily unawake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background includes a symmetric reactive 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness includes an increase in background slowing. Deeper stages of sleep were not sustained.
Hyperventilation:  elicits a small amount of theta
Photic stimulation:  vigorous bilateral driving
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep and brief drowsiness.
Generous beta
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual with acute neurological symptoms, this is the baseline for continuous video EEG monitoring. Of note, this is similar (normal) to a one hour EEG performed on May 28, 2015
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep and brief drowsiness. Generous beta

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 67-year-old woman with advanced dementia, failure to thrive, prior refusal to eat, cervical myelopathy, status post fusion, admitted with recurrent seizures characterized by twitching of the mouth and right hand.
MEDICATIONS:  Phenytoin, Vimpat, benzodiazepines, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The recording began several hours after the patient has been treated for recurrent focal seizures with little in the way of a clear change in mental status.
 04/07/2015 to 04/08/2015
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  During the early hours of the record, the background EEG is diffusely slow.  There are intermittent rhythmic bursts of theta noted from the left temporal region, but these do not have clear build up and are not associated with clear change in the patient's level of consciousness.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, the EEG is markedly slow and featureless.
In this section of the record, no clinical seizures were recorded.  Practice push buttons were noted.  The patient had an episode of vocalization without clear clinical correlate.
Heart rate:  90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for:
A markedly slow pattern.
Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change.
Markedly slow background.
04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Vimpat, others.
INTRODUCTION:  During this section of the record, the patient was increasingly arousable and interactive, although essentially nonverbal.  No clinical seizures were noted.
Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult.  Intermittent more rhythmic theta was noted from the left temporal region, but not in sustained bursts. Additional recording on the morning of April 9th demonstrate a patient, who is more awake.  The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm.
Epileptiform activity: None
Clinical seizures none.
Electrographic seizures none.
Sleep record:  Markedly slow pattern with at times, rhythmic theta.
Heart rate:  90 bpm.
Impression:  This 2 day, continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for:
Markedly slow background.
Relatively featureless pattern, lacking in a normal wave forms expected in wakefulness and sleep for an adult of this age.
Bursts of rhythmic theta noted from the left temporal region, most remarkable on the 7th, seen much on the 8th and not present on the 9th.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with recurrent seizures on the morning of the 7th, this EEG shows resolution of a recurrent seizure pattern for this patient with a clinical diagnosis of focal motor status epilepticus.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Day #1, April 7th to 8th:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was remarkable for A markedly slow pattern. Some bursts of rhythmic slowing noted in the initial sections of the record without clinical change. Markedly slow background. 04/08/2015 to 04/09/2015
MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Vimpat, others. INTRODUCTION:  During this section of the record, the patient was increasingly arousable and interactive, although essentially nonverbal.  No clinical seizures were noted. Background:  The overall background is markedly slow, lacking the typical morphologies of wakefulness or sleep for this adult.  Intermittent more rhythmic theta was noted from the left temporal region, but not in sustained bursts. Additional recording on the morning of April 9th demonstrate a patient, who is more awake.  The background EEG remained markedly slow, heart rate 90 bpm. Epileptiform activity: None
Clinical seizures none. Electrographic seizures none. Sleep record:  Markedly slow pattern with at times, rhythmic theta. Heart rate:  90 bpm. Impression:  This 2 day, continuous video EEG monitoring session was remarkable for Markedly slow background. Relatively featureless pattern, lacking in a normal wave forms expected in wakefulness and sleep for an adult of this age. Bursts of rhythmic theta noted from the left temporal region, most remarkable on the 7th, seen much on the 8th and not present on the 9th.

START DATE OF STUDY: 07/05/16 at 18:34

END DATE OF STUDY: 07/06/16



RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: 

EEG TYPE: Long term recording






HISTORY:

This is a 46 y.o. FEMALE PRESENTS WITH H/O SCHIZOPHRENIA, SEIZURE DISORDER, STROKE
3/2014 WITH LT SIDED WEAKNESS. NOW STATES SZ X 3 DAYS AGO WITH LOC AND
POSTICTAL CONFUSION. PT STATES THAT SHE HAS A SZ EVERY THREE DAYS. TODAY HAD
AN EVENT OF UNRESPONSIVENESS WHILE IN THE OFFICE.




Continuous video EEG is initiated for:  Evaluation of paroxysmal events. Differential diagnosis.



Inpatient continuous EEG monitoring required due to one or more of the following reasons:

- The patient is having medically uncontrolled seizures or clinical events, which poses a significant
mortality and morbidity risk.  Continuous monitoring will aid in diagnosis and determining best
treatment options.  If seizures are left untreated, there is a 10-20% annual morbidity and 2% annual
mortality rate.









- Continuous monitoring is required to capture a sufficient number of clinical events or seizures, while
medication are reduced or provoked, which increases the risk of severe seizures and at risk of seizures
causing injury or status epilepticus;


- The EMU is set up to monitor and record EEGs during seizures and it includes nurses trained to
provide first aid and patient safety during seizures;


- The full hospital team must be present to deal with these medical emergency situations should they
arise, including nurses to document patients exam


There have been 13 reported deaths during various video-EEG monitoring procedures, so this is not
a "low risk" service



CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:

A routine 21 channel digital EEG was recorded at the onset of monitoring.  The patient then
underwent continuous CCTV/EEG monitoring using a cable telemetry system.  Scalp electrodes were
placed and secured with collodion according to the 10-20 international electrode system.
Sphenoidal electrodes were not used in this case.  Impedances were measured and verified to be
below 5 Kohms.  EEG activity was recorded referentially to vertex reference, digitized, and stored to
computer hard drive.  Periods of interest were subsequently reformatted to the montage of interest
and reviewed in detail.






Staff supervision, patient-initiated event buttons and computerized algorithms allowed detection of
epileptiform EEG activity and correlation with behavior.  For 24 hours each weekday (and 12-24
hours on weekend) the patient was attended by an EEG technician.  A neurologist was available in
person or on call 24 hours per day.  The patient was monitored via video 24 hours per day by a
registered nurse with special training in seizure recognition and testing.  During times when a
technician was not available, EEG recording, video recording, and computer analysis continued, and
nursing performed seizure testing and electrode maintenance.





The Gotman spike and seizure detection computer program (trademark named "Stellate") was used
to screen the EEG in real time for electrographic seizures and interictal discharges.  Samples of EEG
were recorded periodically.  Detections were reviewed in detail by attending neurologist.  All events
and detections, as well as selected samples, were stored to external hard drive media.




MEDICATIONS:


KEPPRA, KLONOPIN, DOXEPIN, DRONABNOL, RISPERDAL, ATORVO QUONE, PERPHENAZINE


SEDATION: None



DAY 1 (7/05/2016, 18:34 - 7/06/2016, 09:00)



EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient. Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present. No focal slowing is present.

No epileptiform activity is present.

None

produce any EEG changes.

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is a normal awake and asleep only routine EEG. There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.






SUMMARY OF VIDEO EEG FINDINGS:

None





Ictal Findings:

The patient had no clinical events while hooked up to continuous video EEG monitoring in the
epilepsy monitoring unit.




SEIZURE DIAGNOSIS:

1. Possible PNES



CONCLUSION:

 was admitted to the epilepsy monitoring unit for 1 day with continuous video EEG.  This

The patient had a discussion about nonepileptic events and their association with
underlying psychiatric co-morbidities and are not due to abnormal electrical discharges of the

We recommend that he/she to see a psychiatrist or therapist for assessment of underlying

HISTORY:

enhancing cerebral lesions treated as toxoplasmosis, and a seizure 1 year ago, admitted 5/12/2016
for fever and bacteremia, referred for routine EEG for possible seizures.




MEDICATIONS: Flerxeril, Zofran, Prograf, Heparin, Atrovastatin, Keppra, Citalopram, Topamax,
Levothyroxine, Loperamide, Bactrin, Norvasc, Oxycodone



SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically limited record,
with periods of muscle artifact obscuring the bi-temporal chains, rendering interpretation of these
regions suboptimal. The study included a single channel of EKG.




EEG BACKGROUND:





The waking background is continuous, symmetric, reactive, and fairly organized. Waking background
consists of mostly theta with admixed alpha and sharply contoured delta.  Fragments of a symmetric
posterior dominant rhythm ~6-7 Hz are present.




During drowsiness, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and further
background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured.



Moderate generalized slowing is present.

No definite focal slowing is present.



Occasionally frontally predominant generalized rhythmic delta at 1 Hz is seen for runs <7 seconds
(FIRDA [frontally predominant intermittent rhythmic delta activity], also known as frontal GRDA
[generalized rhythmic delta activity]).



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


None


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 66 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal, technically limited as noted above, awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:


1. Moderate generalized slowing and suboptimal organization

2. Occasional frontally predominant generalized rhythmic delta at 1 Hz for runs <7 seconds



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These findings indicate the presence of a moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.




Frontally predominant generalized rhythmic delta activity (GRDA, also known as FIRDA) is a
nonspecific but pathologic finding that is most commonly seen in toxic-metabolic states, but may
also be seen with deep structural lesions or increased intracranial pressure. Clinical correlation is
advised.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal, technically limited as noted above, awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to 

1. Moderate generalized slowing and suboptimal organization

report:
History:	22 year man with history of seizures.
Medications:	None
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is present.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity
is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm
attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL 26-minute EEG, awake and drowsy.  No epileptiform discharges were present,
but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information

report:
HISTORY:

24 y.o. male with a history of motor vehicle accident in 2015 and new onset
seizure in June referred for routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

divalproex (DEPAKOTE) 500 mg EC tablet, Take 500 mg by mouth 3 times daily.

zonisamide (ZONEGRAN) 100 mg capsule, Take 3 capsules by mouth daily for 360 days.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:





A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of 10-11 Hz rhythmic posterior activity,
higher in amplitude on the right, reactive to eye opening and closing. Low amplitude 18-30 Hz
activity was seen with normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude present.




During drowsiness, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse
background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



A moderate amount of irregular medium amplitude 2-5 Hz slowing was seen over right temporal
regions.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

Occasional wicket waves are noted during drowsiness over the right temporal regions



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RHYTHM:

Sinus arrhythmia at 50-60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:



This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:

1. Intermittent irregular right temporal slowing, maximum during drowsiness and sleep.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:



These findings are suggestive of functional disturbance involving the right temporal region without
any definite pathologic paroxysmal epileptiform discharges recorded.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 


This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 
1. Intermittent irregular right temporal slowing, maximum during drowsiness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 43-year-old male with epilepsy, seizures began at age 15, a total of 5-10 seizures in his lifetime. Most recent seizures October 2014. History of alcohol-related neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Neurontin, hydrocodone, mirtazapine, Benadryl, sertraline, lisinopril, simvastatin, hydroxyz pam.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Impedances were below 5 kilo-ohms.  The patient was nervous, had difficulty relaxing with tightening of the jaw and frequent eye movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. There is a small amount of theta and a small amount of background disorganization.  Slightly asynchronous eye movements were noted by the technologist during this study and electrode placement was confirmed, but eye movements remained asynchronous.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of background slowing.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was drifting off to sleep and did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate: 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Very mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to,
Excess theta.
Mild disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a second EEG for this subject without epileptiform activity.  The background theta and disorganization may be related to this patient's medications, history or other causes.  In both studies, the patient had great difficulty relaxing.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Very mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to,
Excess theta. Mild disorganization.

a 52 y.o. female with a history of asthma and seizures since age 31, last seizure 3 wks

topiramate (TOPAMAX) 50 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily. One at bed for two
weeks, then one twice daily


omeprazole (PRILOSEC) 20 mg capsule,

naproxen (NAPROSYN) 500 mg tablet,


loratadine (CLARITIN) 10 mg tablet,

ANTI-DIARRHEAL, LOPERAMIDE, 2 mg tablet,

ferrous sulfate 325 mg (65 mg iron) tablet,


DOC-Q-LACE 100 mg capsule,

VENTOLIN HFA 90 mcg/actuation inhaler,

MAPAP EXTRA STRENGTH 500 mg tablet,




phenytoin (DILANTIN) 100 mg ER capsule, Take 3 capsules by mouth nightly. (Patient taking
differently: Take 300 mg by mouth 4 times daily.)

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
occasional alpha and excess beta frequencies, with occasional fragments of a symmetric and reactive
9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and
amplitude is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.

sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




No generalized slowing is present.

No focal slowing is present.

1. Rare right anterior temporal (F8/T2>T4) spikes

2. Frequent left anterior temporal (T1>F7/T3) sharp-and-wave discharges

None

Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.

symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1-hour EEG due to:


1. Rare right anterior temporal (F8/T2>T4) spikes

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old woman with chronic back pain, paresthesias, and tremor.  Evaluated for seizures.  The patient had an episode where she woke up with soreness of the left side of her tongue.  Past history of fainting spells, thyromegaly, and childhood epilepsy.
INTRODUCTION:  One-hour digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This extended study permitted the patient to become somewhat more drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Abundant mu activity was noted.  Rhythmic midtemporal theta of drowsiness was also noted.  In the transition to sleep, there are multiple different patterns, which were identified.  These included hypnagogic hypersynchrony.  In addition to the rhythmic temporal theta with characteristics of 5 hertz morphology, there is a bit of underlying, irregular slowing noted in the temporal regions.
Additionally, when the technologist allowed the record to run a little longer, there are bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontal delta, and some of these bursts appear to have an underlying 3-5 Hz spike and wave complex, maximum FZCZ with slight asymmetry, spreading to the right.
Heart rate: 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG has multiple normal variants including mu and rhythmic midtemporal theta of drowsiness, but it also has demonstrates the following abnormal findings:
Shifting arrhythmic temporal slowing in drowsiness.
In drowsy bursts, there are subtle 3-5 Hz spike and wave complexes
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings may be correlated with childhood history and imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG has multiple normal variants including mu and rhythmic midtemporal theta of drowsiness, but it also has demonstrates the following abnormal findings Shifting arrhythmic temporal slowing in drowsiness. In drowsy bursts, there are subtle 3-5 Hz spike and wave complexes

Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, comatose
Description:
Patient is sedated as the recording opens.  The background is symmetrical and consists of a mixture
of polymorphic frequencies (delta, theta, alpha and beta).  Occasionally the background becomes
discontinuous or frankly burst-suppressed.  These changes are related to adjustments in anesthesia.
Left internal carotid artery is clamped at 6:55 pm and left common carotid artery is clamped ~ 25-
30 seconds later.  Within ~ 15-20 seconds of clamping the left common carotid artery, diffuse
change is seen.  It is more pronounced over the left.  This change is characterized by voltage
attenuation as well as abrupt disappearance of fast frequencies.  The attending surgeon is notified
of these changes immediately and shunt placement takes place.  Simultaneously, there is increase
in the dose of  sevoflurane and prominent diffuse delta activity appears as a result.  The primary
team is informed of these changes.  EEG returns to the pre-clamp baseline b ~ 7:06 PM.  Left
carotid artery is re-clamped at ~ 8:48 PM and EEG changes within ~ 5 seconds.  This change is
characterized by diffuse (left>right) voltage attenuation and dominance of delta activity.  EEG
change persists until ~ 8;55 PM when left internal and common carotid arteries are unclamped.
EEG gradually returns to the pre-clamp baseline.
Summary of Findings:
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL ~4 hour continuous intraoperative EEG due to global (left>right) changes
that were seen after clamp was applied to the left common and internal carotid arteries. However,
by the end of the recording, EEG appeared symmetrical and at pre-clamp baseline.  Total time of
the direct EEG monitoring by the EEG attending: ~ 2 hours.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL ~4 hour continuous intraoperative EEG due to global (left>right) changes
that were seen after clamp was applied to the left common and internal carotid arteries. However,
by the end of the recording, EEG appeared symmetrical and at pre-clamp baseline.  Total time of
the direct EEG monitoring by the EEG attending: ~ 2 hours

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 22-year-old woman, status post delivery of an infant 8 days ago with epidural anesthesia.  Two days ago, she developed a headache of increase in severity.  Possible seizure earlier this morning.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproate, Fioricet, morphine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This was a technically challenging bedside record in an uncomfortable individual with a hair weave.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow with primarily a theta frequency pattern and a glimpse of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  Shifting slowing was noted.  Bursts of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing were noted as the patient becomes drowsy.
There is a brief section where the patient appears to transition briefly to stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and then an arousal.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are nonspecific, but support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  Although this is a sharply contoured record, there are no definitive epileptiform discharges.  These findings should be incorporated into this patient's current clinical scenario.
__________________________
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Marked background slowing. FIRDA.

A posterior dominant rhythm at best reached 8Hz.  Background activity was characterized by disorganized diffuse theta activity with absence of the expected anterior to posterior gradient of frequencies.  Intermittently normal fronto-central beta can be seen.  At times frontally maximal sharp waves with triphasic morphology are present throughout the recording. Frequent brief (2-5 second) bursts of 100-200uV, 2- 4Hz rhythmic bifrontal slow waves occur throughout the recording, increasing in frequency during drowsiness. Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, continuous, mild diffuse
FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity), frequent
Triphasic waves, occasional

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old male with single seizure in January, perhaps reactive.  Patient subsequently received tramadol for a fracture and had a tonic-clonic seizure.  The patient was started on carbamazepine and since then, complains of feeling spacey.
INTRODUCTION:  One-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient has received levetiracetam 1000 mg during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the background EEG is diffusely slow with an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm, but with excess beta and bursts of theta.  Bursts of frontally predominant spike and wave activity are noted.  In addition, isolated right or left frontal spike and wave discharges are noted.  Some of these demonstrate a prominence in the right hemisphere.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record and clearly accentuates frontally predominant spike and wave activity.  The spike and wave activity ranges from 3 to 5 hertz in frequency.   Discharges are not sustained with most spike and wave complexes either isolated or occurring in bursts, less than 1.5 seconds duration.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep.  This spike and wave discharges did not seem to be augmented by the photic stimulation, but as the patient transitions to sleep, there was a higher amplitude, frontally predominant slowing with a bit more slow spike and wave activity.  Levetiracetam was given at approximately 12 p.m. and the EEG was recorded until 12:41.  Following the levetiracetam, by 12:30, there did appear to be a decrease in the spike and wave activity.  The paroxysmal slowing was a little less remarkable and while the EEG remained abnormal with excess theta, the overall pattern was improving.  The alpha rhythm was at 8.3 hertz at conclusion.
Heart rate, slightly irregular at 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record.
Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity.
Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG may represent a focal or a secondary generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  There was a small degree of irregularity in the heart rate noted in the final pages of the EEG, which may be evaluated by different mechanisms.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Initially markedly abnormal background with excess slowing and disorganized pattern, improving towards the close of the record. Frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity. Focal spike and slow wave activity with a predominance further on the right.

report:
History: 59 year old woman with a reported first convulsion several days ago.
Medications:	Ativan, Ambien, Zoloft
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of 10.5-11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye
opening.  There is an expected AP gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.
Diffuse excess beta activity is captured.  Symmetrical sleep architecture consisting of vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes is captured in the second half of the recording.
Multiple events concerning for focal electrographic seizures are captured in the first half of the
recording.  Clinically, patient has not complaints and able to answer questions correctly, including
able to count during these events.  They last ~ 35-55 seconds.  The onset is not clearly lateralized
for the majority of the events.  They start with P3/P4 broad moderate amplitude sharp waves that
gradually increase in frequency up to 6 Hz and spread to the left posterior temporal region
(example ~12:17 PM).  Some events start with ~ 4 Hz medium amplitude rhythmic right parietal
activity that gradually spreads to the left parietal and left temporal regions (example ~12:35:50 pm).
After hyperventilation, brief bursts (<10 sec) of non-evolving shifting bilateral
posterior 5-6 Hz rhythmic moderate amplitude delta activity are captured.  Once P3 and P4 leads
are exchanged at ~12:46:55 PM, the above activity is no longer present.  A single clear right
posterior temporal sharp wave with aftergoing slow wave is captured early in the recording.
Maximal scalp negativity occurs over the T6 lead.  Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds
with good cooperation, and results in increase of bilateral parietal rhythmic delta activity.  Stepped
photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple
Summary of Findings:
Beta, excessive
Sharp waves, one, right temporal, posterior
Sleep, stage 2
Seizure, frequent, bilateral parietal, 35-55 seconds
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 48 minute awake and asleep EEG due to presence of multiple suspected
bilateral parietal focal brief (35-55 sec) seizures/ ictal runs.  Of note, these runs disappeared once
P3 and P4 electrodes were exchanged but patient also fell asleep.  Additionally, a single clear
right posterior temporal epileptiform discharge is present.  These findings suggest structural focal
cerebral abnormality over the bilateral parietal, right temporal region.  Since It is possible that
activity seen was artifactual (it disappeared after leads were exchanged), a repeat prolonged EEG
may be of benefit.  These findings were discussed with the ordering physician.  Excessive beta
activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.

report:

in the last 3 weeks.
Medications:	Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 9.5-10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow
waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple lash rates.  There is frequent eye flutter artifact.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Artifact, other, eye flutter
No epileptiform discharges

but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may
provide additional information. There is frequent eye flutter artifact, so subtle anterior
abnormalities might have been missed.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does
not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: A 22-year-old male, transferred from prison to an outside hospital with multiple recurrent seizures. History of childhood epilepsy, asthma, schizophrenia, no known structural abnormalities on MRI.
MEDICATIONS:   Depakote, Keppra, Ativan, Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient was relatively somnolent. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern with rhythmic theta and delta.  Spontaneous eye opening and movements are noted, as is some chewing artifact.  In this diffusely slow record, there is some bursts of shifting slowing and subtle asymmetry characterized by somewhat lower voltage pattern on the right with a bit more arrhythmic delta activity and a bit more theta on the left. Stimulation of the patient produces a bit more theta as well as eye opening.
Heart rate 80 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified. Overall background described above is typical of a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, notable for this individual elevated serum ammonia. If additional information is needed, either a repeat study or a long-term EEG monitoring may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Shifting slowing.

Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, obtunded
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 15 hours from 12/16/2015 to 12/17/2015.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.   Ongoing raw EEG data was
reviewed at least twice daily by the attending neurologist for detection of seizures and changes in
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
No posterior dominant rhythm was present.  Background activity was characterized by diffuse low
voltage delta activity with absence of the expected anterior to posterior gradient of frequencies.
There is a frontal predominant but mainly diffuse intermixed beta discharge seen during the entire
study.  During the last hours of the study the patient is stimulated. The EEG appears reactive with a
transient change in the background to a diffuse theta.  No normal sleep architecture was present.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  The patient had multiple
events of sudden arm stiffening and arm trembling with eyes closed for 1-5 seconds with no EEG
correlate. These are consistent with psychogenic non-epileptic seizures (PNES).
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  HR was 48
Summary of Findings:
Event, intermittent, pseudoseizures
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, continuous
Excessive fast
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG because of multiple episodes of arm stiffening and shaking with no
EEG correlate consistent with PNES. In addition there is diffuse background slowing.  This finding
is an etiologically nonspecific indicator of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  The diffuse beta
discharge may be indicative of a medication effect.  No clinical or electrographic seizures are present.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG because of multiple episodes of arm stiffening and shaking with no
EEG correlate consistent with PNES. In addition there is diffuse background slowing.  This finding
is an etiologically nonspecific indicator of moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  The diffuse beta
discharge may be indicative of a medication effect.  No clinical or electrographic seizures are present

diffuse bihemispheric theta (5-6Hz) slowing intermittently throughout the recording even when the
patient is awake.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal beta
activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During brief stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to vertex 2-4Hz activity.
There is subtle left frontal and temporal predominance of the background slowing.  No epileptiform
discharges are present.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, bilateral diffuse
Focal slowing, polymorphic, intermittent, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep due to diffuse bihemispheric slowing and
focal left frontotemporal slowing. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and possible left sided structural brain injury.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL EEG, awake, drowsy, and asleep due to diffuse bihemispheric slowing and
focal left frontotemporal slowing. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and possible left sided structural brain injury

report:
History:	30 year old woman with new onset of events concerning for seizures.
Medications:	Trileptal in am only and then stopped
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep
Continuous bedside video-EEG monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for ~24 hours from 11/2/2015 till 11/3/2015.   Nursing-
initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior. Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed
at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All
automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During drowsiness, the background
slows to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm
attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate
voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.  Two typical events are
captured early in the recording (~11:47 AM and 12:07 PM).  They are characterized by decreased
responsiveness, eye closure, no recollection of the event, not following commands and being
emotional at the end of the event.  They last several minutes. The background remains normal
throughout the events and following the events.
Summary of Findings:
Event, two, no EEG correlate
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is a NORMAL ~24-hour continuous video EEG. Two events characterized by decreased
responsiveness, not answering commands and post-event emotional liability have no abnormal
EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a NORMAL ~24-hour continuous video EEG. Two events characterized by decreased
responsiveness, not answering commands and post-event emotional liability have no abnormal
EEG correlate

Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates 
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over 
bilateral frontal regions.  Mild degree of excess polymorphic theta activity is captured.  Patient 
remains awake throughout the study.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.

symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) 
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.

	Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
	No epileptiform discharges
	No stage 2 sleep

This is a mildly abnormal awake-only 21-minute EEG due to mild diffuse slowing and 
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral 
dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If 
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.

Indications: GENERALIZED ANXIETY DISORDER levetiracetam (KEPPRA) 500 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth every 12 hours for 30 days. Indications: seizure disorder hydroxyzine hcl (ATARAX) 50 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth at bedtime for 30 days. Indications: ANXIETY TECHNIQUE: A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.  EEG BACKGROUND: The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 8.5-9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening. There is a small amount of background disorganization noted.  Lambda was present During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.  Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with POSTS synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured. No major generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.   EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: No epileptiform activity is present.  OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:        Hyperventilation: Produces a small amount of slowing       Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.   EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  HEART RATE: A heart rate of 50 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  IMPRESSION: This is a very mildly abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or detected. 1.  Mild excess theta and disorganization CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were noted.  The findings described above can be related to the patient's underlying illness or medications.  This routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
HISTORY:

21 y.o. male p/w history of seizure since the age of 12. Admitted to TUH
after having a total of 12 SZ this week.


PMH: Schizophrenia, BPD

Hx of drug abuse: Cocaine, Heroin, Marijuana, K2



MEDICATIONS:

Current Facility-Administered Medications:


busPIRone (BUSPAR) tablet 10 mg

levETIRAcetam (KEPPRA) tablet 500 mg

sodium chloride 0.9 % injection (flush) 10 mL


LORazepam (ATIVAN) injection 2 mg

enoxaparin (LOVENOX) injection 40 mg

valproic acid (DEPAKENE) capsule 500 mg



SEDATION: None




TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.



EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


Posterior slow waves of youth are seen.


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of  90 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake only routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or
detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:




This is a normal awake only  routine EEG.

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake only routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events reported or
detected.

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 05/12/16

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, drowsy and asleep



HISTORY:

a 34 y.o. male with a history of possible diabetes, possible alcoholic hepatitis,
recent three-minute tonic-clonic seizure one month ago referred for routine EEG for characterization
of seizures.




MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

amLODIPine (NORVASC) 10 mg tablet, Take 10 mg by mouth daily.


SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically challenging
record and included a single channel of EKG, HV and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:








The waking background is very low voltage, but symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of
alpha and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior
gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant
rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.  There is generous low-voltage
beta.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.  Different electrode artifact is noted in
sleep




Sleep is characterized by spike in vertex waves, spindles and posts



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Elicits an increase in theta

Photic Stimulation: Patient is falling asleep but there is a brief driving response



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 96 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a technically challenging low-voltage but otherwise normal EEG.  There are no clinical or
electrographic events reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


The low-voltage pattern is a nonspecific finding.  The excessive drowsiness may be due to sleep
deprivation.  Given the artifacts, , please consider a more prolonged study or at least a repeat study

A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a technically challenging low-voltage but otherwise normal EEG.  There are no clinical or
electrographic events reported or detected.
